  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1: '
      title: 
      number: 1
      content: 'To Theophilus, [[COMMENT(0)]] the lover of God.I write to you again,
        my dear friend, to give you further details   about the life of our Lord
        Jesus and all the things that he did and taught. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:1
        content: "  Some scholars believe that Theophilus could be a symbolic name
          and not necessarily one individual. This is most likely not written to
          one individual. When the meaning of his name is translated, the sentence
          reads, \u201CI wrote to you before, O&nbsp;lover of God.\u201D Both Luke
          and Acts were written to every lover of God.      This account was written
          by Luke, the human author of the Gospel of Luke. The title Lord Jesus is
          found only in the Aramaic. The Greek is simply \u201CJesus.\u201D     
          Although Jesus\u2019 work of redemption has been completed for us, there
          is still the unfinished work of preparing and beautifying his eternal partner,
          the bride of Christ. With gifts of power Jesus\u2019 church is continuing
          what he began to do and teach through evangelism and discipleship. See 
          ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Just before he ascended into heaven, Jesus left instructions [[COMMENT(0)]]
        through the Holy Spirit for the apostles he had chosen. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:2
        content: "  Or \u201Ccommands.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "After the sufferings of his cross, Jesus appeared alive many times 
        [[COMMENT(0)]] to these same apostles over a forty-day period,  proving to
        them with many convincing signs that he had been resurrected.  During these
        encounters, he taught them the truths of God\u2019s kingdom. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:3
        content: "  Jesus appeared to his followers at least eleven times and taught
          them the mysteries of God\u2019s kingdom realm. See also  .      The number
          forty is significant, for it speaks of transformation and completeness
          through testing. Jesus was tempted for forty days, the deluge during Noah\u2019s
          day lasted forty days and nights, Moses met with God for forty days on
          Sinai, Israel wandered for forty years, and Elijah fasted for forty days.
          Jesus spent forty days appearing to his disciples to teach them that a
          day of completeness and transformation had arrived. It took them forty
          days to comprehend that Christ\u2019s kingdom was spiritual, not political.     
          The world is still waiting to see \u201Cmany convincing signs\u201D from
          our lives signifying that we too have been raised from the dead. Spiritual
          fruit and spiritual power provide these signs.      The Aramaic adds, \u201Cand
          shared meals with them.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Jesus instructed them, <JESUS>\u201CDon\u2019t leave Jerusalem, but
        wait here until you receive the gift I told you about, the gift the Father
        has promised.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "<JESUS>For John baptized you in water, but in a few days from now
        you will be baptized in the Holy Spirit!\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: "  The Aramaic implies that they would be the ones who would do
          the baptizing: \u201CJohn baptized you in water, but you will baptize [others]
          in the Holy Spirit.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Every time they were gathered together, they asked Jesus, \u201CLord,
        is it now the time for you to free Israel and restore our kingdom?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "He answered, <JESUS>\u201CThe Father is the one who sets the fixed
        dates and the times of their fulfillment. You are not permitted to know the
        timing of all that he has prepared by his own authority.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "<JESUS>But I promise you this\u2014the Holy Spirit will come upon
        you, and you will be seized with power.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>You
        will be my messengers</JESUS>    <JESUS>to Jerusalem, throughout Judea, the
        distant provinces</JESUS>  <JESUS>\u2014even to the remotest places on earth!\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:8
        content: "  Or \u201CYou will seize power.\u201D      Or \u201Cwitnesses.\u201D
          The Greek word can also be translated \u201Cmartyrs.\u201D      Or \u201CSamaria,\u201D
          a term used for a distant province populated by another people group.     
          See  .    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Right after Jesus spoke those words, the disciples saw him being
        lifted into the sky, and disappearing into a cloud! [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:9
        content: "  Or \u201CA cloud came under him and took him up from their sight.\u201D
          The Aramaic is \u201CA cloud accepted him and covered him from their eyes.\u201D
          He did not start from a cloud and ascend to outer space. He started from
          their visible presence, and disappeared from view in a cloud, ascending
          by that means into heaven. And when he returns, it will be in reverse order.
          We will see him appearing from out of a cloud, then descending back into
          our visible presence where we can see him and be forever with him.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'As they stared into the sky, watching Jesus ascend, two men in white
        robes suddenly appeared beside them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: A New Apostle Is Chosen'
      title: A New Apostle Is Chosen
      number: 11
      content: "They told the startled disciples, \u201CGalileans, why are you staring
        up into the sky? Jesus has been taken from you into heaven, but he will come
        back in the same way that you saw him ascend.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The disciples left the Mount of Olives and returned to Jerusalem,
        which was less than a mile away. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:12
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cseven stadia\u201D (furlongs). A furlong
          is about one-eighth of a mile. The Greek uses a phrase not found in the
          Septuagint or elsewhere in the Greek New Testament or in any Greek literature:
          \u201Cof a Sabbath having away.\u201D It is rendered in most modern translations
          \u201Ca Sabbath\u2019s journey.\u201D    "
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "Arriving there, they went into a large second-floor room to pray.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Those present were Peter, John, Jacob, Andrew, Philip, Thomas,
        Bartholomew, Matthew, Jacob (the son of Alpheus), Simon (the zealot), Judas
        (the son of Jacob), and a number of women, including Mary, Jesus\u2019 mother.
        His brothers  were there as well. All of them were united in prayer, gripped
        with one passion,  interceding night and day."
      comments:
      - number: "1:13\u201314"
        content: "  The Greek uses the definite article \u201Cthe upstairs room.\u201D
          This was where they had met before to have the Last Supper with Jesus.
          In Mark\u2019s Gospel, after the disciples returned from witnessing the
          ascension, they preached, for Mark is the Gospel of ministry. In Luke,
          after Jesus\u2019 ascension, they praised, and here in Acts they prayed.     
          Or \u201Csiblings.\u201D Jesus\u2019 four brothers are named in    and   
          as Jacob, Joses (or Joseph), Simon, and Judah. Even though    records that
          early in Jesus\u2019 ministry his own brothers did not believe in him,
          they obviously later repented and received the revelation of the resurrected
          Christ, their own brother, and believed in him.      The Aramaic is \u201CThey
          prayed with one soul.\u201D    "
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "Arriving there, they went into a large second-floor room to pray.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Those present were Peter, John, Jacob, Andrew, Philip, Thomas,
        Bartholomew, Matthew, Jacob (the son of Alpheus), Simon (the zealot), Judas
        (the son of Jacob), and a number of women, including Mary, Jesus\u2019 mother.
        His brothers  were there as well. All of them were united in prayer, gripped
        with one passion,  interceding night and day."
      comments:
      - number: "1:13\u201314"
        content: "  The Greek uses the definite article \u201Cthe upstairs room.\u201D
          This was where they had met before to have the Last Supper with Jesus.
          In Mark\u2019s Gospel, after the disciples returned from witnessing the
          ascension, they preached, for Mark is the Gospel of ministry. In Luke,
          after Jesus\u2019 ascension, they praised, and here in Acts they prayed.     
          Or \u201Csiblings.\u201D Jesus\u2019 four brothers are named in    and   
          as Jacob, Joses (or Joseph), Simon, and Judah. Even though    records that
          early in Jesus\u2019 ministry his own brothers did not believe in him,
          they obviously later repented and received the revelation of the resurrected
          Christ, their own brother, and believed in him.      The Aramaic is \u201CThey
          prayed with one soul.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'During this time Peter stood up among the 120 believers who were
        gathered and said, '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CFellow believers, [[COMMENT(0)]] the Scripture David prophesied
        by the Holy Spirit concerning Judas had to be fulfilled.  Judas betrayed
        our Lord Jesus and led the mob to the garden to arrest him. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cbrothers.\u201D      That is, replacing Judas with another
          to complete the Twelve. See v.  .    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'He was one of us, and he was chosen to be an apostle just as we were.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:17
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'He earned the wages of his sin, [[COMMENT(0)]] for he fell headfirst,
        and his belly split open, spilling his intestines on the ground. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:18
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CHe acquired
          a field with the reward of his wickedness.\u201D Judas would have had no
          time between his betrayal and his suicide to purchase land. This plot of
          land was likely purchased by the Jewish authorities. They could not use
          the returned blood money for temple purposes, so instead they purchased
          a small burial plot for Judas.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Everyone in Jerusalem knows what happened to him. That\u2019s why
        the field where he died is called in Aramaic [[COMMENT(0)]] \u2018Haqel Dama,\u2019
        that is, \u2018The Bloody Field.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 1:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cin the language of the region.\u201D The Greek text
          is clear that the Jews of Jesus\u2019 day spoke Aramaic, the language that
          Jesus and his apostles taught in. The Greek text transliterates the name
          of the field into a Greek equivalent for a Greek audience.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "For it is written in the Psalms:\u2018Let his house be deserted and
        become a wasteland.No one will live there.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]And also:\u2018Let
        another take his ministry.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 1:20
        content: '  See  .      See  .    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CSo then, we must choose his replacement from among those who
        have been with us from the very beginning, [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cthat our Lord Jesus went in and out among us.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "from John\u2019s baptism until Jesus\u2019 ascension. And, like us,
        he must be a witness of his resurrection.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "They proposed two candidates: Joseph, who is also called Barsabbas
        the Just, and Matthias. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>.\u201D</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:23
        content: "  Barsabbas means \u201Cson of promise.\u201D Matthias means \u201Cgift
          of      "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "They all prayed, \u201CLord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        you know the heart of every man.  Please give us clear revelation to know
        which of these two men you have chosen "
      comments:
      - number: 1:24
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is simply \u201CLord.\u201D     
          The Greek is \u201CLord, you are the heart knower of all.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "to be an apostle and take Judas\u2019 place because he renounced
        his apostleship to go where he belonged.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:25
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cgo to his place.\u201D The Greek is \u201Cdeparted
          from this life,\u201D a euphemism for death.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "They cast lots [[COMMENT(0)]] and determined that Matthias was the
        Lord\u2019s choice, so he was added to the eleven apostles."
      comments:
      - number: 1:26
        content: "  This was similar to rolling dice. Casting lots is not mentioned
          again in the New Testament after the Holy Spirit was poured out. The Aramaic
          reads \u201CThey raised up a shaking-free and elevated Matthias,\u201D
          which indicates they shook free from Judas\u2019 claim to apostleship and
          appointed Matthias.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Holy Spirit Comes at Pentecost'
      title: The Holy Spirit Comes at Pentecost
      number: 1
      content: 'On the day Pentecost was being fulfilled, [[COMMENT(0)]] all the
        disciples were gathered in one place. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:1
        content: "  Or \u201Ccame to be fulfilled.\u201D The Greek word means \u201Cto
          fill completely (to be fulfilled).\u201D Pentecost was one of the main
          feasts of Israel. The name is derived from  , which means \u201Cfiftieth,\u201D
          since it was held on the fiftieth day after the Passover Sabbath. It was
          also known as the Feast of Harvest.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Suddenly they heard the sound of a violent blast of wind [[COMMENT(0)]]
        rushing into the house  from out of the heavenly realm. The roar of the wind
        was so overpowering it was all anyone could bear! '
      comments:
      - number: 2:2
        content: "  The Aramaic can also be translated \u201Clike the roar of a groaning
          spirit.\u201D This mighty wind is for power; the breath of Jesus breathed
          into his disciples in    was for life.      Or \u201CIt filled the house.\u201D
          Tradition says they were gathered in an upper room; however, it is more
          likely that it was the House of the Lord (the temple), where they all gathered
          to celebrate Pentecost. See also  .    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Then all at once a pillar of fire appeared before their eyes. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        It separated into tongues of fire that engulfed  each one of them. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:3
        content: "  This was the pillar of fire that led Israel from bondage into
          the promised land. The same pillar of fire manifested here to initiate
          a new beginning from dead religious structures into the powerful life of
          the Spirit. Each believer received an overpowering flame of fire, signified
          by the shaft of light that engulfed them. It was as though each one received
          his own personal pillar of fire that would empower him and lead him throughout
          his life. This was the promise Jesus gave to his disciples of \u201Cthe
          one like me\u201D (), who would be sent by the Father and never leave them.
          Today every believer is indwelt by the Spirit of Christ (). This was the
          birthday of the church of Jesus Christ.      Or \u201Crested over them.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "They were all filled and equipped [[COMMENT(0)]] with the Holy Spirit
        and were inspired  to speak in tongues\u2014empowered by the Spirit to speak
        in languages they had never learned!"
      comments:
      - number: 2:4
        content: "  There are two Greek words used here for \u201Cfilled.\u201D In
          v.  , it is  , which means \u201Cfilled inwardly.\u201D In v.    it is 
          , which means \u201Cfilled outwardly\u201D or \u201Cfurnished and equipped.\u201D
          This was the anointing of the Spirit for ministry. Every believer needs
          the filling of the Spirit both inwardly for life and outwardly for ministry.     
          The Greek word    literally means \u201Cto ring out\u201D (like a bell).
          It can also mean \u201Ccarried along\u201D or \u201Cinspired.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Now, at that time there were Jewish worshipers [[COMMENT(0)]] who
        had emigrated from many different lands to live in Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cdevout Jewish men.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'When the people [[COMMENT(0)]] of the city heard the roaring sound,
        crowds came running to where it was coming from, stunned over what was happening,
        because each one could hear the disciples speaking in his or her own language. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:6
        content: "  The Greek word    implies respect, such as \u201Cladies and gentlemen.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Bewildered, they said to one another, \u201CAren\u2019t these all
        Galileans? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:7
        content: '  It is likely they knew they were Galileans by their Aramaic dialect
          common in Galilee.    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So how is it that we hear them speaking in our own languages? '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'We are northeastern Iranians, [[COMMENT(0)]] northwestern Iranians, 
        Elamites,  and those from Mesopotamia,  Judea, east central Turkey,  the
        coastal areas of the Black Sea,  Asia,   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:9
        content: "  Or \u201CParthians.\u201D      Or \u201CMedes.\u201D      This
          area is now Khuzestan and the Ilam Province, including a small part of
          southern Iraq.      The Aramaic is Beth-Nahrin, which means \u201Cland
          of the rivers.\u201D This would include Iraq, parts of Syria, southeastern
          Turkey, and southwestern Iran. The Assyrians also consider themselves to
          be natives of Beth-Nahrin (Mesopotamia).      Or \u201CCappadocia.\u201D     
          Or \u201CPontus,\u201D which is northeastern Turkey. Pontus means \u201Csea.\u201D     
          Or \u201COrientals.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'north central Turkey, [[COMMENT(0)]] southern Turkey, Egypt, Libyans
        who are neighbors of Cyrene, visitors from all over the Roman Empire, both
        Jews and converts to Judaism, Cretans and Arabs. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:10
        content: "  Or \u201CPhrygia.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Yet we hear them speaking of God\u2019s mighty wonders in our own
        dialects!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:11
        content: '  This is the universal remedy of the curse of Babel, where human
          beings were divided by languages (). Now, in Christ, the language of the
          Spirit unifies us all in him.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "They all stood there, dumbfounded and astonished, saying to one another,
        \u201CWhat is this phenomenon?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:12
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: "13: Peter\u2019s Pentecost Sermon"
      title: "Peter\u2019s Pentecost Sermon"
      number: 13
      content: "But others poked fun at them and said, \u201CThey\u2019re just drunk
        on new wine.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Peter stood up with the eleven apostles [[COMMENT(0)]] and shouted 
        to the crowd. \u201CListen carefully, my fellow Jews  and residents of Jerusalem.
        You need to clearly understand what\u2019s happening here. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:14
        content: "  All of the twelve standing there would prove that they were not
          drunk. They stood before this massive crowd, possibly in the courts of
          the temple. There were three thousand converted and baptized that day,
          so the crowd was possibly much larger than that.      See footnote for
          v.  . Peter was speaking under the anointing of the Holy Spirit. The tongues
          being spoken, along with the sound of the wind, drew the crowd. Peter would
          have spoken to them in the common language of Aramaic. Even with the Galilean
          and Judean dialects, nearly all of the Jewish people present would understand
          his words.      Or \u201Cyou Jewish men.\u201D This is also used in  ; 
          ;  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "These people are not drunk like you think they are, for it is only
        nine o\u2019clock in the morning. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe third hour,\u201D the time for Jewish morning prayer.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'This is the fulfillment of what was prophesied through the prophet
        Joel, for God says: [[COMMENT(0)]]'
      comments:
      - number: 2:16
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u2018This is what I will do in the last days [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014I
        will pour out  my Spirit on everybody and cause your sons and daughters to
        prophesy, and your young men will see visions,  and your old men will experience
        dreams from God.   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:17
        content: "  The New Testament term \u201Cthe last days\u201D began at Pentecost
          and extends until the return of Christ. We have technically been in \u201Cthe
          last days\u201D for over two thousand years.      Or \u201Cgush forth,\u201D
          or \u201Crun greedily.\u201D The Aramaic can be translated \u201CI will
          be splashing my Spirit-Wind over all flesh\u201D (humanity).      Or \u201Cdivinely
          appointed appearances.\u201D The Greek word for \u201Cvisions,\u201D  ,
          can also mean \u201Cour eyes opened to have divine encounters and see into
          the spiritual realm.\u201D These are not daydreams but visions of the heavenly
          realm. (See  , Gr. 3700 and 3706.)      This verse can be translated from
          the Aramaic as \u201CYour grandparents shall see visions and your priests
          shall dream dreams.\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'The Holy Spirit will come upon all my servants, men and women alike,
        and they will prophesy. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'I will reveal startling signs and wonders in the sky above and mighty
        miracles on the earth below. Blood and fire and pillars of clouds [[COMMENT(0)]]
        will appear. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:19
        content: "  Or \u201Ccolumns [plumes] of smoke.\u201D The Aramaic can be
          translated \u201Cthe sweet smell of burning incense.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'For the sun will be turned dark [[COMMENT(0)]] and the moon blood-red
        before that great and awesome appearance of the day of the Lord. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:20
        content: "  This could be a figure of speech similar to \u201CLights out
          on the old order.\u201D The Aramaic is \u201CThe sun will be in mourning.\u201D
          Perhaps this prophecy was fulfilled when Christ was crucified.    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "But everyone who calls on the name of the Lord [[COMMENT(0)]] will
        be saved.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 2:21
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CWhoever calls on the name
          of Jesus as the Messiah will receive life.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Peter continued, \u201CPeople of Israel, listen to the facts. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Jesus, the Victorious,  was a man on a divine mission  whose authority was
        clearly proven. For you know how God performed many powerful miracles, signs,
        and wonders through him. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:22
        content: "  Peter wisely begins his sermon with a recounting of Jewish history,
          keeping the main point of his sermon until the end. A great transformation
          had taken place in Peter, who had denied Christ three times only six weeks
          ago. Now he preaches with power and authority. This is the difference the
          Holy Spirit makes in the life of a believer.      Or \u201CJesus the Nazarene\u201D
          (the Branch). The Aramaic word used here also implies the title of an heir
          of a powerful family, or one who is victorious (\u201CJesus, the Victorious\u201D).     
          The Aramaic is \u201Cthe man from God,\u201D which may be an idiomatic
          saying for \u201Cthe man born of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "This Man\u2019s destiny was prearranged, for God knew that Jesus
        would be handed over to you to be crucified and that you would execute him
        on a cross by the hands of lawless men. Yet it was all part of his predetermined
        plan. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "God destroyed the cords of death [[COMMENT(0)]] and raised him up,
        because it was impossible for death\u2019s power to hold him prisoner. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:24
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic, which can also be translated
          \u201CGod destroyed death\u2019s destruction.\u201D The Greek is \u201CGod
          freed him from the travails of death.\u201D The Greek word translated \u201Ctravails\u201D
          is commonly used for the labor pains of childbirth.    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "This is the very thing David prophesied about him: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2018I
        continually see the Lord <smallcaps>.</smallcaps> in front of me.He\u2019s
        at my right hand, and I am never shaken. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:25
        content: "  See  .      The Hebrew-Aramaic word is        As translated from
          the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cso that I will not be shaken.\u201D    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'No wonder my heart is glad and my glory celebrates! [[COMMENT(0)]]My
        mouth is filled with his praises,and I have hope that my body will live '
      comments:
      - number: 2:26
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic.      The Greek word for \u201Clive\u201D
          () is always used for \u201Cpitch a tent.\u201D Or \u201CMy body will pitch
          its tent in hope (expectation).\u201D The Aramaic is \u201CEven my body
          he will restore to hope.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: because you will not leave my soul among the dead, [[COMMENT(0)]]nor
        will you allow your sacred one to experience decay.
      comments:
      - number: 2:27
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CSheol\u201D; the Greek is \u201CHades.\u201D
          Both refer to the realm of death.    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "For you have revealed to me the pathways to life,and seeing your
        face fills me with euphoria!\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:28
        content: "  This Greek word () occurs only here and in  . It is the spirit
          of joy, an ecstasy that comes from God. The Aramaic is \u201CYou will fill
          me, O&nbsp;Sweetness, with your presence.\u201D    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CMy fellow Jews, I can tell you there is no doubt that our noted
        patriarch has both died and been buried in his tomb, which remains to this
        day. So you can see that he was not referring to himself with those words. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "But as a prophet, he knew God\u2019s faithful promise, made with
        God\u2019s unbreakable oath, that one of his descendants would take his throne.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:30
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "So when peering into the future, David prophesied [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of the Messiah\u2019s resurrection. And God revealed to him that the Messiah
        would not be abandoned to the realm of death, nor would his body experience
        decay."
      comments:
      - number: 2:31
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CDavid rose up after seeing
          a vision and he saw.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "\u201CCan\u2019t you see it? God has resurrected Jesus, and we all
        have seen him! [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:32
        content: "  Or \u201Cof whom we are witnesses,\u201D which implies that they
          all had seen the resurrected Jesus.    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "\u201CThen God exalted him to his right hand upon the throne of highest
        honor. And the Father gave him the authority to send the promised Holy Spirit,
        which is being poured out [[COMMENT(0)]] upon us today. This is what you\u2019re
        seeing and hearing!"
      comments:
      - number: 2:33
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Csplashed out the gift of the Holy Spirit.\u201D    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CDavid wasn\u2019t the one who ascended into heaven, but the
        one who prophesied:\u2018<smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  [[COMMENT(0)]] said
        to my Lord,I honor you by enthroning you beside me, "
      comments:
      - number: 2:34
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic.      Or \u201Cat my right hand.\u201D    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "until I make your enemiesa footstool beneath your feet.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:35
        content: "  See  , which is the most frequently quoted Old Testament verse
          found in the New Testament. This shows there is a continuing work of defeating
          Christ\u2019s enemies as his kingdom increases on earth as it is in heaven.    "
    - name: "36: The Crowd Responds to Peter\u2019s Words"
      title: "The Crowd Responds to Peter\u2019s Words"
      number: 36
      content: "\u201CNow everyone in Israel [[COMMENT(0)]] can know for certain 
        that Jesus, whom you crucified, is the one God has made <smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
        both Lord  and the Messiah.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 2:36
        content: "  Or \u201Call the house of Israel.\u201D      Or \u201Cinescapably,\u201D
          for no one can escape the claims of Christ.      The Aramaic is \u201CLord 
          made him [from birth] to be both Elohim and Messiah.\u201D The Greek verb
          used for \u201Cmade\u201D can also mean \u201Cbrought forth.\u201D This
          is a clear statement of both Jesus\u2019 humanity (God brought him forth
          by human birth) and his deity.        (Jesus) is now Lord of a new creation
          company, a new heaven, and a new earth\u2014he is Lord of all. The Greek
          word    is not necessarily a divine title. The Aramaic text uses a clear
          title of Jesus\u2019 deity.    "
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "When they heard this they were crushed and realized what they had
        done to Jesus. [[COMMENT(0)]] Deeply moved, they said to Peter and the other
        apostles, \u201CWhat do we need to do, brothers?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 2:37
        content: "  This Greek verb indicates the deepest sorrow and emotional agitation.
          It is taken from a root word that means \u201Cmortally wounded\u201D and
          is found only here in all the New Testament.      The Aramaic contains
          an idiomatic figure of speech, \u201CWhat do we need to do to be your brothers?\u201D    "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Peter replied, \u201CRepent and return to God, [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        each one of you must be baptized in the name of Jesus, the Anointed One,
        <smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps> to have your sins removed.
        Then you may take hold of the gift of the Holy Spirit. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:38
        content: "  The Greek word translated \u201Crepent\u201D means both \u201Cto
          change the mind and direction of your life\u201D and \u201Cto turn back
          to God.\u201D      Peter was likely saying these words from the steps of
          the temple. Below him were dozens of    (immersion pools used for ceremonial
          cleanings of Jewish worshipers). Peter was pointing them to the cleansing
          that comes through the name and authority of Jesus Christ. The Aramaic
          is startling: \u201CBe immersed in the name of Lord  .\u201D Peter is clearly
          saying that Lord  and Jesus are one and the same.    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "For God\u2019s promise of the Holy Spirit is for you [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and your families, for those yet to be born  and for everyone whom the Lord
        our God calls to himself.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 2:39
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CThis outpouring is for you.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cfor those who are far away (gentiles).\u201D    "
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "Peter preached to them and warned them with these words: \u201CBe
        rescued from the wayward and perverse culture of this world!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:40
        content: "  Or \u201CBe free from and preserved from this crooked people!\u201D    "
    - name: '41: The Community of Believers'
      title: The Community of Believers
      number: 41
      content: Those who believed the word that day numbered three thousand. They
        were all baptized and added to the church. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 2:41
        content: '  Although the word    is not in the text, it is implied. They
          were converted by the message of Peter and brought into the fellowship
          of the believers.    '
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'Every believer was faithfully devoted to following the teachings
        [[COMMENT(0)]] of the apostles. Their hearts were mutually linked to one
        another,  sharing communion  and coming together regularly for prayer.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:42
        content: "  The Greek word    means \u201Cskilled instruction and training.\u201D     
          Or \u201CThey became partners.\u201D      Or \u201Cbreaking of bread.\u201D
          This was more than sharing meals, but participating together in observing
          the Lord\u2019s Table. The Aramaic, which can be translated \u201Cthe Eucharist\u201D
          or \u201Choly communion,\u201D makes it even more explicit.      Or \u201C[all
          kinds of] prayers.\u201D    "
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'A deep sense of holy awe [[COMMENT(0)]] swept over everyone, and
        the apostles performed many miraculous signs and wonders.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:43
        content: "  Or \u201CFear [of God] came upon every person.\u201D      The
          Aramaic adds, \u201Cin Jerusalem,\u201D which is missing in the Greek.    "
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: 'All the believers were in fellowship as one body, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and they shared with one another whatever they had. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:44
        content: "  Or \u201Cadded into one body.\u201D    "
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'Out of generosity they even sold their assets to distribute the proceeds
        to those who were in need among them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "Daily they met together in the temple courts and in one another\u2019s
        homes to celebrate communion. They shared meals together with joyful hearts
        and tender humility. "
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: They were continually filled with praises to God, enjoying the favor
        of all the people. And the Lord kept adding to their number daily those who
        were coming to life. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 2:47
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Aramaic word for \u201Cchurch\u201D
          is the joining of \u201Cmeet\u201D and \u201Ccome.\u201D This word is an
          invitation to enter into fellowship with Christ and his people. The Greek
          word for \u201Cchurch\u201D is  , which is \u201Ccalled-out ones.\u201D
          (See the second footnote on  .)  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Healing at the Beautiful Gate'
      title: Healing at the Beautiful Gate
      number: 1
      content: "One afternoon Peter and John went to the temple for the three o\u2019clock
        prayer. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:1
        content: "  Daily sacrifices were made in the temple at sunrise and about
          three o\u2019clock every afternoon.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'As they came to the entrance called the Beautiful Gate, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        they were captured by the sight of a man crippled from birth being carried
        and placed at the entrance to the temple. He was often brought there to beg
        for money from those going in to worship. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe gate called Wonderful\u201D in Aramaic. It is difficult
          to ascertain which of the many gates of the temple this might have been,
          and there is varying speculation with no certain conclusion. However, this
          Beautiful Gate points to Jesus Christ, who is the gate or entrance into
          the sheepfold of God. Furthermore, it hints of Ezekiel\u2019s temple (),
          which has a river flowing out from the threshold through the gateway of
          the temple. This river was first measured to be ankle deep. This man, lame
          in his ankles, was healed by the spiritual \u201Criver\u201D that flowed
          out the \u201CBeautiful Gate\u201D of Christ. The gateway opened up and
          the river poured out of Peter and John, bringing healing to the lame.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: When he noticed Peter and John going into the temple, he begged them
        for money.
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Peter and John, looking straight into the eyes of the crippled man,
        said, \u201CLook at us!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Expecting a gift, he readily gave them his attention. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then Peter said, \u201CI don\u2019t have money, but I\u2019ll give
        you this\u2014by the power of the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth, stand
        up and walk!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7-8: '
      title: 
      number: 7-8
      content: Peter held out his right hand to the crippled man. As he pulled the
        man to his feet, suddenly power surged into his crippled feet and ankles.
        The man jumped up, stood there for a moment stunned, and then began to walk
        around! As he went into the temple courts with Peter and John, he leapt for
        joy and shouted praises to God.
      comments: []
    - name: '7-8: '
      title: 
      number: 7-8
      content: Peter held out his right hand to the crippled man. As he pulled the
        man to his feet, suddenly power surged into his crippled feet and ankles.
        The man jumped up, stood there for a moment stunned, and then began to walk
        around! As he went into the temple courts with Peter and John, he leapt for
        joy and shouted praises to God.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'When all the people saw him jumping up and down and heard him glorifying
        God, '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: Peter Preaches to the Crowd'
      title: Peter Preaches to the Crowd
      number: 10
      content: they realized it was the crippled beggar they had passed by in front
        of the Beautiful Gate. Astonishment swept over the crowd, for they were amazed
        over what had happened to him.
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Dumbfounded over what they were witnessing, the crowd ran over to
        Peter and John, who were standing under the covered walkway called Solomon\u2019s
        Porch. Standing there also was the healed beggar, clinging to Peter and John.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:11
        content: "  What an amazing picture this makes. This scene transpired at
          Solomon\u2019s Porch. Lessons of wisdom, greater than the wisdom of Solomon,
          were uncovered by this miracle to those who had hearts of understanding.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "With the crowd surrounding him, Peter said to them all, \u201CPeople
        of Israel, [[COMMENT(0)]] listen to me! Why are you so amazed by this healing?
        Why do you stare at us? We didn\u2019t make this crippled man walk by our
        own power or authority.   "
      comments:
      - number: 3:12
        content: "  The Aramaic could be translated \u201Cprotectors of Israel.\u201D     
          As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cpiety.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "The God of our ancestors, the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        has done this. For he has glorified his Servant  Jesus, the one you denied
        to Pilate\u2019s face when he decided to release him\u2014and you insisted
        that he be crucified. "
      comments:
      - number: 3:13
        content: '  See  .      See  .    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'You rejected [[COMMENT(0)]] the one who is holy and righteous, and
        instead begged for a murderer to be released. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cdenied.\u201D It is amazing how complete was the healing
          of Peter\u2019s life. Just fifty days previously, it was Peter who denied
          he knew Jesus three times. Now he says to his fellow Jews, \u201CYou denied
          the holy and righteous One!\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'You killed the Prince of Life! [[COMMENT(0)]] But God raised him
        from the dead, and we stand here as witnesses to that fact. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:15
        content: "  Or \u201COriginator of Life.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Faith in Jesus\u2019 name has healed this man standing before you.
        It is the faith that comes through believing in Jesus\u2019 name that has
        made the crippled man walk right in front of your eyes!"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CMy fellow Jews, I realize that neither you nor your leaders
        realize the grave mistake you made. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "But in spite of what you\u2019ve done, God has fulfilled what he
        foretold through the prophets long ago about the sufferings of his Anointed
        One. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "And now you must repent and turn back [[COMMENT(0)]] to God so that
        your sins will be removed,  and so that times of refreshing  will stream
        from the Lord\u2019s presence. "
      comments:
      - number: 3:19
        content: "  Peter uses the Greek word    (\u201Cturn back to God,\u201D \u201Cbe
          converted\u201D). We need to not only repent but to return home to God\u2019s
          grace and truth. This is a Hebraic thought of returning to the Lord God
          (the Hebrew word  ). Every Jew would know what that means: \u201CCome back
          to God!\u201D Repentance and return is more than a passive changing of
          one\u2019s mind.      The Greek word used here,  , means \u201Cobliterated\u201D
          or \u201Ccanceled.\u201D      Or \u201Ccooling breeze,\u201D which occurs
          only here in the New Testament. This hints of the time when God walked
          with Adam in the cooling breeze of the day. The work of the cross begins
          the restoration of Paradise within the hearts of Christ\u2019s followers.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'And he will send you Jesus, the Messiah, the appointed one. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 3:20
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CHe will send you all that
          has been already prepared for you through Jesus, the Anointed One.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'For he must remain in heaven until the restoration of all things
        [[COMMENT(0)]] has taken place,   fulfilling everything that God said long
        ago through his holy prophets. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cuntil the time for the universal restoration.\u201D     
          Or \u201CThis one the heavens must receive until the times of universal
          restoration.\u201D The word    in Greek is  , which infers the restoration
          of creation to the state of existence before the fall, but also Davidic
          covenant being restored. Luke\u2019s choice of the Greek word found only
          here in the New Testament is noteworthy. It is a medical term that means
          \u201Crestoration of perfect health.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "For has not Moses told us: [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2018The Lord your God
        will raise upa prophet from among you who is like me.Listen to him and follow
        everything he tells you."
      comments:
      - number: 3:22
        content: '  See  ;  ,  .    '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Every person who disobeys that prophetwill be cut off and completely
        destroyed.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CIn fact, every prophet from the time of Samuel onward has prophesied
        of these very days! "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "And you are heirs of their prophecies [[COMMENT(0)]] and of the covenants
        God made with your fathers when he promised Abraham,  \u2018Your descendant 
        will bring blessing to all the people on the earth.\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 3:25
        content: "  Or \u201Csons of the prophets.\u201D      See  ;  .      Or \u201Cseed\u201D
          (descendants).    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CNow that God raised up his Son, [[COMMENT(0)]] he has chosen
        to send him first to you that he might bless you by turning each one of you 
        from your wickedness.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 3:26
        content: "  The Greek word    can mean either \u201Cservant\u201D or \u201Cson.\u201D
          (See  , Gr. 3816.) The Aramaic is clearly \u201Cson.\u201D Notice how many
          times in the book of Acts that the followers of Christ preached the resurrection.
          The power and virtue of the cross can never be diminished; however, it
          is the resurrection of Christ that became the apostolic center of their
          preaching in the book of Acts.      The Aramaic uses the conditional clause
          \u201Cif you turn and repent from your evils.\u201D      The Greek is plural,
          \u201Cwickednesses\u201D or \u201Cevil ways.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1-2: Peter and John Arrested'
      title: Peter and John Arrested
      number: 1-2
      content: 'The teaching and preaching of Peter and John angered the priests,
        the captain of the temple police, and representatives of the Jewish sect
        of the Sadducees. [[COMMENT(0)]] They were furious that the people were being
        taught that in Jesus there is a resurrection from the dead. So while Peter
        and John were still speaking, the Jewish authorities came to the temple courts
        to oppose them. '
      comments:
      - number: "4:1\u20132"
        content: '  Of the three major sects of Judaism of that day (Pharisees, Essenes,
          and Sadducees), the Sadducees were a small but influential group that philosophically
          denied the supernatural and gravitated instead toward political control
          of the people. Their denial of the resurrection is what prompted their
          actions here.    '
    - name: '1-2: Peter and John Arrested'
      title: Peter and John Arrested
      number: 1-2
      content: 'The teaching and preaching of Peter and John angered the priests,
        the captain of the temple police, and representatives of the Jewish sect
        of the Sadducees. [[COMMENT(0)]] They were furious that the people were being
        taught that in Jesus there is a resurrection from the dead. So while Peter
        and John were still speaking, the Jewish authorities came to the temple courts
        to oppose them. '
      comments:
      - number: "4:1\u20132"
        content: '  Of the three major sects of Judaism of that day (Pharisees, Essenes,
          and Sadducees), the Sadducees were a small but influential group that philosophically
          denied the supernatural and gravitated instead toward political control
          of the people. Their denial of the resurrection is what prompted their
          actions here.    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'They had them arrested, and since it was already evening they kept
        them in custody until the next day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: Yet there were many in the crowd who believed the message, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        bringing the total number of men who believed  to nearly five thousand!
      comments:
      - number: 4:4
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Word\u201D (Gr.  ).      Although the cultural way
          of numbering the Jewish crowd is technically \u201Cadult males,\u201D the
          usage of the Greek term    is consistently found throughout Greek literature
          as an inclusive and formal term of respect, similar to \u201Cladies and
          gentlemen.\u201D Including women and children, the early church swelled
          rapidly into tens of thousands.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The next day many Jewish leaders, religious scholars, and elders
        of the people convened a meeting in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Annas the high priest was there with Caiaphas, John, Alexander, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and others who were members of the high priest\u2019s family. "
      comments:
      - number: 4:6
        content: '  There is little known about John (or Jonathan) and Alexander.
          It is possible that John was the son of Caiaphas, who would one day be
          the high priest. Or John and Alexander could have been the leaders of the
          Sadducees.    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "They made Peter and John stand in front of the council as they questioned
        them, saying, \u201CTell us, by what power and authority have you done these
        things?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:7
        content: "  Or \u201CIn whose name did you do this?\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Peter, filled with the Holy Spirit, answered, \u201CRespected elders
        and leaders of the people, listen. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Are we being put on trial today for doing an act of kindness by healing
        a frail, crippled man? Well then, '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'you and everyone else in Israel should know that it is by the power
        of the name of Jesus that the crippled man stands here today completely healed!
        You crucified Jesus Christ of Nazareth, [[COMMENT(0)]] but God raised him
        from the dead. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Nazarene.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "This Jesus is \u2018the stone that you, the builders, have rejected,
        and now he has become the cornerstone!\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 4:11
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "There is no one else [[COMMENT(0)]] who has the power to save us,
        for there is only one name to whom God has given authority by which we must
        experience salvation:   the name of Jesus.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 4:12
        content: "  Peter insisted there was no man who could claim to be the Messiah
          other than Jesus.      The Aramaic is \u201CWe must experience the Life
          Giver\u201D or \u201CWe must receive the covenant of life.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'The council members were astonished as they witnessed the bold courage
        [[COMMENT(0)]] of Peter and John, especially when they discovered that they
        were just ordinary men who had never had religious training.  Then they began
        to understand the effect Jesus had on them simply by spending time with him. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:13
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Chearing the bold words of Peter and John.\u201D     
          The Aramaic is \u201CThey did not know the scrolls.\u201D The Greek is
          \u201Cuneducated.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: Standing there with them was the healed man, and there was nothing
        further they could say.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So they ordered them to leave the room while they discussed the matter.
        Among themselves, they said, '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CWhat should we do with these men? Everyone in Jerusalem can
        clearly see that they\u2019ve performed a notable sign and wonder\u2014we
        can\u2019t deny that. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But to keep this propaganda from spreading any further among the
        people, let\u2019s threaten them severely and warn them to never speak to
        anyone in this name again.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'So they had them brought back in before the council, and they commanded
        them to never teach the people or speak again using the name of Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "But Peter and John replied, \u201CYou can judge for yourselves\u2014is
        it better to listen to you or to God? "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "It\u2019s impossible for us to stop speaking about all the things
        we\u2019ve seen and heard!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Since the members of the council couldn\u2019t come up with a crime
        they could punish them for, they threatened them once more and let them go.
        All the people praised God, thrilled over the miraculous healing of the crippled
        man. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 4:21
        content: "  Made explicit from the text, \u201Cover what had happened.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: The Church Prays'
      title: The Church Prays
      number: 22
      content: And the man who received this miracle sign of healing was over forty
        years old. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 4:22
        content: '  For the significance of the number forty, see the second footnote
          on  .    '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'As soon as they were released from custody, Peter and John went to
        the other believers and explained all that had happened with the high priest
        and the elders. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "When the believers heard their report, they raised their voices in
        unity and prayed, \u201CLord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        you are the Lord of all! You created the universe\u2014the earth, the sky,
        the sea, and everything that is in them.   "
      comments:
      - number: 4:24
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.      See  ;  .    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "And you spoke by the Holy Spirit through your servant David, our
        forefather, saying:\u2018How dare the nations plan a rebellion,ranting and
        raging against the Lord Most High?Their foolish plots are futile!"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Look at how the kings of the earth take their stand,with the rulers
        scheming and conspiring togetheragainst God [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>,\u201D
        and the Greek is \u201CLord\u201D (</smallcaps> and his anointed Messiah!\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 4:26
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CLord  ).      See  .    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CIn fact, Herod and Pontius Pilate, along with Jews and non-Jews,
        met together to take their stand against your holy servant, Jesus the Messiah. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'They did to him all that your purpose and will had determined, according
        to the destiny you had marked out for him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'So now, Lord, listen to their threats to harm us. Empower us, as
        your servants, to speak the word of God freely and courageously. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Stretch out your hand of power through us to heal, and to move in
        signs and wonders by the name of your holy Son, Jesus!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:30
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cyour holy
          servant, Jesus.\u201D    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'As they prayed the earth shook beneath them, causing the building
        they were in to tremble. [[COMMENT(0)]] Each one of them was filled with
        the Holy Spirit, and they proclaimed the word of God with unrestrained boldness. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:31
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Can earthquake.\u201D      The Greek word
          is  . This involves more than confidence; it was a free-flowing, unrestrained
          boldness. It can also mean \u201Cfreedom of speech.\u201D    carries nuances
          that are not easily brought over into English. The person who speaks with   
          will say everything that is on his mind with no restraint, flowing out
          of his heart with confidence. It involves being frank and honest, hiding
          nothing and speaking directly to the heart. Most often it is a word used
          for public speaking. It refers to speech that is not tailored to make everyone
          happy but to speak the truth, in spite of what that may cost. It is the
          courage to speak truth into the ears of others. This was reserved for only
          the highest rank of Greek citizens, not people of other lands or slaves.
          The right to speak freely was an essential aspect of Athenian democracy.
          Although it is sometimes associated with negative speech, in this context   
          refers to an unrestrained boldness. There was a Greek idiom that said essentially,
          \u201CIf you tell me the truth no matter what that truth turns out to be,
          I will not punish you.\u201D This was known as the Parresiastic Contract.
          See M. Foucault, \u201CDiscourse and Truth: The Problematization of Parresia,\u201D
          six lectures given at the University of California at Berkeley, 1983, ed.
          by Joseph Pearson in 1985.    is found also in  ;  ,  ,  ;  ;  ,  ;  ; 
          ;  ;  ;  ; and numerous other places.    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'All the believers were one in mind and heart. Selfishness was not
        a part of their community, for they shared everything they had with one another. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'The apostles gave powerful testimonies about the resurrection of
        the Lord Jesus, and great measures of grace [[COMMENT(0)]] rested upon them
        all. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:33
        content: "  Or \u201Cmega-grace.\u201D    "
    - name: '34-35: '
      title: 
      number: 34-35
      content: Some who owned houses or land sold them and brought the proceeds before
        the apostles to distribute to those without. Not a single person among them
        was needy.
      comments: []
    - name: '34-35: '
      title: 
      number: 34-35
      content: Some who owned houses or land sold them and brought the proceeds before
        the apostles to distribute to those without. Not a single person among them
        was needy.
      comments: []
    - name: '36-37: '
      title: 
      number: 36-37
      content: "For example, there was a Levite from Cyprus named Joseph, who sold
        his farmland and placed the proceeds at the feet of the apostles. They nicknamed
        him Barnabas (or \u201CEncourager\u201D). [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: "4:36\u201337"
        content: "  The name Barnabas means \u201Cson of encouragement,\u201D or
          \u201Cson of the prophet.\u201D This was the Barnabas who traveled with
          Paul as an apostle.  "
    - name: '36-37: '
      title: 
      number: 36-37
      content: "For example, there was a Levite from Cyprus named Joseph, who sold
        his farmland and placed the proceeds at the feet of the apostles. They nicknamed
        him Barnabas (or \u201CEncourager\u201D). [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: "4:36\u201337"
        content: "  The name Barnabas means \u201Cson of encouragement,\u201D or
          \u201Cson of the prophet.\u201D This was the Barnabas who traveled with
          Paul as an apostle.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Judgment of Ananias and Sapphira'
      title: The Judgment of Ananias and Sapphira
      number: 1
      content: 'Now, a man named Ananias and his wife, Sapphira, [[COMMENT(0)]] likewise
        sold their farm. '
      comments:
      - number: 5:1
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CAnanias, together with his
          wife, who was famous for her beauty.\u201D The Aramaic name    means \u201Cbeauty.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'They conspired to secretly keep back for themselves a portion of
        the proceeds. So when Ananias brought the money to the apostles, it was only
        a portion of the entire sale. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "God revealed their secret to Peter, [[COMMENT(0)]] so he said to
        him, \u201CAnanias, why did you let Satan fill your heart and make you think
        you could lie to the Holy Spirit? You only pretended to give it all, yet
        you hid back part of the proceeds from the sale of your property to keep
        for yourselves. "
      comments:
      - number: 5:3
        content: "  With supernatural discernment, God revealed to Peter what had
          happened. The words \u201Cpretended to give it all\u201D are not in the
          original text, but supplied because of the inference of the words \u201Clie
          to the Holy Spirit.\u201D The true sin was more than simply telling Peter
          a lie, but lying to the Holy Spirit.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Before you sold it, wasn\u2019t it yours to sell or to keep? And
        after you sold it, wasn\u2019t the money entirely at your disposal? How could
        you plot such a thing in your heart? You haven\u2019t lied to people; you\u2019ve
        lied to God!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 5:4
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CYou are not a phony with
          just men, but with God.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The moment Ananias heard those words, he fell over dead. Everyone
        was terrified when they heard what had happened. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: Some young men came in and removed the body and buried him.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: Three hours later, his wife came into the room, with no clue what
        had happened to her husband.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Peter said to her, \u201CTell me, were the two of you paid this amount
        for the sale of your land?\u201DSapphira said, \u201CYes, that\u2019s how
        much it was.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Peter told her, \u201CWhy have you agreed together to test the Spirit
        of the Lord? [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>.\u201D</smallcaps> I hear the footsteps
        of those who buried your husband at the door\u2014they\u2019re coming here
        to bury you too!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 5:9
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe Spirit of the Lord      "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "At that moment she dropped dead at Peter\u2019s feet.When the young
        men came in, she was already dead, so they carried her out and buried her
        next to her husband. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: The Apostles Perform Miracles, Signs, and Wonders'
      title: The Apostles Perform Miracles, Signs, and Wonders
      number: 11
      content: The entire church was seized with a powerful sense of the fear of
        God, [[COMMENT(0)]] which came over all who heard what had happened.
      comments:
      - number: 5:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cmega-fear fell on the church.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The apostles performed many signs, wonders, and miracles among the
        people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And the believers were wonderfully united as they met regularly in
        the temple courts in the area known as Solomon\u2019s Porch. No one dared
        harm them, [[COMMENT(0)]] for everyone held them in high regard."
      comments:
      - number: 5:13
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CNo one else
          dared join them,\u201D which is somewhat confusing because of the next
          verse.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Continually more and more people believed in the Lord [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>.\u201D</smallcaps>
        and were added to their number\u2014great crowds of both men and women. "
      comments:
      - number: 5:14
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe Lord      "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'In fact, when people knew Peter was going to walk by, they carried
        the sick out to the streets and laid them down on cots and mats, knowing
        the incredible power emanating from him would overshadow them and heal them.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 5:15
        content: "  The Greek word translated \u201Covershadow\u201D is  , which
          is used exclusively for the power of the Almighty \u201Covershadowing,\u201D
          such as with Mary, who conceived a child supernaturally by God. It is also
          used for the cloud that overshadowed Jesus on the Mount of Transfiguration.
          See  ;  ;  . This was not a natural shadow created by the light of the
          sun, but the supernatural overshadowing of God\u2019s power coming upon
          the sick to bring healing.    "
    - name: '16: The Apostles Persecuted'
      title: The Apostles Persecuted
      number: 16
      content: "Great numbers of people swarmed into Jerusalem from the nearby villages.
        They brought with them the sick and those troubled by demons\u2014and everyone
        was healed!"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'The high priest and his officials, who formed the party of the Sadducees,
        became extremely jealous over all that was happening, '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'so they had the apostles arrested, placed in chains, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and thrown into jail. '
      comments:
      - number: 5:18
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "But during the night, the Lord [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>.\u201D</smallcaps>
        sent an angel who appeared before them. He supernaturally opened their prison
        doors and brought the apostles outside. "
      comments:
      - number: 5:19
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CLord      "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CGo,\u201D the angel told them. \u201CStand in the temple courts
        and preach the words that bring life!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'So early that morning they entered the temple courts and taught the
        people. The high priest and his officials, unaware of their supernatural
        release from prison, convened the members of the supreme council. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        They sent for the apostles to be brought to them from prison. '
      comments:
      - number: 5:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Sanhedrin.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'But when the officers came to the prison cell, it was empty! They
        returned to the council and informed them, '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CWe found the jail securely locked and the guards standing by
        their cell, but when we opened the door, there was no one inside!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: When the captain of the temple guard and the leading priests heard
        this report, they were perplexed and at a loss over what to make of it.
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Someone came and informed them, \u201CThe men you put in prison are
        out there standing in the temple courts, teaching the people!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: So the captain of the temple guard and his officers went to arrest
        them once again, but without using force, for they were afraid the people
        would stone them.
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'When they brought them before the council, the high priest demanded
        an explanation, '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "saying, \u201CDidn\u2019t we strictly warn you that you were to never
        again teach in this name? But instead you have now filled all of Jerusalem
        with this doctrine and are committed to holding us responsible for this man\u2019s
        death!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 5:28
        content: "  Or \u201Cbringing [the guilt of] this man\u2019s blood on us.\u201D    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Peter and the apostles replied, \u201CWe must listen to and obey
        God more than pleasing religious leaders. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'You had Jesus arrested and killed by crucifixion, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        but the God of our forefathers  has raised him up. '
      comments:
      - number: 5:30
        content: "  Or \u201Cby hanging him on a tree,\u201D an Aramaic idiom for
          crucifixion. See  .      See  .    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "He\u2019s the one God has exalted and seated at his right hand as
        our Savior and Champion. [[COMMENT(0)]] He is the provider of grace as the
        Redeemer of Israel.   "
      comments:
      - number: 5:31
        content: "  Or \u201CPrince.\u201D      As translated from the Aramaic. The
          Greek is \u201CHe gives repentance and removal of sins to Israel.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "We are witnesses of these things, [[COMMENT(0)]] and so is the Holy
        Spirit, whom God freely gives to all who believe in him.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 5:32
        content: "  Or \u201Cwords.\u201D This is the Greek word  .      As translated
          from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cto those who hear and obey him.\u201D    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'When they heard this, they were infuriated and determined to murder
        them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'But a Pharisee named Gamaliel, a noted religious professor who was
        highly respected by all, stood up. He gave orders to send the apostles outside. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Then he said to the council, \u201CMen of Israel, you need to be
        very careful about how you deal with these men. "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: Some time ago there was a man named Theudas who rose up claiming to
        be somebody. He had a following of about four hundred men, but when he was
        killed, all of his followers were scattered, and nothing came of it.
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "\u201CAfter him, in the days of the census, [[COMMENT(0)]] another
        man rose up, Judas the Galilean, who got people to follow him in a revolt.
        He too perished, and all those who followed him were scattered. "
      comments:
      - number: 5:37
        content: "  Or \u201Cregistration for the Roman tax.\u201D  "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'So in this situation, you should just leave these men to themselves.
        For if this plan or undertaking originates with men, it will fade away and
        come to nothing. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "But if this movement is of God, you won\u2019t be able to stop it.
        And you might discover that you were fighting God all along!\u201DGamaliel\u2019s
        words convinced the council. "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: So they brought the apostles back in and had them severely beaten.
        They ordered them never again to speak in the name of Jesus and then let
        them go.
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'The apostles left there rejoicing, thrilled that God had considered
        them worthy to suffer disgrace for the name of Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "And nothing stopped them! They kept preaching every day in the temple
        courts and went from house to house, preaching the gospel of Jesus, God\u2019s
        Anointed One!"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Servant Leaders'
      title: Servant Leaders
      number: 1
      content: "During those days the number of Jesus\u2019 followers kept multiplying
        greatly. But a complaint was brought against those who spoke Aramaic [[COMMENT(0)]]
        by the Greek-speaking Jews,  who felt their widows were being overlooked
        during the daily distribution of food."
      comments:
      - number: 6:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Hebrews\u201D (converts from orthodox Judaism).
          There was one dominant language in Israel: Aramaic. However, the issue
          between the two groups was more than merely a language difference. Those
          who spoke Aramaic were natives, while the Greek-speaking minority were
          most likely Jews from other nations.      Or \u201CHellenists.\u201D These
          were Jewish converts who sought to maintain a Greek language and culture
          and were predominantly Alexandrian Jews. These may have been Jews who were
          scattered throughout the Roman Empire, including Greece and Alexandria,
          Egypt.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "The twelve apostles called a meeting of all the believers and told
        them, \u201CIt is not advantageous for us to be pulled away from the word
        of God to wait on tables. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'We want you to carefully select [[COMMENT(0)]] from among yourselves
        seven godly men. Make sure they are honorable, full of the Holy Spirit and
        wisdom, and we will give them the responsibility of this crucial ministry
        of serving. '
      comments:
      - number: 6:3
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cselect with awe,\u201D that is, in the presence
          of the Lord.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "That will enable us to give our full attention to prayer and preaching
        the word of God.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Everyone in the church loved this idea. [[COMMENT(0)]] So they chose
        seven men. One of them was Stephen,  who was known as a man full of faith
        and overflowing with the Holy Spirit. Along with him they chose Philip, Prochorus,
        Nicanor, Timon, Parmenas, and Nicholas from Antioch,  who had converted to
        Judaism. '
      comments:
      - number: 6:5
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CThis proposal appeared beautiful.\u201D     
          It is most likely that Stephen was not a gentile but a Jewish believer.
          His Hebrew name,  , is transliterated into Greek as    (Stephen in English).   
          is the name of the prophet Zephaniah. Zephaniah means \u201CYah has treasured
          [him].\u201D Stephen was not a gentile proselyte to Judaism but a Greek-speaking
          Hebrew. He spoke in    and addressed his hearers as \u201Cfellow Jews and
          fathers.\u201D Although he was a powerful minister of the Word, Stephen
          was humble to accept the task of serving.      The Aramaic can be translated
          \u201CNicholas, the hero of Antioch.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: All seven stood before the apostles, who laid their hands on them
        and prayed for them, commissioning them to this ministry. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 6:6
        content: '  The practice of laying on of hands indicates approval, impartation
          of authority, commissioning, and ordaining. As the Old Testament priest
          laid hands on a sacrifice and transferred the guilt of sins upon the animal,
          the New Testament apostles laid their hands on men and appointed them to
          ministry. See  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "God\u2019s word reigned supreme [[COMMENT(0)]] and kept spreading.
        The number of Jesus\u2019 followers in Jerusalem quickly grew and increased
        by the day. Even a great number of Jewish priests became believers and were
        obedient to the faith!"
      comments:
      - number: 6:7
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Stephen, who was a man full of grace and supernatural power, performed
        many astonishing signs and wonders and mighty miracles among the people.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 6:8
        content: '  Stephen was not an apostle, yet he worked miracles of power through
          his ministry. The miraculous is not for the few, but for the many.    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'This upset some men belonging to a sect who called themselves the
        Men Set Free. [[COMMENT(0)]] They were Libyans,  Egyptians,  and Turks. They
        all confronted Stephen to argue  with him. '
      comments:
      - number: 6:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Synagogue of the Freedmen.\u201D Although most expositors
          view these as former Hebrew slaves, the Aramaic is \u201CLibertines.\u201D
          It is possible that these were pagan cult members who followed a Roman
          mythical hero named Liber. From this word we get the English word  . They
          emphasized drunkenness and promiscuity. They boasted in their freedom from
          all moral laws as the Men Set Free to do whatever they desired. They were
          so hedonistic that even other pagans viewed them as wicked. These Libertines
          were the antithesis to the true freedom that comes through Christ ().     
          Or \u201CCyrene,\u201D a region of eastern Libya.      Or \u201CAlexandria,\u201D
          a large Egyptian city on the Mediterranean.      Or \u201CCilicia\u201D
          (southeastern coastal area of Turkey) and \u201Cthe province of Asia\u201D
          (that is, Asia Minor, comprised of western and southwestern Turkey). Both
          regions are included in the word  .      The Aramaic is \u201Cword wrestle.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'But the Holy Spirit gave Stephen remarkable wisdom to answer them.
        His words were prompted by the Holy Spirit, and they could not refute what
        he said. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "So the Men Set Free conspired in secret to find those who would bring
        false accusations against Stephen and lie about him by saying, \u201CWe heard
        this man speak blasphemy against Moses and God.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The Men Set Free agitated the crowd, the elders, and the religious
        scholars, [[COMMENT(0)]] then seized Stephen and forcefully took him before
        the supreme council. '
      comments:
      - number: 6:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cscribes.\u201D These were considered the experts in
          the law of Moses.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "One after another, false witnesses stepped forward and accused Stephen,
        saying, \u201CThis man never stops denigrating our temple and our Jewish
        law. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "For we have heard him teach that Jesus of Nazareth will destroy the
        temple and change the traditions and customs that Moses handed down to us.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 6:14
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CWe heard him teach that Jesus the Nazarene
          is the one who freed our nation and changed the feasts that Moses observed.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: Every member of the supreme council focused his gaze on Stephen, for
        right in front of their eyes, while being falsely accused, his face glowed
        as though he had the face of an angel! [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 6:15
        content: "  As he faced persecution and martyrdom, Stephen\u2019s face lit
          up with heaven\u2019s light, shining as an angelic messenger. What manifests
          in your life when you are opposed and falsely accused?  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Stephen\u2019s Sermon"
      title: "Stephen\u2019s Sermon"
      number: 1
      content: "The high priest asked, \u201CAre these accusations true?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Stephen replied, \u201CMy fellow Jews and fathers, listen to me.
        The God of glory appeared [[COMMENT(0)]] to our ancestor Abraham while he
        was living in Iraq  and before he moved to Haran  in Syria. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:2
        content: "  The entire Hebrew family, and consequently the life of believers
          today, all began with a divine encounter as the God of glory appeared before
          Abraham. It is this same glory that calls people to faith in Christ. We,
          like Abraham, have been captured by the God of glory. See  .      Or \u201CMesopotamia,\u201D
          or \u201Cthe land between two rivers\u201D (Euphrates and Tigris).     
          This is the city to which Abraham migrated on his way to the promised land.
          Haran was also the son of Caleb who claimed a mountain. Haran means \u201Cmountain
          climber.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "God said to him, \u2018Go! Leave behind your country and your relatives.
        Begin your journey and come to the land that I will show you.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:3
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CSo Abraham left southeastern Iraq [[COMMENT(0)]] and began
        his journey. He settled in Haran and stayed there until his father passed
        away. Then God had him move to the land of Israel with only a promise. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:4
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe land of Chaldeans.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Although God gave him no parcel of land he could call his own, not
        even a footprint, [[COMMENT(0)]] yet he promised Abraham that he and his
        descendants would one day have it all. And even though as yet Abraham had
        no child, '
      comments:
      - number: 7:5
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "God spoke with him and gave him this promise:\u2018Your descendants
        will live in a foreign land with a peoplewho will make slaves of themand
        oppress them for four hundred years. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:6
        content: '  See  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "But I will judge the nation that enslaves them,and your descendants
        will be set freeto return to this land to serve and worship me.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:7
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CThen God entered into covenant with Abraham, which included
        the requirement of circumcision. So when he became the father of Isaac, he
        circumcised him eight days after his birth."
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CIsaac then became the father of Jacob, who was the father of
        our twelve patriarchs. Jacob\u2019s sons became jealous of their brother
        Joseph and sold him to be a slave in Egypt. But God\u2019s favor and blessing
        rested upon Joseph, and in time, "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: God rescued him from all his oppression and granted him extraordinary
        favor before Pharaoh, the king of Egypt. Pharaoh appointed him as the overseer
        of his nation and even of his own palace. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 7:10
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CThen a devastating famine came over all of Egypt and Canaan,
        bringing great misery to the people, including our ancestors, who couldn\u2019t
        find food. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 7:11
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But when Jacob learned that there was food in Egypt, he sent his
        sons, our ancestors, on their first trip to purchase grain for their family. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "On their second trip to Egypt, Joseph revealed his identity to his
        brothers, [[COMMENT(0)]] and because of this, Pharaoh learned about Joseph\u2019s
        family and where he came from."
      comments:
      - number: 7:13
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CJoseph sent for his father, Jacob, and his entire family, a
        total of seventy-five people, to come and reside in Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Eventually, Jacob died there, along with all of his sons, our forefathers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: Their bones [[COMMENT(0)]] were later carried back to the promised
        land and buried in Shechem, in the tomb Abraham had purchased for a sum of
        money from the sons of Hamor.
      comments:
      - number: 7:16
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Chis [Jacob\u2019s] bones,\u201D while every
          Greek manuscript is \u201Ctheir bones.\u201D Jacob was buried in Abraham\u2019s
          tomb according to  . Joseph was buried in a plot purchased in Shechem for
          one hundred pieces of silver (;  ).    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CThe time drew near for God to fulfill the prophetic promise
        he had made to Abraham. Our Jewish people had increased greatly in number,
        multiplying many times over while in Egypt."
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CAnother [[COMMENT(0)]] king, who had forgotten how Joseph had
        made their nation great, arose to rule over Egypt.   "
      comments:
      - number: 7:18
        content: "  The Greek is \u201Canother of a different kind [or \u2018character\u2019].\u201D     
          See  .    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: He was an abusive king who exploited our people with his smooth talk.
        With cruelty he forced our ancestors to give up their little boys as he committed
        infanticide! [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 7:19
        content: "  The Aramaic can also be translated \u201Cforced them to abort
          their children.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CThen Moses came on the scene\u2014a child of divine beauty.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] His parents hid him from Pharaoh as long as they could to
        spare his life.  After three months they could conceal him no longer, "
      comments:
      - number: 7:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cbeautiful [well pleasing] in the eyes of God.\u201D
          The Aramaic is \u201CHe was loved by God.\u201D Ancient Hebrew scholars
          believed Moses may have had a shining of glory on his countenance when
          he was born, distinguishing him as a special servant of the Lord God. This
          shining face would later mark him as one who dwelt in the presence of the
          Lord (). Moses was a type or picture of the Lord Jesus Christ. No one was
          fairer than he; but no one was more extraordinary than our Lord. We learn
          from    that Moses\u2019 father was Amram and his mother was Jochebed.
          Amram means \u201Cfamily of the lofty One\u201D and Jochebed means \u201CYah
          makes great.\u201D The sister of Moses was Miriam (the Hebrew name for
          Mary), which comes from the root word for \u201Cmyrrh,\u201D meaning \u201Caromatic,\u201D
          \u201Cfragrant,\u201D or \u201Cbitter.\u201D The name Moses means \u201Crescued
          out of the water.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "so they had to abandon him to his fate. But God arranged that Pharaoh\u2019s
        daughter would find him, take him home, and raise him as her own son. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: So Moses was fully trained in the royal courts and educated in the
        highest wisdom Egypt had to offer, until he arose as a powerful prince and
        an eloquent orator. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 7:22
        content: "  Jewish tradition is that Pharaoh\u2019s daughter had no child
          of her own and she herself was an only child. Moses stood in line to receive
          the throne of Egypt, the great world power. God was going to prepare a
          servant who would do his pleasure. All the education and culture of this
          world dynasty with its unlimited resources was placed before Moses. See 
          .    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CWhen Moses turned forty, his heart was stirred for his people,
        the Israelites. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'One day he saw one of our people being violently mistreated, so he
        came to his rescue, and with his own hands Moses murdered the abusive Egyptian. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Moses hoped that when the people realized how he had rescued one
        of their own, they would recognize him as their deliverer. How wrong he was! '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "The next day he came upon two of our people engaged in a fist fight,
        and he tried to break it up by saying, \u2018Men, you are brothers! Why would
        you want to hurt each other?\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CBut the perpetrator pushed Moses aside and said, \u2018Who
        do you think you are? Who appointed you to be our ruler and judge? "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Are you going to kill me like you did the Egyptian yesterday?\u2019
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:28
        content: "  See  . Moses missed God\u2019s timing. To know God\u2019s will
          doesn\u2019t mean you know God\u2019s timing. God made Moses a ruler and
          a judge, but it took forty years to prepare him. Moses wanted the position
          forty years before he was ready. No one can make himself ruler and judge\u2014only
          God has authority to set leaders in place. We cannot raise ourselves up
          with ministry responsibilities until God releases us. See also  .    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CShaken by this, Moses fled Egypt [[COMMENT(0)]] and lived as
        an exile in the land of Midian, where he became the father of two sons. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:29
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'After forty years had passed, while he was in the desert near Mount
        Sinai, the Messenger of <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  [[COMMENT(0)]] appeared
        to him in the midst of a flaming thorn bush.   '
      comments:
      - number: 7:30
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.      See  .    '
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'Moses was astonished and stunned by what he was seeing, so he drew
        closer to observe this marvel. Then the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>
        spoke to him out of the flames:'
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "\u2018I am the living God, [[COMMENT(0)]] the God of your ancestors.I
        am the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.\u2019\u201CTrembling in God\u2019s
        presence and overwhelmed with awe, Moses didn\u2019t even dare to look into
        the fire."
      comments:
      - number: 7:32
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "\u201COut of the flames the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps> said
        to him:\u2018Take the sandals off your feet, [[COMMENT(0)]]for you are standing
        in the realm of holiness. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:33
        content: "  Removing one\u2019s shoes indicated the highest reverence. It
          is symbolic of removing earthly matters from our minds and hearts in readiness
          to accept spiritual realities.      Or \u201Cyou are standing on ground
          that is set apart\u201D (sacred).    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "I have watched and seen how my peoplehave been mistreated [[COMMENT(0)]]
        in Egypt.I have heard their painful groaning,and now I have come down to
        set them free.So come to me, Moses,for I am sending you to Egypt to represent
        me.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 7:34
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CI have seen their torment.\u201D      See 
          .    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "\u201CSo God sent back to Egypt the man our people rejected and refused
        to recognize by saying, \u2018Who appointed you to be our ruler and judge?\u2019
        God sent this man back to be their ruler and deliverer, commissioned with
        the power of the messenger who appeared to him in the flaming thorn bush. "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "This man brought the people out from their Egyptian bondage with
        many astonishing wonders and miracle signs\u2014miracles in Egypt, miracles
        at the Red Sea, and miracles during their forty-year journey through the
        wilderness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "This is the same Moses who said to our ancestors, \u2018The Lord
        God [[COMMENT(0)]] will raise up one from among you who will be a prophet
        to you, like I have been. Listen to everything he will say!\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 7:37
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.      As translated from the Aramaic.
          See  .    '
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "\u201CMoses led the congregation in the wilderness [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and he spoke face-to-face with the angel who spoke with him on the top of
        Mount Sinai. Along with our ancestors, he received the living oracles of
        God that were passed down to us. "
      comments:
      - number: 7:38
        content: "  Or \u201CMoses is the one who was in the assembly in the wilderness.\u201D    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: But our forefathers refused to obey. They pushed him away, and their
        hearts longed to return to Egypt.
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "\u201CWhile Moses was on the mountain, our forefathers said to Aaron,
        \u2018Make us gods to lead us, because we don\u2019t know what has become
        of this Moses who brought us out of Egypt.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:40
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CWe don\u2019t know who this Moses is.\u201D
          See  ,  .    "
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "\u201CSo they made a god, an idol in the form of a bull calf. They
        offered sacrifices to it and celebrated with delight what their own hands
        had made. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:41
        content: "  Or \u201CThey had a party in honor of what their own hands had
          made.\u201D    "
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "\u201CWhen God saw what they had done, he turned away from them and
        handed them over to the worship of the stars of heaven, [[COMMENT(0)]] as
        recorded in the prophetic writings: \u2018People of Israel, you failed to
        worship mewhen you offered animal sacrificesfor forty years in the wilderness."
      comments:
      - number: 7:42
        content: '  This was in violation of  ;  .      See  .    '
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "Instead you worshiped the god Moloch, [[COMMENT(0)]]and you carried
        his tabernacle, not mine.You worshiped your star-god, Rephan. You made idols
        with your handsand worshiped them instead of me.So now I will cast you into
        exile beyond Babylon.\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 7:43
        content: "  This was the Canaanite god of the sun and sky.      Or \u201CDerphan,\u201D
          or \u201CRemphan.\u201D This is the Assyrian deity also referred to as
          Saturn.    "
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "\u201CGod gave Moses the revelation of the pattern of the tabernacle
        of the testimony. By God\u2019s command, he made it exactly according to
        the specifications given to him for our ancestors in the wilderness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "The next generation received possession of it, and under Joshua\u2019s
        [[COMMENT(0)]] leadership they took possession of the land of the nations,
        which God drove out in front of them. The tabernacle was carried about until "
      comments:
      - number: 7:45
        content: '  In Aramaic-Hebrew, the spelling of Joshua and Jesus is the same: 
          .    '
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: 'David found loving favor with God and prayed for a dwelling place
        for the God of Jacob, '
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: but it was Solomon who built him a house. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 7:47
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: "\u201CHowever, the Most High God does not live in temples made by
        human hands, as the prophet said: [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:48
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "\u2018Heaven is my throne room and the earthis but a footstool for
        my feet.How could you possibly build a housethat could contain me?\u2019
        says the Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>.\u2018And where could you find
        a place where I could live?"
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: "Don\u2019t you know that it is my handsthat have built my house,
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  not yours?\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 7:50
        content: "  Or \u201Call these things.\u201D    "
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "\u201CWhy would you be so stubborn as to close your hearts and your
        ears to me? You are always opposing the Holy Spirit, just like your forefathers! "
      comments: []
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: "Which prophet was not persecuted and murdered by your ancestors?
        Name just one! They killed them all\u2014even the ones who prophesied long
        ago of the coming of the Righteous One! Now you follow in their steps and
        have become his betrayers and murderers. "
      comments: []
    - name: '53: Stephen Is Stoned to Death'
      title: Stephen Is Stoned to Death
      number: 53
      content: "You have been given the law by the visitation [[COMMENT(0)]] of angels,
        but you have not obeyed it.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 7:53
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cby angelic
          decrees.\u201D    "
    - name: '54: '
      title: 
      number: 54
      content: 'When they heard these things, they were overtaken with violent rage
        filling their souls, and they gnashed their teeth at him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '55: '
      title: 
      number: 55
      content: "But Stephen, overtaken with great faith, [[COMMENT(0)]] was full
        of the Holy Spirit. He fixed his gaze into the heavenly realm and saw the
        glory and splendor of God\u2014and Jesus, who stood up at the right hand
        of God."
      comments:
      - number: 7:55
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '56: '
      title: 
      number: 56
      content: "\u201CLook!\u201D Stephen said. \u201CI can see the heavens opening
        and the Son of Man standing at the right hand of God to welcome me home!\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 7:56
        content: '  Jesus sits at the right hand of God, but when he saw Stephen
          give his last breath for the gospel, he stood to welcome his martyr into
          his eternal reward.    '
    - name: '57: '
      title: 
      number: 57
      content: 'His accusers covered their ears with their hands and screamed at
        the top of their lungs to drown out his voice. '
      comments: []
    - name: '58: '
      title: 
      number: 58
      content: Then they pounced on him and threw him outside the city walls to stone
        him. His accusers, one by one, placed their outer garments at the feet of
        a young man named Saul of Tarsus. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 7:58
        content: "  That is, Saul, who would be converted and become Paul the apostle.
          Stephen\u2019s graduation was Paul\u2019s initiation.    "
    - name: '59: '
      title: 
      number: 59
      content: "As they hurled stone after stone at him, Stephen prayed, \u201COur
        Lord Jesus, accept my spirit into your presence.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '60: '
      title: 
      number: 60
      content: "He crumpled to his knees and shouted in a loud voice, \u201COur Lord,
        don\u2019t hold this sin against them.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] And then he died."
      comments:
      - number: 7:60
        content: '  See  ,  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Saul Persecutes the Believers'
      title: Saul Persecutes the Believers
      number: 1
      content: "Now, Saul agreed to be an accomplice to Stephen\u2019s stoning and
        participated in his execution. From that day on, a great persecution of the
        church in Jerusalem began. All the believers scattered into the countryside
        of Judea and among the Samaritans, except the apostles who remained behind
        in Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: God-fearing men gave Stephen a proper burial and mourned greatly over
        his death.
      comments: []
    - name: '3: The Gospel Spreads to Samaria'
      title: The Gospel Spreads to Samaria
      number: 3
      content: Then Saul mercilessly persecuted the church of God, going from house
        to house into the homes of believers to arrest both men and women and drag
        them off to prison.
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Although the believers were scattered by persecution, they preached
        the wonderful news of the word of God wherever they went. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Philip traveled to a Samaritan city [[COMMENT(0)]] and preached to
        them the wonderful news of the Anointed One. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe main city of Samaria.\u201D Many believe this was
          the Samaritan city of Sebaste.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "The crowds were eager to receive [[COMMENT(0)]] Philip\u2019s message
        and were persuaded by the many miracles and wonders he performed. "
      comments:
      - number: 8:6
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic, which indicates they did more
          than just hear the good news; they silenced those who said anything against
          Philip\u2019s message.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Many demon-possessed people were set free and delivered as evil spirits
        came out of them with loud screams and shrieks, and many who were lame and
        paralyzed were also healed. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 8:7
        content: '  Healings, miracles, and deliverances were being accomplished
          through others, not just the apostles.    '
    - name: '8: Simon the Sorcerer Converted'
      title: Simon the Sorcerer Converted
      number: 8
      content: This resulted in an uncontainable joy filling the city!
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Now, there was a man who lived there who was steeped in sorcery.
        For some time he had astounded the people of Samaria with his magic, boasting
        to be someone great. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 8:9
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CHe boasted of himself, saying, \u2018I am
          the great god!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Everyone, from the least to the greatest among them, was dazzled
        by his sorcery, [[COMMENT(0)]] saying, \u201CThis man is the greatest wizard
        of all! The divine power of God walks among us!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 8:10
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CThey were all praying to him\u201D or \u201Cbowing
          down to him.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: For many years everyone was in awe of him because of his astonishing
        displays of the magic arts.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "But as Philip preached the wonderful news of God\u2019s kingdom realm,
        and the name of Jesus the Anointed One, many believed his message and were
        baptized, both men and women. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: Even Simon believed and was baptized! Wherever Philip went, Simon
        was right by his side, astounded by all the miracles, signs, and enormous
        displays of power that he witnessed.
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "When the apostles in Jerusalem heard that the Samaritans had accepted
        God\u2019s message of life, they sent Peter and John "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'to pray over them so that they would receive the Holy Spirit. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 8:15
        content: "  Or \u201Ctake hold of the Holy Spirit.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'For they had only been baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus and
        were yet to have the Holy Spirit fall upon them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: As soon as Peter and John arrived, they laid their hands on the Samaritan
        believers, one after another, and the Holy Spirit fell and filled each one
        of them! [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 8:17
        content: "  Implied in the text. The Greek is \u201CThey took hold of the
          Holy Spirit.\u201D That is, the power of the Holy Spirit came upon them
          and filled them.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "When Simon saw how the Holy Spirit was released through the laying
        on of the apostles\u2019 hands, he approached them and offered them money, "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "saying, \u201CI want this power too. I\u2019m willing to pay you
        for the anointing [[COMMENT(0)]] that you have, so that I also can lay my
        hands on everyone to receive the Holy Spirit.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 8:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cauthority.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Peter rebuked him and said, \u201CYour money will go with you to
        destruction! How could you even think that you could purchase God\u2019s
        supernatural gift with money? "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'You will never have this gift or take part in this ministry, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        for your heart is not right with God. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:21
        content: "  Or \u201CYou have no part with us in this word\u201D (). The
          Aramaic is \u201CYou have no portion in this faith.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Repent this moment for allowing such wickedness to fill you. Plead
        with the Lord that perhaps he would forgive you the treachery of your heart. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "For I discern that jealous envy [[COMMENT(0)]] has poisoned you and
        binds you as a captive to sin.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 8:23
        content: "  Or \u201Cbitter anger.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: Philip and the Ethiopian'
      title: Philip and the Ethiopian
      number: 24
      content: "Simon begged, \u201CPeter, please pray to God for me. Plead with
        him so that nothing you just said over me may come to pass!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: After Peter and John had testified and taught the word of God in that
        city, they returned to Jerusalem, stopping at many Samaritan villages along
        the way to preach the hope of the gospel. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 8:25
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Then the Lord\u2019s angel said to Philip, \u201CNow go south from
        Jerusalem on the desert road to Gaza.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'He left immediately on his assignment.Along the way he encountered
        an Ethiopian who believed in the God of the Jews, [[COMMENT(0)]] who was
        the minister of finance for Candace, queen of Ethiopia. He was on his way
        home from worshiping God in Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:27
        content: "  Implied by the Aramaic word  , a homonym that can mean \u201Cbeliever\u201D
          or \u201Ceunuch.\u201D It is difficult to understand why a minister of
          finance would need to become a eunuch.    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: As he rode along in his chariot, he was reading from the scroll of
        Isaiah.
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "The Holy Spirit said to Philip, \u201CGo and walk alongside the chariot.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "So Philip ran to catch up. As he drew closer he overheard the man
        reading from the scroll of Isaiah the prophet. Philip asked him, \u201CSir,
        do you understand what you\u2019re reading?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "The man answered, \u201CHow can I possibly make sense of this without
        someone explaining it to me?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] So he invited Philip up
        into his chariot to sit with him."
      comments:
      - number: 8:31
        content: "  Or \u201Cunless someone guide me.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "The portion from Isaiah he was reading was this:He was led away to
        the slaughterlike a lamb to be offered.He was like a lamb that is silentbefore
        those who sheared him\u2014he never even opened his mouth."
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'In his lowliness justice was stripped away from him. [[COMMENT(0)]]And
        who could fully express his struggles?For his life was taken from the earth. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:33
        content: "  Which means he had no one there to defend him and stand up for
          justice.      As translated from the Aramaic. Both the Greek and the Aramaic
          are difficult to translate. The Greek is \u201CWho can describe his posterity?\u201D
          or \u201CWho could describe the [evil] people of his time?\u201D The Aramaic
          word for \u201Cstruggles\u201D (sufferings) and \u201Cgeneration\u201D
          is the homonym  . See  .    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "The Ethiopian asked Philip, \u201CPlease, can you tell me who the
        prophet is speaking of? Is it himself or another man?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: Philip started with this passage and shared with him the wonderful
        message of Jesus.
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "As they were traveling down the road, the man said, \u201CLook, here\u2019s
        a pool of water. Why don\u2019t I get baptized right now?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "Philip replied, \u201CIf you believe with all your heart, I\u2019ll
        baptize you.\u201DThe man answered, \u201CI believe that Jesus is the Anointed
        One, the Son of God.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 8:37
        content: '  Although only a few later Greek manuscripts include v.  , it
          is found in one of the oldest Aramaic texts (Harklean Syriac Version, AD
          616) and one Greek uncial from the eighth century. There is widespread
          consensus among scholars of both Greek and Aramaic texts that v.    was
          added as an ancient Christian confession of faith.    '
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'The Ethiopian stopped his chariot, and they went down into the water
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and Philip baptized him. '
      comments:
      - number: 8:38
        content: '  There was no need to go down into the water if it was a baptism
          of sprinkling. Philip immersed the believing Ethiopian man in baptism.    '
    - name: '39-40: '
      title: 
      number: 39-40
      content: 'When they came up out of the water, Philip was suddenly snatched
        up by the Spirit of the Lord and instantly carried away to the city of Ashdod,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] where he reappeared, preaching the gospel in that city.The
        man never saw Philip again. He returned to Ethiopia full of great joy. Philip,
        however, traveled on to all of the towns of that region, bringing them the
        good news, until he arrived at Caesarea. '
      comments:
      - number: "8:39\u201340"
        content: "  Or \u201CAzotus.\u201D This translation of Philip was an amazing
          miracle, as the city of Ashdod would have been fifteen miles or more from
          the desert road to Gaza. This miracle of being translated also took place
          with Ezekiel. See  .      This prominent Roman city was also known as Caesarea
          by the Sea.  "
    - name: '39-40: '
      title: 
      number: 39-40
      content: 'When they came up out of the water, Philip was suddenly snatched
        up by the Spirit of the Lord and instantly carried away to the city of Ashdod,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] where he reappeared, preaching the gospel in that city.The
        man never saw Philip again. He returned to Ethiopia full of great joy. Philip,
        however, traveled on to all of the towns of that region, bringing them the
        good news, until he arrived at Caesarea. '
      comments:
      - number: "8:39\u201340"
        content: "  Or \u201CAzotus.\u201D This translation of Philip was an amazing
          miracle, as the city of Ashdod would have been fifteen miles or more from
          the desert road to Gaza. This miracle of being translated also took place
          with Ezekiel. See  .      This prominent Roman city was also known as Caesarea
          by the Sea.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Saul Encounters Jesus'
      title: Saul Encounters Jesus
      number: 1
      content: 'During those days, Saul, full of angry threats and rage, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        wanted to murder the disciples of the Lord Jesus. So he went to ask the high
        priest '
      comments:
      - number: 9:1
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'and requested a letter of authorization he could take to the Jewish
        leaders in Damascus, [[COMMENT(0)]] requesting their cooperation in finding
        and arresting any who were followers of the Way.  Saul wanted to capture
        all of the believers he found, both men and women, and drag them as prisoners
        back to Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: 9:2
        content: "  Or \u201Csynagogues of Damascus.\u201D      The \u201CWay\u201D
          is Jesus Christ, the way that God dispenses himself into human beings.
          He lives inside of those who believe in him. See  . \u201CThe Way\u201D
          is also a term Luke uses throughout the book of Acts to designate believers
          in Jesus.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So he obtained the authorization and left for Damascus.Just outside
        the city, a brilliant light flashing from heaven suddenly exploded all around
        him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Falling to the ground, he heard a booming voice say to him, <JESUS>\u201CSaul,
        Saul, why are you persecuting me?\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 9:4
        content: '  To persecute the church is to persecute Jesus. He is one with
          his beloved church. See  .    '
    - name: '5-7: '
      title: 
      number: 5-7
      content: "The men accompanying Saul were stunned and speechless, for they heard
        a heavenly voice but could see no one.Saul replied, \u201CWho are you, Lord?\u201D<JESUS>\u201CI
        am Jesus, the Victorious,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>the one you are
        persecuting.</JESUS>    <JESUS>Now, get up and go into the city, where you
        will be told what you are to do.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: "9:5\u20137"
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic, which uses the word  . Although   
          is often translated \u201Cbranch\u201D (Nazarene), it can also be mean
          \u201Cvictorious\u201D or \u201Cheir of a mighty family.\u201D      The
          Aramaic adds a line here that can be translated \u201CIs it hard for you
          to rear up against a scorpion\u2019s stinger [or \u201Cgoads\u201D]?\u201D    "
    - name: '5-7: '
      title: 
      number: 5-7
      content: "The men accompanying Saul were stunned and speechless, for they heard
        a heavenly voice but could see no one.Saul replied, \u201CWho are you, Lord?\u201D<JESUS>\u201CI
        am Jesus, the Victorious,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>the one you are
        persecuting.</JESUS>    <JESUS>Now, get up and go into the city, where you
        will be told what you are to do.\u201D</JESUS>"
