    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CBut Lord,\u201D Ananias replied, \u201Cmany have told me about
        his terrible persecution of those in Jerusalem who are devoted to you. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 9:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cyour holy ones.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "In fact, the high priest has authorized him to seize and imprison
        all those in Damascus who call on your name.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "The Lord <smallcaps>Yahweh</smallcaps>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>,\u201D</smallcaps>
        answered him, <JESUS>\u201CArise and go! I have chosen this man to be my
        special messenger.</JESUS>    <JESUS>He will be brought before kings, before
        many nations, and before the Jewish people to give them the revelation of
        who I am.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 9:15
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic word for \u201C  .      Or \u201Ctool.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "<JESUS>And I will show him how much he is destined to suffer</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>because of his passion for me.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 9:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cexperience.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Ananias left and found the house where Saul was staying. He went
        inside and laid hands on him, saying, \u201CSaul, my brother, the Lord Jesus,
        who appeared to you on the road, has sent me to pray for you so that you
        might see again and be filled to overflowing with the Holy Spirit.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "All at once, the crusty substance that was over Saul\u2019s eyes
        disappeared and he could see perfectly. Immediately, he got up and was baptized. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'After eating a meal, [[COMMENT(0)]] his strength returned. '
      comments:
      - number: 9:19
        content: "  Some Aramaic manuscripts add, \u201CHe accepted the message of
          salvation,\u201D or \u201CHe received the hope\u201D (of the kingdom).     
          The sentence \u201CSaul remained with the disciples for several days\u201D
          has been placed in v.    as a concluding statement of the narrative.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Within the hour [[COMMENT(0)]] he was in the synagogues, preaching
        about Jesus and proclaiming, \u201CJesus is the Son of God!\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 9:20
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic.      Or \u201CThis Man is the
          Son of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Those who heard him were astonished, saying among themselves, \u201CIsn\u2019t
        this the Saul who furiously persecuted those in Jerusalem who called on the
        name of Jesus? Didn\u2019t he come here with permission from the high priest
        to drag them off and take them as prisoners?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: Saul Escapes from Damascus'
      title: Saul Escapes from Damascus
      number: 22
      content: "Saul\u2019s power increased greatly as he became more and more proficient
        in proving that Jesus was the anointed Messiah. Saul remained there for several
        days with the disciples, even though it agitated the Jews of Damascus."
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'As time passed, the Jews plotted together to kill Saul, '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'but it was revealed to him what they were about to do. They closely
        guarded the gates of the city and tracked his every movement so they could
        kill him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: Saul Returns to Jerusalem'
      title: Saul Returns to Jerusalem
      number: 25
      content: "But during the night, some of Saul\u2019s converts helped him escape
        by lowering him down through an opening in the wall, hiding him in a woven
        basket. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 9:25
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'When Saul arrived in Jerusalem, he attempted to introduce himself
        to the fellowship of the believers, but everyone was afraid of him because
        they doubted he was a true disciple. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Barnabas [[COMMENT(0)]] came to his defense and brought him before
        the apostles. Saul shared with them his supernatural experience of seeing
        the Lord, who spoke with him on the road to Damascus. Barnabas also told
        them how boldly Saul preached throughout the city in Jesus\u2019 mighty name."
      comments:
      - number: 9:27
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Then they accepted him as a brother and he remained with them, joining
        them wherever they went in Jerusalem, boldly preaching in the power and authority
        of Jesus. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 9:28
        content: "  Or \u201Cin the name of Jesus.\u201D    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'He openly debated with some of the Jews who had adopted the Greek
        culture, [[COMMENT(0)]] yet they were secretly plotting to murder him. '
      comments:
      - number: 9:29
        content: "  Or \u201CHellenist Jews.\u201D These were Jews who had adopted
          the Greek culture and language, as opposed to the orthodox Jews, who were
          strictly following Hebrew culture. The respected historian Josephus writes
          in AD 44, in his book of Jewish wars, that Greek was not the predominant
          language spoken in Israel. (See    xx, xi, 2.) The Hellenists were Jewish
          immigrants who had lived in Alexandria, Greece, and in Rome. They would
          have learned Greek culture and language as well as Hebrew.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: When the believers discovered their scheme, they smuggled him out
        of the city and took him to Caesarea and then sent him on to Tarsus. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 9:30
        content: "  Tarsus was a city in south-central Turkey, about ten miles from
          the Mediterranean coast. Saul\u2019s family originated from Tarsus, but
          he grew up in Jerusalem as an orthodox Jew.    "
    - name: '31: Peter Heals Aeneas'
      title: Peter Heals Aeneas
      number: 31
      content: After this, the church all over Judea, Galilee, and Samaria experienced
        a season of peace. [[COMMENT(0)]] The congregations grew larger and larger,
        with the believers being empowered and encouraged by the Holy Spirit. They
        worshiped God in wonder and awe,  and walked in the fear of the Lord.
      comments:
      - number: 9:31
        content: "  The \u201Cchurch\u201D in a region is mentioned here, \u201CJudea,
          Galilee, and Samaria.\u201D Even though great cultural distinctions existed
          between them, the Holy Spirit had made them one church.      Implied in
          the Hebraic concept of \u201Cthe fear of the Lord,\u201D which means more
          than just dread or terror. It also includes \u201Cto worship with awe.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "As Peter was ministering [[COMMENT(0)]] from place to place, he visited
        God\u2019s devoted ones in the village of Lydda.   "
      comments:
      - number: 9:32
        content: "  Or \u201Ctraveling.\u201D      Lydda (Aramaic,  ) means \u201Cstrife.\u201D    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'He met a man there named Aeneas [[COMMENT(0)]] who had been paralyzed
        and bedridden for eight years. '
      comments:
      - number: 9:33
        content: "  Aeneas means \u201Cpraise.\u201D \u201CPraise\u201D had been
          paralyzed for eight years. Eight is the number of a new beginning.    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Peter said to him, \u201CAeneas, Jesus the Anointed One instantly
        and divinely heals you. Now, get up and make your bed.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '35: Peter Raises the Dead'
      title: Peter Raises the Dead
      number: 35
      content: All at once he stood to his feet. And when all the people of Lydda
        and Sharon saw him, they became believers in the Lord. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 9:35
        content: "  Or \u201Cthey turned to the Lord.\u201D    "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Now, there was a follower of Jesus who lived in Joppa. Her Aramaic
        name, Tabitha, means \u201Cgazelle.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] She lived her life
        doing kind things for others and serving the poor. "
      comments:
      - number: 9:36
        content: "  Or \u201CDorcas,\u201D which is the Greek word for \u201Cdeer.\u201D
          The name Dorcas is also found in v.    in the Greek.    "
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: But then she became very ill and died. After the disciples prepared
        her body for burial, [[COMMENT(0)]] they laid her in an upstairs room.
      comments:
      - number: 9:37
        content: "  Or \u201Cwashed her body.\u201D By implication they prepared
          her for burial.    "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'When the believers heard that Peter was nearby in Lydda, they sent
        two men with an urgent message for him to come without delay. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'So Peter went with them back to Joppa, and upon arriving they led
        him to the upper room.There were many widows standing next to Peter, weeping.
        One after another showed him the tunics and other garments that Tabitha had
        made to bless others. '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "Peter made them all leave the room. [[COMMENT(0)]] Then he knelt
        down and prayed. Turning to the dead body, he said, \u201CTabitha, rise up!\u201DAt
        once she opened her eyes, and seeing Peter, she sat up. "
      comments:
      - number: 9:40
        content: "  The Greek word used here is  , a strong word that can mean \u201Cdrive
          out\u201D or \u201Ccast out.\u201D    "
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: He took her by the hand and helped her to her feet. Then he called
        for the believers and all the widows to come and see that she was alive!
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'The news spread all over the city of Joppa, and many believed in
        the Lord. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: Peter remained in Joppa for several more days as a guest at the house
        of Simon the tanner. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 9:43
        content: "  Or \u201CSimon Berseus.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: An Angel Comes to Cornelius'
      title: An Angel Comes to Cornelius
      number: 1
      content: 'At that time there was a Roman military officer, Cornelius, who was
        in charge of one hundred men stationed in Caesarea. He was the captain of
        the Italian regiment, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:1
        content: '  Cornelius was a centurion who was in charge of a sixth of a cohort
          of six hundred men. It seems likely that Cornelius was a gentile who had
          converted to Judaism.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: a devout man of extraordinary character who worshiped God and prayed
        regularly, together with all his family. He also had a heart for the poor
        and gave generously to help them.
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "One afternoon about three o\u2019clock, he had an open vision and
        saw the angel of God appear right in front of him, calling out his name,
        \u201CCornelius!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Startled, he was overcome with fear by the sight of the angel. He
        asked, \u201CWhat do you want, Lord?\u201DThe angel said, \u201CAll of your
        prayers and your generosity to the poor have ascended before God as an eternal
        offering. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 10:4
        content: "  Or \u201Cas an offering that he remembers.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Now, send some men to Joppa at once. Have them find a man named Simon
        the Rock, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:5
        content: "  Or \u201CSimon, who is also called Peter\u201D (Rock).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "who is staying as a guest in the home of Simon the tanner, whose
        house is by the sea.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "After the angel left, Cornelius called for two of his servants and
        a trusted, godly soldier who was his personal attach\xE9. "
      comments: []
    - name: "8: Peter\u2019s Trance"
      title: "Peter\u2019s Trance"
      number: 8
      content: He explained to them everything that had just happened and sent them
        off to Joppa.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "The next day around noon, as Cornelius\u2019 men were approaching
        Joppa, Peter went up to the flat roof [[COMMENT(0)]] of the house to pray. "
      comments:
      - number: 10:9
        content: '  This was common when the house was filled with smoke from the
          cooking fires.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He was hungry and wanted to eat, but while lunch was being prepared
        he fell into a trance and entered into another realm. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:10
        content: "  The Greek word for \u201Ctrance\u201D (, from which we get the
          word  ) literally means \u201Cto be taken to another place\u201D (state
          or realm). (See  , Gr. 1611.) He was actually taken into another realm
          as a trance came over him.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'As the heavenly realm opened up, he saw something resembling a large
        linen tablecloth that descended from above, being let down to the earth by
        its four corners. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: As it floated down he saw that it held many kinds of four-footed animals,
        reptiles, and wild birds.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "A voice said to him, \u201CPeter, go and prepare them to be eaten.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Peter replied, \u201CThere\u2019s no way I could do that, Lord, for
        I\u2019ve never eaten anything forbidden or impure according to our Jewish
        laws.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "The voice spoke again. \u201CNothing is unclean if God declares it
        to be clean.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 10:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cpurified.\u201D The meaning of this spiritual vision
          is this: God has declared every human being to be of special worth and
          dignity. The entire world needs the gospel. The four corners of the large
          tablecloth represent the four corners of the earth. The clean animals represent
          God\u2019s people, the Jews, and the unclean speak of the non-Jewish nations.
          This encounter helped Peter understand that God was about to send him off
          with the men who were at the door of the house, even though their religion
          had been labeled \u201Cunclean.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: The vision was repeated three times. [[COMMENT(0)]] Then suddenly
        the linen sheet was snatched back up into heaven.
      comments:
      - number: 10:16
        content: "  Peter\u2019s history contains a number of threes. Peter denied
          he knew Jesus three times, the Lord restored Peter by challenging his love
          three times, and here we have the vision repeated three times.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Peter was so stunned by the vision that he couldn\u2019t stop wondering
        about what all it meant.Meanwhile, Cornelius\u2019 men had learned where
        Peter was staying and at that same moment were standing outside the gate."
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "They called out to those in the house, \u201CIs this where Simon,
        the Rock, [[COMMENT(0)]] is staying?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 10:18
        content: "  Or \u201CPeter.\u201D    "
    - name: '19-20: '
      title: 
      number: 19-20
      content: "As Peter was in deep thought, trying to interpret the vision, the
        Spirit said to him, \u201CGo downstairs now, for three men are looking for
        you. Don\u2019t hesitate to go with them, [[COMMENT(0)]] because I have sent
        them.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "10:19\u201320"
        content: "  Or \u201CDon\u2019t let prejudice keep you from going with them.\u201D
          The Aramaic is literally \u201CDon\u2019t be divided\u201D (in your soul).    "
    - name: '19-20: '
      title: 
      number: 19-20
      content: "As Peter was in deep thought, trying to interpret the vision, the
        Spirit said to him, \u201CGo downstairs now, for three men are looking for
        you. Don\u2019t hesitate to go with them, [[COMMENT(0)]] because I have sent
        them.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: "10:19\u201320"
        content: "  Or \u201CDon\u2019t let prejudice keep you from going with them.\u201D
          The Aramaic is literally \u201CDon\u2019t be divided\u201D (in your soul).    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Peter went downstairs to the men and said, \u201CI believe I\u2019m
        the one you\u2019re looking for. What brings you here?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "They answered, \u201CWe serve Cornelius, a Roman military captain,
        who sent us to find you. He is a devout man of the highest integrity who
        worships [[COMMENT(0)]] God and is respected throughout the Jewish community.
        He was divinely instructed through the appearance of an angel to summon you
        to his home and to listen to the message that you would bring him.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 10:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cfears God.\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: Peter invited them to stay for the night as his guests. The next morning
        they departed, accompanied by some of the believers from Joppa.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'The next day they arrived in Caesarea, where Cornelius was waiting
        anxiously for them and had gathered together all of his relatives and close
        friends. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'The moment Peter walked in the door, Cornelius fell at his feet to
        worship him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "But Peter pulled him to his feet and said, \u201CStand up, for I\u2019m
        only a man and no different from you.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: They talked together and then went inside, where Peter found a large
        gathering waiting to hear his words.
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Peter said to them, \u201CYou all know that it is against the Jewish
        laws for me to associate with or even visit the home of one who is not a
        Jew. Yet God has shown me that I should never view anyone as inferior [[COMMENT(0)]]
        or ritually unclean. "
      comments:
      - number: 10:28
        content: "  Or \u201Cforbidden.\u201D    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "So when you sent for me, I came without objection. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Now, may I ask why you sent for me?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 10:29
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CI was destined to come to you.\u201D    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Cornelius replied, \u201CFour days ago I was fasting [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and praying here in my home at this very hour, three o\u2019clock in the
        afternoon, when a man in glistening clothing suddenly appeared in front of
        my eyes. "
      comments:
      - number: 10:30
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek has no mention of Cornelius
          fasting.    '
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "He said, \u2018Cornelius, God has heard your prayers. Your generosity
        to the poor has been recorded and remembered in God\u2019s presence. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 10:31
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CYour acts of righteousness are offerings
          before God.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "However, you must send for a man named Simon, the Rock, who is staying
        in Joppa as a guest of Simon the tanner, who lives by the sea.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "So I immediately sent my men to bring you here\u2014and you were
        kind enough to come. And now, here we are, all of us in God\u2019s presence,
        anxious to hear the message that God has put into your heart to share with
        us.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Peter said, \u201CNow I know for certain that God doesn\u2019t show
        favoritism with people [[COMMENT(0)]]  but treats everyone on the same basis.   "
      comments:
      - number: 10:34
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CGod is not the God of hypocrites.\u201D     
          The Greek is \u201CGod is not one who receives masks (faces).\u201D God
          doesn\u2019t treat us according to externalities but according to what
          is in our hearts.    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "It makes no difference what race of people one belongs to. If they
        show deep reverence for God, and are committed to doing what\u2019s right,
        they are acceptable before him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'God sent his word to the Jewish people first, [[COMMENT(0)]] announcing
        the wonderful news of hope and peace  through Jesus, the Anointed One, the
        Lord of all. <smallcaps>  </smallcaps><smallcaps>  </smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:36
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CFor the Living Expression was the inheritance
          of the Jewish people.\u201D      Or by inference, \u201Cpeace with God
          through Jesus Christ.\u201D Only the Aramaic has \u201Chope and peace.\u201D     
          The Aramaic is \u201Cwho is Master  of all.\u201D That is, Jesus is Lord,
          not just for the Jewish people but for all people groups. The Aramaic is
          \u201Cwho is Master  of all.\u201D    "
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: You are well aware of all that began in Galilee and spread throughout
        the land of Israel immediately after John preached his message of baptism.
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "\u201CJesus of Nazareth was anointed by God with the Holy Spirit
        and with great power. He did wonderful things for others and divinely healed
        all who were under the tyranny of the devil, [[COMMENT(0)]] for God had anointed
        him. "
      comments:
      - number: 10:38
        content: "  The Greek word for \u201Cdevil\u201D can also be translated \u201Cslanderer-liar.\u201D    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'We apostles were eyewitnesses to all the miracles [[COMMENT(0)]]
        that he performed throughout the land of Israel. Finally, in Jerusalem, he
        was crucified on a cross,   '
      comments:
      - number: 10:39
        content: "  Or \u201Cthings.\u201D By inference, the miracles of healing
          and deliverance.      Or \u201Chung him on a tree and killed him.\u201D
          See  .    "
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'but God raised him from the dead three days later, allowing him to
        be seen openly. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 10:40
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "He didn\u2019t appear to everyone, but he appeared to us, his chosen
        witnesses. He actually ate and drank with us [[COMMENT(0)]] after he rose
        from the dead! "
      comments:
      - number: 10:41
        content: "  The word    means \u201Cto drink together.\u201D It is used only
          here in the New Testament and refers to being refreshed by drinking the
          after-dinner wine together. Jesus celebrated with his disciples after his
          resurrection. He still longs to celebrate with us today.      See  .    "
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: "\u201CJesus ordered us to preach and warn the people [[COMMENT(0)]]
        that God had appointed him to be the judge of the living and the dead. "
      comments:
      - number: 10:42
        content: "  Or \u201CHe commanded us to tell everyone the command.\u201D    "
    - name: '43: The Holy Spirit Falls'
      title: The Holy Spirit Falls
      number: 43
      content: "And not only us, but all of the prophets agree in their writings
        that everyone who believes in him receives complete forgiveness [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of sins through the power of his name.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 10:43
        content: "  Or \u201Ccancellation.\u201D    "
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: 'While Peter was speaking, the Holy Spirit cascaded over all those
        listening to his message. '
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "The Jewish brothers who had accompanied Peter were astounded that
        the gift of the Holy Spirit was poured out on people who weren\u2019t Jews, "
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: for they heard them speaking in supernaturally given languages and
        passionately praising God. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 10:46
        content: '  This is the gentile Pentecost as the Holy Spirit fell on gentile
          believers for the first time, imparting to them the gift of tongues.    '
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "Peter said, \u201CHow could anyone object to these people being baptized?
        For they have received the Holy Spirit just as we have.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: So he instructed them to be baptized in the power of the name of Jesus,
        the Anointed One.After their baptism, they asked Peter to stay with them
        for a few more days. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 10:48
        content: '  At last the gospel broke through and penetrated into the non-Jewish
          cultures and people groups. The Holy Spirit was now uniting Jewish believers
          and non-Jewish believers into one mystical body of Christ on the earth.
          Because of this, there would no longer be a distinction between Jew and
          non-Jew, but one family of believers formed by faith in Jesus Christ. See 
          . The three conversions of the Ethiopian dignitary in ch.  , Saul of Tarsus
          in ch.  , and the Roman officer Cornelius in ch.    prove the power of
          the gospel of God. One could view these three represent all of the sons
          of Noah: Ham (Ethiopian), Shem (Saul), and Japheth (the Roman Cornelius).
          A black man, a Jew, and a gentile were converted!  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ethnic Barriers Broken'
      title: Ethnic Barriers Broken
      number: 1
      content: "The news traveled fast and soon reached the apostles and the believers
        living in Judea that non-Jewish people were also receiving God\u2019s message
        of new life. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'When Peter finally arrived in Jerusalem, the Jewish believers called
        him to task, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CWhy did you stay in the home of people who aren\u2019t Jewish?
        You even ate your meals with them!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Peter explained what had happened, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201COne day when I was in the city of Joppa, while I was praying
        I fell into an ecstatic trance and I went into another realm. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        I saw in a vision something like a linen tablecloth descending out of heaven,
        being let down by its four corners, and it got close to me. "
      comments:
      - number: 11:5
        content: '  See footnote on  .    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'As I examined it I saw many four-footed animals, wild animals, reptiles,
        and wild birds. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then I heard a voice say to me, \u2018Get up, Peter. Kill and eat
        them.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CI said, \u2018I can\u2019t do that, Lord! For I\u2019ve never
        eaten anything that is forbidden or impure according to our Jewish laws.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CThe voice spoke to me again, saying, \u2018Nothing is unclean
        if God declares it to be clean.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CThe vision repeated itself three times. Then suddenly the linen
        sheet was snatched back up into heaven. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'At that moment three men from Caesarea, who had been sent for me,
        approached the house where I was staying. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The Spirit told me to accompany them with no questions asked. These
        six brothers here with me made the trip, and we entered into the home of
        the man who had sent for me. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'He shared with us about the angel who appeared to him and told him
        to send messengers to Joppa to find Simon, the Rock. The angel had told him, '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u2018He will tell you and your family the message of how you can
        be saved!\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CShortly after I began to speak, the Holy Spirit was poured
        out upon them, just like what happened to us at the beginning. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "And I remembered the words the Lord had told us: <JESUS>\u2018John
        immersed you in water, but you will be immersed in the Holy Spirit.\u2019</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So I concluded that if God is pleased to give them the same gift
        of the Holy Spirit that he gave us after they believed in the Lord Jesus
        Christ, who am I to stand in the way of God?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: The Church at Antioch'
      title: The Church at Antioch
      number: 18
      content: "When they heard this, their objections were put to rest and they
        all glorified God, saying, \u201CLook what God has done! He\u2019s giving
        the gift of repentance that leads to life to people who aren\u2019t even
        Jews.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Because of the persecution triggered by Stephen\u2019s death in Jerusalem,
        many of the believers were scattered. Some reached as far as the coast of
        Lebanon, [[COMMENT(0)]] the island of Cyprus, and Antioch of Syria, but they
        were still only preaching the word to Jews. "
      comments:
      - number: 11:19
        content: "  Or \u201CPhoenicia.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'However, some of the believers from Cyprus and Cyrene, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        who had come to Antioch in Syria,  preached to the non-Jews living there,
        proclaiming the message of salvation in the Lord Jesus.   '
      comments:
      - number: 11:20
        content: '  A city on the coast of Libya. Some have linked the man who carried
          the cross of Jesus, Simon of Cyrene, to this group of missionary evangelists.     
          Antioch was important from both a commercial and a military point of view.
          It was the seat of the Roman governor-general, with large garrisons and
          military supplies stored there. It was also a center of art and culture,
          known for its beauty and recognized as the capital of the Syrian kingdom.
          The church prospered greatly in Antioch, and it became a Christian hub
          and headquarters for the apostles. For many centuries in church history,
          Antioch remained a strong witness for evangelization, sending missionaries
          into Persia and throughout the Roman Empire.      In the early days of
          the church, every believer was a missionary. There was a great cost involved
          with following Christ. They laid their lives down to serve him and to make
          him known among the nations. Not just the apostles, but all of the believers
          did their part in spreading the teachings of Jesus wherever they went.    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: The mighty power of the Lord was with them as they ministered, and
        a large number of people believed and turned their hearts to the Lord.
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'News of what was happening in Antioch reached the church of Jerusalem,
        so the apostles sent Barnabas to Antioch as their emissary. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "When he got there and witnessed for himself God\u2019s marvelous
        grace, he was enthused and overjoyed. He encouraged [[COMMENT(0)]] the believers
        to remain faithful and cling to the Lord with passionate hearts.   "
      comments:
      - number: 11:23
        content: "  Barnabas was given the nickname \u201CEncourager.\u201D See 
          .      The Aramaic is \u201CHe begged them to imitate the Lord with all
          their hearts.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: Barnabas was a good man, [[COMMENT(0)]] full of the Spirit of holiness,
        and he exuded a life of faith. Because of his ministry even more crowds of
        people were brought to the Lord!
      comments:
      - number: 11:24
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CHe was a blessed man.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'Barnabas left for Tarsus to find Saul and bring him back to Antioch. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: Agabus Prophesies a Coming Famine'
      title: Agabus Prophesies a Coming Famine
      number: 26
      content: "Together Saul and Barnabas ministered there for a full year, equipping
        the growing church and teaching the vast number of new converts. It was in
        Antioch that the followers of Jesus were first revealed as \u201Canointed
        ones.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 11:26
        content: "  Or \u201CChristians.\u201D The Greek word    means \u201Csupernaturally
          revealed\u201D (imparted), more than simply \u201Ccalled.\u201D It was
          first in Antioch that the revelation came that the believers were anointed
          ones. See also  , where the term is used as God giving revelation in a
          dream.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'At that time there were prophets in the church of Jerusalem, and
        some of them came to Antioch. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'One of them, named Agabus, stood up in one of the meetings and prophesied
        by the Holy Spirit that a severe famine was about to come over Israel. (This
        prophecy was fulfilled during the reign of Claudius Caesar.) [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 11:28
        content: "  This would have been about AD 45\u201346.    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'So they determined that each believer, according to his or her ability,
        would give an offering to send as relief to the brothers living in Judea. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'They set aside the gifts and entrusted the funds to Barnabas and
        Saul to take to the elders [[COMMENT(0)]] of the church in Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: 11:30
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cpriests.\u201D      Upon hearing the prophecy
          of a famine coming, the church of Antioch determined to receive an offering
          for the Judean believers, for the gospel came to them from Jerusalem. They
          gave back to the place where the gospel was sent to them.  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Peter\u2019s Miraculous Escape from Prison"
      title: "Peter\u2019s Miraculous Escape from Prison"
      number: 1
      content: 'During this period King Herod [[COMMENT(0)]] incited persecution
        against the church, causing great harm to the believers. '
      comments:
      - number: 12:1
        content: "  Or \u201CKing Herod Agrippa.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "He even had the apostle Jacob, [[COMMENT(0)]] John\u2019s brother,
        beheaded.   "
      comments:
      - number: 12:2
        content: "  Or \u201CJames.\u201D Both Greek and Aramaic leave the Hebrew
          name as it is, Jacob. According to the Gospels, Jacob (James) and John
          were the first two disciples of Jesus, and Jacob was the first apostle
          to be martyred.      Or \u201Cexecuted by the sword.\u201D    "
    - name: '3-4: '
      title: 
      number: 3-4
      content: 'When Herod realized how much this pleased the Jewish leaders, he
        had Peter arrested and thrown into prison during the Feast of Passover. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Sixteen soldiers were assigned to guard him until Herod could bring him to
        public trial, immediately after the Passover celebrations were over. '
      comments:
      - number: "12:3\u20134"
        content: '  These events most likely took place in AD 42 or 43.    '
    - name: '3-4: '
      title: 
      number: 3-4
      content: 'When Herod realized how much this pleased the Jewish leaders, he
        had Peter arrested and thrown into prison during the Feast of Passover. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Sixteen soldiers were assigned to guard him until Herod could bring him to
        public trial, immediately after the Passover celebrations were over. '
      comments:
      - number: "12:3\u20134"
        content: '  These events most likely took place in AD 42 or 43.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: The church went into a season of intense intercession, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        asking God to free him.
      comments:
      - number: 12:5
        content: "  The Greek phrase used here for \u201Cintense intercession\u201D
          means \u201Cto stretch tightly in prayer.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The night before Herod planned to bring him to trial, he made sure
        that Peter was securely bound with two chains. Peter was sound asleep between
        two soldiers, with additional guards stationed outside his cell door, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "when all at once an angel of the Lord appeared, filling his prison
        cell with a brilliant light. The angel struck Peter on the side [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to awaken him and said, \u201CHurry up! Let\u2019s go!\u201D Instantly the
        chains fell off his wrists. "
      comments:
      - number: 12:7
        content: "  The word translated \u201Cstruck\u201D is the same Greek word
          used for Jesus being \u201Cstruck\u201D for our sins (). Jesus was pierced
          in his side to awaken hearts to God. Peter was awakened from his sleep
          by an angel who struck him on his side.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "The angel told him, \u201CGet dressed. Put on your sandals, bring
        your cloak, and follow me.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Peter quickly left the cell and followed the angel, even though he
        thought it was only a dream or a vision, for it seemed unreal\u2014he couldn\u2019t
        believe it was really happening! "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "They walked unseen past the first guard post and then the second
        before coming to the iron gate that leads to the city\u2014and the gate swung
        open all by itself right in front of them!They went out into the city and
        were walking down a narrow street when all of a sudden the angel disappeared. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "That\u2019s when Peter realized that he wasn\u2019t having a dream!
        He said to himself, \u201CThis is really happening! The Lord sent his angel
        to rescue me from the clutches of Herod and from what the Jewish leaders
        planned to do to me.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'When he realized this, he decided to go to the home of Mary [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and her son John Mark. The house was filled with people praying. '
      comments:
      - number: 12:12
        content: '  This Mary was a relative of Barnabas. See  .    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'When he knocked on the door to the courtyard, a young servant girl
        named Rose [[COMMENT(0)]] got up to see who it was. '
      comments:
      - number: 12:13
        content: "  Or \u201CRhoda.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "When she recognized Peter\u2019s voice, she was so excited that she
        forgot to open the door, but ran back inside the house to announce, \u201CPeter
        is standing outside!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CAre you crazy?\u201D they said to her. But when she kept insisting,
        they answered, \u201CWell, it must be his angel.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: Meanwhile, Peter was still outside, knocking on the door. When they
        finally opened it, they were shocked to find Peter standing there.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "He signaled for them to be quiet as he shared with them the miraculous
        way the Lord brought him out of prison. Before he left he said, \u201CMake
        sure you let Jacob [[COMMENT(0)]] and all of the other believers know what
        has happened.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 12:17
        content: '  This was Jacob (James), the brother of Jesus.    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "At the first sign of daylight, the prison guards were in a tremendous
        uproar because of Peter\u2019s disappearance. Herod ordered a thorough search
        for him, but no one could find him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: After he interrogated the guards, he ordered them executed. Then Herod
        left the province of Judea for Caesarea and stayed there for a period of
        time.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: Now, during those days, Herod was engaged in a violent dispute with
        the people of Tyre and Sidon. [[COMMENT(0)]] So they sent a united delegation
        to Caesarea to appeal to him and reconcile their differences  with the king,
        for Herod controlled their food supply. First they enlisted the support of
        his trusted personal assistant, Blastus, who secured them an appointment
        with the king.
      comments:
      - number: 12:20
        content: "  Tyre and Sidon are coastal cities in Lebanon, north of Israel.     
          The Aramaic can also be translated \u201CThey wanted cultivated land,\u201D
          which makes sense if their food supply was running out.    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'On the chosen day, Herod came before them, arrayed in his regal robes.
        Sitting on his elevated throne, he delivered a stirring public address to
        the people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "At its conclusion the people gave him a round of applause. The crowd
        shouted, \u201CThese are the words of a god, not a man!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Immediately, an angel of the Lord struck Herod with a sickness, an
        infestation of worms, because he accepted the people\u2019s worship and didn\u2019t
        give the glory to God, and he died. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "But the hope of God\u2019s kingdom [[COMMENT(0)]] kept spreading
        and multiplying everywhere!"
      comments:
      - number: 12:24
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cthe word.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: After Barnabas and Saul had delivered the charitable offering for
        relief, they left Jerusalem, bringing with them a disciple named Mark (who
        was also known as John). [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 12:25
        content: '  This is the Mark who wrote the second Gospel included in our
          New Testament. John (or  ) was his Jewish name; Marcus was his Roman name.
          Because he once abandoned Paul during a missionary journey, Paul refused
          to take him with him again. But later, Mark and Paul were fully restored
          in their ministry together. See  .  '
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Saul and Barnabas Sent Out as Apostles'
      title: Saul and Barnabas Sent Out as Apostles
      number: 1
      content: 'In the church at Antioch there were a number of prophets and teachers
        of the Word, including Barnabas, Simeon from Niger, [[COMMENT(0)]] Lucius
        the Libyan, Manean (the childhood companion of King Herod Antipas),  and
        Saul. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:1
        content: "  The Aramaic word    means \u201Csomeone who works with wood,
          a carpenter.\u201D The Latin word    means \u201Cblack.\u201D      Or \u201Cwho
          was like a brother to Herod the tetrarch.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "While they were worshiping as priests [[COMMENT(0)]] before the Lord
        in prayer and fasting, the Holy Spirit said,  \u201CI have called Barnabas
        and Saul to do an important work for me. Now, release them  to go and fulfill
        it.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 13:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cserving the Lord.\u201D The Greek word used here is
          also used for priestly duties.      Here we see the Lord of the harvest,
          the Holy Spirit, sending out laborers into the harvest field. The Holy
          Spirit speaks in many different ways. Perhaps he spoke a prophecy through
          one of the prophets in the church, or a divine voice may have interrupted
          their worship. God\u2019s Spirit still speaks today in any way he chooses.     
          Or \u201Cappoint them.\u201D The Greek word used here is found in the Septuagint
          of    for consecrating Levites for God\u2019s service as priests.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: So after they had fasted and prayed, they laid hands on them and sent
        them off. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 13:3
        content: "  Or \u201Cdispatched them\u201D (a military term). This was the
          commissioning of Barnabas and Saul as apostles. The word    means \u201Csent
          one.\u201D They were sent by the Holy Spirit and by the church and released
          as missionaries. The New Testament shows there were many other apostles
          besides the Twelve. See also  .    "
    - name: '4-5: '
      title: 
      number: 4-5
      content: 'So Saul and Barnabas, and their assistant Mark (known as John), were
        directed by the Holy Spirit to go to Seleucia, [[COMMENT(0)]] and from there
        they sailed to Cyprus.  When they arrived at Salamis,  they went to the synagogues
        and declared the Word of God. '
      comments:
      - number: "13:4\u20135"
        content: "  Implied in the text. Seleucia (modern-day Samandag) was a coastal
          city in Syria from which Paul and Barnabas left with John Mark for their
          first missionary journey in AD 49. Seleucia means \u201Cwhite light.\u201D     
          Cyprus was the home of Barnabas.      Salamis is a city on the southeastern
          coast of Cyprus. Salamis means \u201Cin the middle of salty water.\u201D    "
    - name: '4-5: '
      title: 
      number: 4-5
      content: 'So Saul and Barnabas, and their assistant Mark (known as John), were
        directed by the Holy Spirit to go to Seleucia, [[COMMENT(0)]] and from there
        they sailed to Cyprus.  When they arrived at Salamis,  they went to the synagogues
        and declared the Word of God. '
      comments:
      - number: "13:4\u20135"
        content: "  Implied in the text. Seleucia (modern-day Samandag) was a coastal
          city in Syria from which Paul and Barnabas left with John Mark for their
          first missionary journey in AD 49. Seleucia means \u201Cwhite light.\u201D     
          Cyprus was the home of Barnabas.      Salamis is a city on the southeastern
          coast of Cyprus. Salamis means \u201Cin the middle of salty water.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "From there they crossed the island as far as Paphos, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        where they encountered a Jewish false prophet, a sorcerer named Elymas, 
        who also went by the name of \u201Cson of Jesus.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 13:6
        content: "  Paphos is a city on the southwestern coast of Cyprus.    means
          \u201Cboiling hot.\u201D      Or \u201Cspiritual advisor.\u201D The Greek
          word    is often translated \u201Castrologer.\u201D Although the text does
          not give us his name, Elymas, until v.  , it is included here for the sake
          of the English narrative.      Or \u201CBar-Jesus\u201D (son of Joshua).
          The Aramaic is \u201CBar-Shuma.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "He had gained influence as the spiritual advisor to the regional
        governor, Sergius Paulus, considered by many to be a wise and intelligent
        leader. The governor requested a meeting with Barnabas and Saul because he
        wanted to hear the message of God\u2019s word. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 13:7
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cthe manifestation of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But Elymas, whose name means \u201Csorcerer,\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]
        stood up against them and tried to prevent the governor from believing their
        message."
      comments:
      - number: 13:8
        content: "  The Aramaic name Elymas means \u201Cmagician\u201D or \u201Csorcerer.\u201D
          This would be similar to the Arabic name Alumas, which also means \u201Cmagician.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Saul, also known as Paul, [[COMMENT(0)]] stared into his eyes and
        rebuked him. Filled with the Holy Spirit, he said, '
      comments:
      - number: 13:9
        content: "  From here on in Acts, Saul is only referred to as Paul. Saul
          means \u201Csought after,\u201D and Paul means \u201Clittle.\u201D The
          name change is descriptive of what happened within Paul, leaving behind
          greatness in his own eyes and being content to be insignificant. This is
          the journey every believer must take.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CYou son of the devil! [[COMMENT(0)]] You are full of every
        form of fraud and deceit and an enemy of all that is right. When will you
        stop perverting the truth of God into lies? "
      comments:
      - number: 13:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cson of the accuser.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "At this very moment the hand of God\u2019s judgment comes down upon
        you and you will be blind\u2014so blind you won\u2019t even be able to see
        the light of the sun.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]As Paul spoke these words, a shadowy
        mist  and darkness came over the sorcerer, leaving him blind and groping
        about, begging someone to lead him around by the hand. "
      comments:
      - number: 13:11
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cuntil the end of the age.\u201D      The
          Aramaic can be translated \u201Cgloom.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: Paul and Barnabas at Antioch in Turkey'
      title: Paul and Barnabas at Antioch in Turkey
      number: 12
      content: When the governor witnessed this, he believed and was awestruck by
        the power of the message of the Lord.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Paul and his companions sailed from the Cyprus port of Paphos to
        Perga in southern Turkey. [[COMMENT(0)]] John left them  there and returned
        to Jerusalem '
      comments:
      - number: 13:13
        content: "  Or \u201CPamphylia,\u201D which may mean \u201Ca place of mingled
          races.\u201D It is a region in southern Turkey.      The sudden departure
          of John from the team became an issue between Paul and Barnabas. See  .    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'as they journeyed on to the city of Antioch in the region of Pisidia.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]On the Sabbath they went into the synagogue and took their
        seats. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:14
        content: '  Antioch in the region of Pisidia is situated in the Sultandag
          Mountains about one hundred miles north of Perga. This would have been
          an arduous journey from the sea into the mountains. God was directing his
          missionaries where to go.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "After the reading from the scrolls of the books of Moses and the
        prophets, the leader of the meeting [[COMMENT(0)]] sent Paul and Barnabas
        a message, saying, \u201CBrothers, do you have a word of encouragement to
        share with us? If so, please feel free to give it.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 13:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cpresident of the synagogue.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Paul stood and motioned that he had something to say. He said, \u201CListen,
        all of you Jews and non-Jews who worship God. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'The God of Israel divinely chose our ancestors to be his people.
        While they were enslaved in Egypt, he made them great, both in numbers and
        in strength, until he unveiled his mighty power and led them out of bondage.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 13:17
        content: '  See  ;  .    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'For nearly forty years, he nourished them in the wilderness. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 13:18
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic and some Greek manuscripts. See
          also  ;  .    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'He was the one who destroyed the seven nations inhabiting the land
        of Canaan [[COMMENT(0)]] and afterward gave the land to his people as their
        inheritance. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:19
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "This took about four hundred and fifty years. [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CThen
        God raised up deliverers for the people until the time of the prophet Samuel. "
      comments:
      - number: 13:20
        content: "  There is much debate over where this clause fits. It is possible
          that it would go with the next sentence, \u201CFor four hundred and fifty
          years God raised up deliverers.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'The people craved for a king, so God gave them one from the tribe
        of Benjamin: Saul, the son of Kish, who ruled for forty years. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "After removing him, God raised up David to be king, for God said
        of him, \u2018I have found in David, son of Jesse, a man who always pursues
        my heart [[COMMENT(0)]] and will accomplish all that I have destined him
        to do.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 13:22
        content: "  See  ;  .      Or \u201Che will do all my pleasure.\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CFrom David\u2019s lineage God brought Israel a Savior, just
        as he promised. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'So before Jesus appeared, John preached the message of a baptism
        of repentance [[COMMENT(0)]] to prepare all of Israel. '
      comments:
      - number: 13:24
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe baptism of grace.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "As John was about to finish his mission, he said repeatedly, \u2018If
        you think that I am the one to come, you\u2019re mistaken. He will come after
        me, and I don\u2019t even deserve to stoop down and untie his sandals!\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CFellow Jews, Abraham\u2019s descendants, and all those among
        you who worship and reverence God, this message of life [[COMMENT(0)]] has
        been sent for us all to hear. "
      comments:
      - number: 13:26
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is, \u201Cthe message
          of salvation.\u201D See  .    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "But the people of Jerusalem and their leaders didn\u2019t realize
        who he was, nor did they understand the prophecies written of him. Yet they
        fulfilled those very prophecies, which they read week after week in their
        meetings, by condemning him to death. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'Even though they could come up with no legal grounds for the death
        sentence, they pleaded with Pilate to have him executed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "And they did to him all that was prophesied they would do.\u201CThen
        they took him down from the cross and laid him in a tomb. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'But God raised him from the dead! '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: And for many days afterward he appeared on numerous occasions to his
        disciples who knew him well and had followed him from Galilee to Jerusalem.
        Those disciples are now his witnesses, [[COMMENT(0)]] telling the people
        the truth about him.
      comments:
      - number: 13:31
        content: "  The Greek word for \u201Cwitnesses\u201D can also be translated
          \u201Cmartyrs.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "\u201CSo here we are to share with you some wonderful news! The promise
        God made to our forefathers "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "has now been fulfilled for us, their children. For God has raised
        Jesus from the dead, as it says in Psalms:\u2018Today I reveal you as my
        Son, and I as your Father.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 13:33
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CGod had promised to not let him decay in the tomb or face destruction
        again, so God raised him from the dead. He gave this promise in the Psalms:\u2018I
        will give to you [[COMMENT(0)]] what I gave to David:Faithful mercies  that
        you can trust.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 13:34
        content: "  The Greek is plural, \u201Cyou all,\u201D or \u201Cto you and
          yours.\u201D      Or \u201Cdecrees.\u201D See  .      The Aramaic is \u201CI
          will give to you the grace [favor] I gave to faithful David.\u201D    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "\u201CHe explains it further in another Psalm:\u2018You will not
        allow your holy oneto experience bodily decay.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 13:35
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "\u201CThis cannot be a reference to David, for after he passionately
        served God\u2019s purpose for his generation, he died. He was buried with
        his ancestors and his body experienced decay. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: But the one whom God raised from the dead has never experienced corruption
        in any form.
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "\u201CSo listen, friends! Through this Jesus, the forgiveness [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of sins is offered to you. "
      comments:
      - number: 13:38
        content: "  Or \u201Ccancellation.\u201D    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "Everyone who believes in him is set free from sin and guilt\u2014something
        the law of Moses had no power to do. "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'So be very careful that what the prophets warned about does not happen
        to you:'
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: "\u2018Be amazed and in agony, you scoffers! [[COMMENT(0)]]For in
        your day I will do something so wonderfulthat when I perform mighty deeds
        among you,you won\u2019t even believe that it was I who did it!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 13:41
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CBe amazed
          and perish, you scoffers.\u201D      As translated from the Aramaic. The
          Greek text seems to quote from the Septuagint version of  , \u201CI am
          doing a work in your days that you won\u2019t believe even when it is announced
          to you.\u201D    "
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'As Paul and Barnabas started to leave, the people pleaded with them
        to share more about these things on the next Sabbath day. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "When the meeting had finally broken up, many of those in attendance,
        both Jews and converts to Judaism, tagged along with Paul and Barnabas, who
        continued to persuade them to go deeper in their understanding of God\u2019s
        grace."
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: 'The following week, nearly everyone in the city gathered to hear
        the word of God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: When the Jewish leaders saw the size of the crowds, vicious jealousy
        filled their hearts and they rose up to oppose what Paul was teaching. They
        insulted him [[COMMENT(0)]] and argued with him over everything he said.
      comments:
      - number: 13:45
        content: "  Or \u201Cblasphemed.\u201D    "
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "Yet Paul and Barnabas did not back down. Filled with courage, they
        boldly replied, \u201CWe were compelled to bring God\u2019s message [[COMMENT(0)]]
        first to you Jews. But seeing you\u2019ve rejected this message and refuse
        to embrace eternal life,  we will focus instead on the nations and offer
        it to them. "
      comments:
      - number: 13:46
        content: "  Or \u201Cword.\u201D      Or \u201CYou view yourselves as unworthy
          of eternal life.\u201D    "
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "This will fulfill what the Lord has commanded us:\u2018I have destined
        you to becomea beacon light for the nationsand release salvation to the ends
        of the earth!\u2019&nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 13:47
        content: '  See  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'When the non-Jewish people in the crowd heard these words, they were
        thrilled and they honored [[COMMENT(0)]] the word of the Lord. All who believed
        that they were destined to experience eternal life received the message.   '
      comments:
      - number: 13:48
        content: "  Or \u201Cpraised.\u201D      As translated from the Aramaic.
          The Greek is \u201CThose who were appointed to experience eternal life
          believed.\u201D The Greek word for \u201Cappointed\u201D can also be translated
          \u201Cstationed in battle order.\u201D    "
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "God\u2019s word spread like wildfire throughout the entire region."
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: 'The Jewish leaders stirred up a violent mob against Paul and Barnabas,
        including many prominent and wealthy people of the city. They persecuted
        them and ran them out of town. '
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: 'As they left, they shook the dust off their feet as a sign of protest
        against them, and they went on to the city of Iconium. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 13:51
        content: "  This is present-day Konya, a large city about sixty-two miles
          (one hundred kilometers) from Antioch. This journey would have taken a
          number of days. Iconium means \u201Csmall image\u201D (idol). In Israel,
          Iconium is a girl\u2019s name that means \u201Ccoming.\u201D  "
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: They left the new converts in Antioch overflowing with the joy of
        the Holy Spirit.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Miracles and Revival in Iconium'
      title: Miracles and Revival in Iconium
      number: 1
      content: When Paul and Barnabas arrived at Iconium, the same thing happened
        there. They went, as they always did, to the synagogue and preached to the
        people with such power that a large crowd of both Jews and non-Jews believed.
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Some of the Jews refused to believe, and they began to poison the
        minds [[COMMENT(0)]] of the non-Jews to discredit the believers. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cembittered their souls.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Yet Paul and Barnabas stayed there for a long time, preaching boldly
        and fearlessly about the Lord. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>,\u201D referring
        to Jesus Christ.</smallcaps> Many trusted in the Lord, for he backed up his
        message  of grace  with miracles, signs, and wonders performed by the apostles."
      comments:
      - number: 14:3
        content: "  The Aramaic uses the phrase \u201Cthe Lord        The Aramaic
          is \u201Cmanifestation of grace.\u201D      The Greek word for grace, 
          , means \u201Cthat which brings delight, joy, pleasure, and sweetness.\u201D
          (See  , Gr. 5485.)    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The people of the city were split over the issue. Some sided with
        the apostles, and others with the Jews who refused to believe. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Eventually, all the opposition factions came together, with their
        leaders devising a plot [[COMMENT(0)]] to harm Paul and Barnabas and stone
        them to death. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:5
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CThey issued a decree\u201D (death sentence).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'When the apostles learned about this, [[COMMENT(0)]] they escaped
        to the region of Lyconia,  to the cities of Lystra  and Derbe  and the nearby
        villages. '
      comments:
      - number: 14:6
        content: "  Although not clearly stated, it is possible that it was by supernatural
          revelation that Paul and Barnabas learned of the plot to kill them.     
          Lyconia means \u201Cland of the wolf.\u201D      Lystra means \u201Cransomed\u201D
          or \u201Cset free.\u201D      Derbe means \u201Ctanner\u201D or \u201Cone
          who covers with skins.\u201D The journey from Iconium to these cities would
          have been about twenty-two miles (thirty-five kilometers).    "
    - name: '7: Paul and Barnabas Preach at Lystra'
      title: Paul and Barnabas Preach at Lystra
      number: 7
      content: And they continued to preach the hope of the gospel. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 14:7
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cthe good news.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'In Lystra, Paul and Barnabas encountered a man who from birth had
        never walked, for he was crippled in his feet. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'He listened carefully to Paul as he preached. All of a sudden, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Paul discerned that this man had faith in his heart to be healed.   '
      comments:
      - number: 14:9
        content: "  There is an implication in the Greek that Paul was watching this
          man and waited until he saw faith rise in the man\u2019s heart for his
          healing.      The same phrase, \u201Cto be healed,\u201D is consistently
          translated elsewhere in the New Testament as \u201Cto be saved.\u201D To
          be saved and to be healed are synonymous.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "So he shouted, \u201CYou! In the name of our Lord Jesus, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        stand up on your feet!\u201D The man instantly jumped to his feet, stood
        for the first time in his life, and walked!"
      comments:
      - number: 14:10
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic. This clause is absent in the
          Greek.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "When the crowds saw the miracle Paul had done, they shouted in their
        own language, [[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CThe gods have come down to us as men!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 14:11
        content: '  That is, the Lyconian language.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "They addressed Barnabas as \u201CZeus\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] and Paul
        as \u201CHermes,\u201D  because he was the spokesman."
      comments:
      - number: 14:12
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe master of deities,\u201D and the Latin
          is \u201CJupiter.\u201D Also found in v.  .      Hermes was considered
          to be the messenger god, whom the Romans called Mercury. In Ovid\u2019s
          famous story  , there is an account of Philemon and Baucis from Lystra,
          who took in two strangers (Zeus and Hermes) and welcomed them into their
          home. But the rest of the village rejected them, and for that the village
          was destroyed\u2014only Philemon and Baucis survived. That story was no
          doubt in the minds of the people when they welcomed Barnabas and Paul.
          They did not want to make the same mistake as their ancestors. (See Ovid,   
          8.611\u2013725.) Archeologists have found a stone altar near Lystra with
          an inscription dedicating it to Zeus and Hermes.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: Now, outside of the city stood the temple of Zeus. The priest of the
        temple, in order to honor Paul and Barnabas, brought bulls with wreaths of
        flowers draped on them to the gates of the courtyard where they were staying.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] The crowds clamored to offer them as sacrifices to the apostles.
        He even brought flower wreaths as crowns to place on their heads.
      comments:
      - number: 14:13
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is ambiguous and could
          be \u201Cthe gates of the temple\u201D or \u201Cthe gates of the city.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'When the apostles [[COMMENT(0)]] understood what was happening, they
        were mortified and tore their clothes as a sign of dismay. They rushed into
        the crowd and shouted, '
      comments:
      - number: 14:14
        content: "  The book of Acts clearly states that there were more than twelve
          apostles who were recognized by the church. Barnabas is described multiple
          times as an apostle.    says that apostles and prophets will minister and
          equip the body of Christ until we are complete and restored into Christ\u2019s
          fullness.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CPeople, what are you doing? We\u2019re only weak human beings
        like everyone else. This is why we\u2019ve come to tell you the good news,
        so that you would turn away from these worthless myths  [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        turn to the living God. He is the Creator of all things: the earth, the heavens,
        the sea, and everything they contain. "
      comments:
      - number: 14:15
        content: "  Implied in the text, which is simply \u201Cthings.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'In previous generations he allowed the nations to pursue their own
        ways, '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "yet he has never left himself without clear evidence of his goodness.
        For he blesses us with rain from heaven and seasons of fruitful harvests,
        and he nourishes us with food to meet our needs. He satisfies our lives,
        and euphoria [[COMMENT(0)]] fills our hearts.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 14:17
        content: '  See footnote on  .    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: Even after saying these things, they were barely able to restrain
        the people from offering sacrifices to them.
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: Some of the Jews who had opposed Paul and Barnabas in Antioch and
        Iconium arrived and stirred up the crowd against them. They stoned Paul and
        dragged his body outside the city and left him for dead.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When the believers encircled Paul\u2019s body, he miraculously stood
        up! [[COMMENT(0)]] Paul stood and immediately went back into the city. The
        next day he left with Barnabas for Derbe."
      comments:
      - number: 14:20
        content: '  The Greek word used here,  , is used twenty-seven times in the
          New Testament for people being raised from the dead.    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'After preaching the wonderful news of the gospel there and winning
        a large number of followers to Jesus, they retraced their steps and revisited
        Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "At each place they went, they strengthened the lives of the believers
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and encouraged them to go deeper in their faith. And they
        taught them, \u201CIt is necessary for us to enter into the realm of God\u2019s
        kingdom, because that\u2019s the only way we will endure our many trials
        and persecutions.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 14:22
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthey confirmed their spirit of discipleship.\u201D     
          That is, the only way to avoid the oppression of the age is to enter deeper
          into God\u2019s kingdom realm. An alternate translation would be \u201CThrough
          great tribulation we enter into God\u2019s kingdom realm.\u201D Neither
          translation of this sentence implies a future kingdom, but a kingdom realm
          that is presently accessible.    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: Paul and Barnabas ordained leaders, known as elders, from among the
        congregations in every church they visited. [[COMMENT(0)]] After prayer and
        fasting, they publicly committed them into the care and protection of the
        Lord of their faith.
      comments:
      - number: 14:23
        content: "  The appointment of elders among the people dates back to the
          days of Moses in the wilderness. See  , where the word used to describe
          these leaders is  , or \u201Cmighty men of valor.\u201D The word    is
          also used for the radiant church (commonly known as the \u201Cvirtuous
          woman\u201D found in  ). These elders were the pastors and leaders of the
          churches, ordained by the apostles. See also  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'After passing through different regions of central Turkey, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 14:24
        content: "  Or \u201CAfter they had passed through Pisidia, they went into
          Pamphylia.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "they went to the city of Perga, preaching the life-giving message
        of the Lord. [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>,\u201D as translated from the Aramaic.
        The Greek is \u201Cthe word of the Lord.\u201D</smallcaps> Afterward they
        journeyed down to the coast at Antalya,   "
      comments:
      - number: 14:25
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe manifestation of Lord        Or \u201CAttalia.\u201D
          Antalya is a city on the southwestern coast of Turkey.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "and from there they sailed back to Antioch.With their mission complete,
        they returned to the church where they had originally been sent out as missionaries,
        for it was in Antioch where they had been handed over to God\u2019s powerful
        grace. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'When they arrived in Antioch, they gathered the church together and
        shared with them all of the wonderful works God had done through them and
        how God had opened the door of faith for the non-Jews to enter in. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: Afterward, Paul and Barnabas stayed there for a long time in fellowship
        with the believers. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 14:28
        content: "  This would have been AD 47\u201348, when Paul wrote his letter
          to the Galatians, the region they had visited during their first missionary
          journey. Antioch of Syria is here seen as the center of the missionary
          enterprise as the church hosts the anointed apostles Paul and Barnabas,
          who taught the church during their time there. For many centuries Antioch
          of Syria was considered a major Christian center. Into the fourth century,
          it was noted as having schools of theology and institutions of learning.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Jerusalem Council of Apostles'
      title: The Jerusalem Council of Apostles
      number: 1
      content: "While Paul and Barnabas were in Antioch, some false teachers came
        from Judea to trouble the believers. They taught, \u201CUnless you are circumcised,
        as the law of Moses requires, you cannot be saved.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'This sparked a fierce argument between the false teachers and Paul
        and Barnabas. So the church appointed a delegation of believers, including
        Paul and Barnabas, to go to Jerusalem to meet with the apostles and elders
        of the church and resolve this issue. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: So the church sent them on their way.As they passed through Lebanon
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and Samaria, they stopped to share with the believers how
        God was converting many from among the non-Jewish people.  Hearing this report
        brought great joy to all the churches.
      comments:
      - number: 15:3
        content: "  Or \u201CPhoenicia.\u201D      The Aramaic is \u201Cthe reconciliation
          of the gentiles.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'When they finally arrived in Jerusalem, Paul and Barnabas were welcomed
        by the church, the apostles, and the elders. They explained to them everything
        God had done among them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "But some of the believers who were of the religious group called
        \u201Cseparated ones\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] were insistent, saying, \u201CWe
        must continue the custom of circumcision and require that the people keep 
        the law of Moses.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 15:5
        content: "  Or \u201CPharisees.\u201D The legalism of the Pharisees continued
          even among some believers, who were still bound in the expressions of external
          religion.      The Aramaic is \u201Cto put a fence around the Torah\u201D;
          that is, to guard the Torah and keep it as a sacred duty to man. The apostolic
          council of    makes it clear that gentile believers had no obligation to
          keep that \u201Cfence\u201D around the Torah (observing the Mosaic laws).    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'So the apostles and elders met privately to discuss the matter further. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "After a lengthy debate, Peter rose to his feet and said to them,
        \u201CBrothers, you know how God has chosen me [[COMMENT(0)]] from the beginning
        to preach the wonderful news of the gospel to the non-Jewish nations. "
      comments:
      - number: 15:7
        content: "  The wording of the Aramaic text is different, stating, \u201CGod
          chose the gentiles from the beginning to hear the manifestation of the
          gospel from my mouth and to believe.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'God, who knows the hearts of every person, confirmed this when he
        gave them the Holy Spirit, just like he has given the Spirit to us. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 15:8
        content: '  This is in reference to the events of  .    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'So now, not one thing separates us as Jews and gentiles, for when
        they believe he makes their hearts pure. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "So why on earth would you now limit God\u2019s grace  [[COMMENT(0)]]
        by placing a yoke of religious duties on the shoulders of the believers that
        neither we nor our ancestors have been able to bear? "
      comments:
      - number: 15:10
        content: "  The text is \u201Ctesting [provoking] God\u201D; e.g., by limiting
          his grace among the gentiles.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Don\u2019t you believe that we are introduced to eternal life through
        the grace of our Lord Jesus\u2014the same grace that has brought these people
        new life?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: Everyone became silent and listened carefully as Paul and Barnabas
        shared with the council at length about the signs and wonders and miracles
        God had worked through them while ministering to the non-Jewish people.
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "When they had finished, Jacob took the floor and said, \u201CLadies
        and gentlemen, listen. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Peter has explained thoroughly that God has determined to win a people
        for himself from among the non-Jewish nations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "And the prophet\u2019s words are fulfilled:"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u2018After these things I will return to youand raise up the tabernacle
        of Davidthat has fallen into ruin.I will restore and rebuild what David experienced"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "so that all of humanity will be able to encounter the Lordincluding
        the gentiles whom I have calledto be my very own,\u2019 says the Lord."
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u2018For I have made known my works from eternity!\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 15:18
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic. This prophecy (vv.  ) is found
          in  .    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CSo, in my judgment, we should not add any unnecessary burden
        upon the non-Jewish converts who are turning to God. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'We will go to them as apostles [[COMMENT(0)]] and teach them to be
        set free from offering sacrifices to idols, sexual immorality, and eating
        anything strangled or with any blood.   '
      comments:
      - number: 15:20
        content: "  Or \u201CWe will be apostles [sent ones] to them.\u201D As translated
          from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cto send a message\u201D (letter).     
          See  .    "
    - name: "21: The Apostles\u2019 Letter to the Non-Jewish People"
      title: "The Apostles\u2019 Letter to the Non-Jewish People"
      number: 21
      content: "For many generations these words of Moses have been proclaimed every
        Sabbath day in the synagogues.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'The apostles and elders and the church of Jerusalem chose delegates
        to go to Antioch in Syria. They chose Judas, called Barsabbas, and Silas,
        both leaders in the church, to accompany Paul and Barnabas. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "They sent with them this letter:\u201CGreetings from the apostles
        and pastors, and from your fellow believers\u2014to our non-Jewish brothers
        and sisters living in Antioch in Syria and the nearby regions. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 15:23
        content: "  Or \u201CCilicia,\u201D which is the southwestern region of coastal
          Turkey that borders Syria.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CWe are aware that some have come to you from the church of
        Jerusalem. These men were not sent by us, but came with false teachings that
        have brought confusion and division, telling you to keep the law and be circumcised\u2014things
        we never commanded them to teach. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 15:24
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic and implied in the Greek. The
          Greek does not make explicit the false teaching, but says simply, \u201CThey
          have upset and unsettled you.\u201D    "
    - name: '25-27: '
      title: 
      number: 25-27
      content: "So after deliberation, we\u2019re sending you our beloved brothers
        Paul and Barnabas, who have risked their lives [[COMMENT(0)]] for the glory
        of the name of our Lord Jesus, the Anointed One. They are accompanied by
        Judas and Silas, whom we have unanimously chosen to send as our representatives
        to you. They will validate all that we\u2019re wanting to share with you. "
      comments:
      - number: "15:25\u201327"
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthey have devoted their souls.\u201D     
          Significant changes in the order of the clauses in these three verses have
          been made for the sake of clarity of the English narrative.    "
    - name: '25-27: '
      title: 
      number: 25-27
      content: "So after deliberation, we\u2019re sending you our beloved brothers
        Paul and Barnabas, who have risked their lives [[COMMENT(0)]] for the glory
        of the name of our Lord Jesus, the Anointed One. They are accompanied by
        Judas and Silas, whom we have unanimously chosen to send as our representatives
        to you. They will validate all that we\u2019re wanting to share with you. "
      comments:
      - number: "15:25\u201327"
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthey have devoted their souls.\u201D     
          Significant changes in the order of the clauses in these three verses have
          been made for the sake of clarity of the English narrative.    "
    - name: '25-27: '
      title: 
      number: 25-27
      content: "So after deliberation, we\u2019re sending you our beloved brothers
        Paul and Barnabas, who have risked their lives [[COMMENT(0)]] for the glory
        of the name of our Lord Jesus, the Anointed One. They are accompanied by
        Judas and Silas, whom we have unanimously chosen to send as our representatives
        to you. They will validate all that we\u2019re wanting to share with you. "
      comments:
      - number: "15:25\u201327"
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthey have devoted their souls.\u201D     
          Significant changes in the order of the clauses in these three verses have
          been made for the sake of clarity of the English narrative.    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CFor it pleases the Holy Spirit and us [[COMMENT(0)]] that we
        not place any unnecessary burden on you, except for the following restrictions: "
      comments:
      - number: 15:28
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Holy Spirit and we have determined\u201D (decided).    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Stay away from anything sacrificed to a pagan idol, from eating what
        is strangled or with any blood, and from any form of sexual immorality. You
        will be beautiful believers [[COMMENT(0)]] if you keep your souls from these
        things, and you will be true and faithful to our Lord Jesus. May God bless
        you!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 15:29
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'They sent the four men off for Antioch, and after gathering the regional
        church together, they delivered the letter. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'When the people heard the letter read out loud, they were overjoyed
        and delighted by its encouraging message. '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'Then Judas and Silas, who were both prophets, spoke to them affirming
        words [[COMMENT(0)]] that strengthened the believers. '
      comments:
      - number: 15:32
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Can abundant word\u201D or \u201Ca rich word.\u201D     
          The ministry of the New Testament prophet is to strengthen the church.    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'After the four men spent some time there, the church sent them off
        in peace to return to the apostles in Jerusalem. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 15:33
        content: "  Or \u201Csent them with peace back to those who sent them.\u201D    "
    - name: '34-35: Paul and Barnabas Disagree'
      title: Paul and Barnabas Disagree
      number: 34-35
      content: However, only Judas departed; [[COMMENT(0)]] Paul, Barnabas, and Silas
        stayed in Antioch, where they and many others preached and taught the wonderful
        message of the word of God.
      comments:
      - number: "15:34\u201335"
        content: '  The most reliable Greek manuscripts do not mention Silas remaining
          in Antioch. However, many manuscripts include this information, such as
          the Aramaic, codices D and C, the Harklean Syriac Version of AD 616, the
          Sahidic Version of the second to third centuries, and the St. Ephraim of
          Syria version of the fourth century. Regardless, v.    indicates that Silas
          did remain behind. An argument could be made that copyists inserted the
          data in v.    to explain the presence of Silas from v.  .    '
    - name: '34-35: Paul and Barnabas Disagree'
      title: Paul and Barnabas Disagree
      number: 34-35
      content: However, only Judas departed; [[COMMENT(0)]] Paul, Barnabas, and Silas
        stayed in Antioch, where they and many others preached and taught the wonderful
        message of the word of God.
      comments:
      - number: "15:34\u201335"
        content: '  The most reliable Greek manuscripts do not mention Silas remaining
          in Antioch. However, many manuscripts include this information, such as
          the Aramaic, codices D and C, the Harklean Syriac Version of AD 616, the
          Sahidic Version of the second to third centuries, and the St. Ephraim of
          Syria version of the fourth century. Regardless, v.    indicates that Silas
          did remain behind. An argument could be made that copyists inserted the
          data in v.    to explain the presence of Silas from v.  .    '
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "After some days, Paul said to Barnabas, \u201CLet\u2019s travel to
        the regions where we\u2019ve preached the word of God and see how the believers
        are getting along.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'Barnabas wished to take Mark (also known as John) along with them, '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "but Paul disagreed. He didn\u2019t think it was proper to take the
        one who had deserted them in south-central Turkey, [[COMMENT(0)]] leaving
        them to do their missionary work without him. "
      comments:
      - number: 15:38
        content: "  Or \u201CPamphylia.\u201D    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'It became a heated argument between them, a disagreement so sharp
        that they parted from each other. Barnabas took Mark and sailed to Cyprus. '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "And Paul chose Silas [[COMMENT(0)]] as his partner.After the believers
        prayed for them, asking for the Lord\u2019s favor on their ministry, they
        left "
      comments:
      - number: 15:40
        content: '  The apostle Silas was acknowledged in church history as one of
          the seventy apostles whom Jesus sent out. See  . After his missionary journey
          with Paul, he remained in Corinth and ministered there until his death.    '
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: for Syria and southeast Turkey. [[COMMENT(0)]] Every place they went,
        they left the church stronger and more encouraged than before.
      comments:
      - number: 15:41
        content: "  Or \u201CCilicia.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Timothy Joins Paul and Silas'
      title: Timothy Joins Paul and Silas
      number: 1
      content: 'Paul and Silas came to the city of Derbe and then went on to Lystra,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] the hometown of a believer named Timothy. His mother was a
        Jewish follower of Jesus, but his father was not a Jew.   '
      comments:
      - number: 16:1
        content: "  Lystra is modern-day Klistra, a city in Turkey. Derbe, also in
          Turkey, was about sixty miles from Klistra (Lystra).      The Aramaic is
          \u201Chis father was a Syrian\u201D (an Aramaic speaker). In the time of
          Paul\u2019s missionary journeys, the Aramaic language was commonly spoken
          in the region he traveled throughout in the Middle East. The Greek is \u201Chis
          father was a Greek.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Timothy was well known and highly respected among all the believers
        of Lystra and Iconium. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Paul recognized God\u2019s favor on Timothy\u2019s life and wanted
        him to accompany them in ministry, but Paul had Timothy circumcised first
        because of the significant Jewish community living in the region, and everyone
        knew that Timothy\u2019s father wasn\u2019t a Jew."
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'They went out together as missionaries, traveling to different cities
        where they preached and informed the churches of the decrees of the apostolic
        council of Jerusalem for the non-Jewish converts to observe. '
      comments: []
    - name: "5: Paul\u2019s Vision of the Man from Macedonia"
      title: "Paul\u2019s Vision of the Man from Macedonia"
      number: 5
      content: All the churches were growing daily and were encouraged and strengthened
        in their faith.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The Holy Spirit had forbidden Paul and his partners to preach the
        word in the southwestern provinces of Turkey, [[COMMENT(0)]] so they ministered
        throughout the region of central and west-central Turkey.   '
      comments:
      - number: 16:6
        content: "  Or \u201CAsia.\u201D This does not refer to the continent of
          Asia as we know it today, but to the far western and southwestern provinces
          of Asia Minor (Turkey).      Or \u201CPhrygia\u201D and \u201CGalatia.\u201D
          The modern-day capital of Turkey, Ankara, is situated in the area known
          as Galatia.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'When they got as far west as the borders of Mysia, they repeatedly
        attempted to go north into the province of Bithynia, [[COMMENT(0)]] but again
        the Spirit of Jesus would not allow them to enter.   '
      comments:
      - number: 16:7
        content: "  Both Mysia and Bithynia are northwestern regions of Turkey.     
          We do not know how the Holy Spirit kept them from going into Bithynia,
          but it could have been through a warning given by means of a dream or vision.
          In any case, it is obvious the Holy Spirit was guiding his missionaries.
          He is the Lord of the harvest who prepares, imparts gifts, anoints, and
          sends out his servants to gather the nations to Jesus Christ. The book
          of Acts is best understood as the book of Activities of the Holy Spirit.
          Here he is designated \u201Cthe Spirit of Jesus.\u201D True and lasting
          fruit in ministry comes through the work and leading of the Spirit of Jesus.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: So instead they went right on through the province of Mysia to the
        seaport of Troas.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "While staying there Paul experienced a supernatural, ecstatic vision
        during the night. A man from Macedonia appeared before him, pleading with
        him, \u201CYou must come across the sea to Macedonia and help us!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: Paul Arrives at Philippi'
      title: Paul Arrives at Philippi
      number: 10
      content: After Paul had this vision, we [[COMMENT(0)]] immediately prepared
        to cross over to Macedonia, convinced that God himself was calling us to
        go and preach the wonderful news of the gospel to them.
      comments:
      - number: 16:10
        content: "  Apparently, Luke now joins the missionary team going to Macedonia
          (which includes parts of modern-day Bulgaria and former Yugoslavia). This
          is the first instance in Acts of the gospel going to Europe. Luke likely
          left the group later, as he is not included in the team starting in v. 
          . Portions of Acts appear to be Luke\u2019s missionary travel journal.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'From Troas we sailed a straight course to the island of Samothrace,
        and the next day to Neapolis. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Finally we reached Philippi, a major city [[COMMENT(0)]] in the Roman
        colony of Macedonia, and we remained there for a number of days. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:12
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe capital city.\u201D      The Aramaic
          can be translated \u201CIn a matter of days we were well known in the city.\u201D
          Other versions of the Aramaic read \u201CWe were there over certain holy
          days.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'When the Sabbath day came, we went outside the gates of the city
        to the nearby river, for there appeared to be a house of prayer and worship
        there. [[COMMENT(0)]] Sitting on the riverbank we struck up a conversation
        with some of the women who had gathered there. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:13
        content: "  Although implied in the Greek text, it is made explicit in the
          Aramaic, \u201CWe saw it was a house [place] of prayer.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "One of them was Lydia, a businesswoman from the city of Thyatira
        who was a dealer of exquisite purple cloth [[COMMENT(0)]] and a Jewish convert.
        While Paul shared the good news with her, God opened her heart to receive
        Paul\u2019s message.   "
      comments:
      - number: 16:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cpurple dye,\u201D a rare commodity that would only be
          purchased by the wealthy.      Or \u201Cfeared [worshiped] God.\u201D The
          implication is that Lydia was a gentile convert to Judaism.    "
    - name: '15: The Python Spirit'
      title: The Python Spirit
      number: 15
      content: "She devoted herself to the Lord, and we baptized her and her entire
        family. Afterward she urged us to stay in her home, saying, \u201CSince I
        am now a believer in the Lord, come and stay in my house.\u201D So we were
        persuaded to stay there."
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: One day, as we were going to the house of prayer, we encountered a
        young slave girl who had an evil spirit of divination, the spirit of Python.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] She had earned great profits for her owners by being a fortune-teller.
      comments:
      - number: 16:16
        content: "  In the religious context of Greek mythology, she was an \u201Coracle,\u201D
          a medium who had the spirit of the gods speaking through her to foretell
          the future. The Python spirit was the epithet of Apollo, known as the Greek
          god of prophecy. An individual (often a young virgin) who became the oracle
          of Apollo was known as the Python, or Pythia.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "She kept following us, shouting, \u201CThese men are servants of
        the Great High God, and they\u2019re telling us how to be saved!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Day after day she continued to do this, until Paul, greatly annoyed,
        turned and said to the spirit indwelling her, \u201CI command you in the
        name of Jesus, the Anointed One, to come out of her, now!\u201D At that very
        moment, the spirit came out of her!"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: When her owners realized that their potential of making profit had
        vanished, they forcefully seized Paul and Silas and dragged them off to the
        city square to face the authorities.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When they appeared before the Roman soldiers and magistrates, the
        slave owners leveled accusations against them, saying, \u201CThese Jews are
        troublemakers. They\u2019re throwing our city into confusion. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "They\u2019re pushing their Jewish religion down our throats. It\u2019s
        wrong and unlawful for them to promote these Jewish ways, for we are Romans
        living in a Roman colony.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: Miracles Can Come Out of Painful Places'
      title: Miracles Can Come Out of Painful Places
      number: 22
      content: A great crowd gathered, and all the people joined in to come against
        them. The Roman officials ordered that Paul and Silas be stripped of their
        garments and beaten with rods on their bare backs.
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'After they were severely beaten, they were thrown into prison and
        the jailer was commanded to guard them securely. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: So the jailer placed them in the innermost cell of the prison and
        had their feet bound and chained. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 16:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cplaced in stocks.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: Paul and Silas, undaunted, prayed in the middle of the night and sang
        songs of praise to God, while all the other prisoners listened to their worship.
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: Suddenly, a great earthquake shook the foundations of the prison.
        All at once every prison door flung open and the chains of all the prisoners
        came loose.
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Startled, the jailer awoke and saw every cell door standing open.
        Assuming that all the prisoners had escaped, he drew his sword and was about
        to kill himself '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "when Paul shouted in the darkness, \u201CStop! Don\u2019t hurt yourself.
        We\u2019re all still here.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'The jailer called for a light. When he saw that they were still in
        their cells, he rushed in and fell trembling at their feet. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "Then he led Paul and Silas outside and asked, \u201CWhat must I do
        to be saved?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "They answered, \u201CBelieve in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved\u2014you
        and all your family.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 16:31
        content: "  The implication is \u201Cyou and anyone in your household who
          believes.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'Then they prophesied the word of the Lord [[COMMENT(0)]] over him
        and all his family. '
      comments:
      - number: 16:32
        content: "  Or \u201Cspoke the word of the Lord.\u201D This phrase is consistently
          used in the Old Testament for prophetic utterance of a supernatural origin.    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Even though the hour was late, he washed their wounds. Then he and
        all his family were baptized. He took Paul and Silas into his home and set
        them at his table and fed them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: The jailer and all his family were filled with joy in their newfound
        faith in God.
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "At daybreak, the magistrates sent officers to the prison with orders
        to tell the jailer, \u201CLet those two men go.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "The jailer informed Paul and Silas, \u201CThe magistrates have sent
        orders to release you. So you\u2019re free to go now.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "But Paul told the officers, \u201CLook, they had us beaten in public,
        without a fair trial\u2014and we are Roman citizens. [[COMMENT(0)]] Do you
        think we\u2019re just going to quietly walk away after they threw us in prison
        and violated all of our rights? Absolutely not! You go back and tell the
        magistrates that they need to come down here themselves and escort us out!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 16:37
        content: "  Paul didn\u2019t notify them that he and Silas were Romans prior
          to their beatings, when they could have escaped persecution. Instead, they
          endured the brutal treatment and ended up leading their jailer to Christ.  "
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'When the officers went back and reported what Paul and Silas had
        told them, the magistrates were frightened, especially upon hearing that
        they had beaten two Roman citizens without due process. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "So they went to the prison and apologized to Paul and Silas, begging
        them repeatedly, saying, \u201CPlease leave our city.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "So Paul and Silas left the prison and went back to Lydia\u2019s house,
        where they met with the believers and comforted and encouraged them before
        departing."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Riot Breaks Out in Thessalonica'
      title: A Riot Breaks Out in Thessalonica
      number: 1
      content: 'After passing through the cities of Amphipolis and Apollonia, Paul
        and Silas arrived at Thessalonica. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 17:1
        content: '  Known today as Salonica or Thessaloniki, it was the ancient capital
          of Macedonia.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'As they customarily did, they went to the synagogue to speak to the
        Jews from the Torah scrolls. For three weeks '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Paul challenged them by explaining the truth and proving to them
        the reality of the gospel\u2014that the Messiah had to suffer and die, then
        rise again from among the dead. He made it clear to them, saying, \u201CI
        come to announce to you that Jesus is the Anointed One, the Messiah!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Some of the Jews were convinced that their message was true, so they
        joined Paul and Silas, along with quite a few prominent women and a large
        number of Greeks who worshiped God. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 17:4
        content: '  It is probable that this is when Timothy arrived in Thessalonica
          with gifts of money and food from the church of Philippi. See  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "But many of the Jews were motivated by bitter jealousy and formed
        a large mob out of the troublemakers, unsavory characters, and street gangs
        to incite a riot. They set out to attack Jason\u2019s house, for he had welcomed
        the apostles into his home. [[COMMENT(0)]] The mob was after Paul and Silas
        and sought to take them by force and bring them out to the people. "
      comments:
      - number: 17:5
        content: '  This information is borrowed from v.    and inserted here for
          the sake of English narrative.    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "When they couldn\u2019t find them, they took Jason instead, along
        with some of the brothers in his house church, [[COMMENT(0)]] and dragged
        them before the city council. Along the way they screamed out, \u201CThose
        troublemakers who have turned the world upside down have come here to our
        city. "
      comments:
      - number: 17:6
        content: "  Although not much about Jason is given here, he is known in church
          history as Jason of Tarsus, who was one of the seventy apostles Jesus sent
          out and is named as one of Paul\u2019s ministry companions. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "And now Jason and these men have welcomed them as guests. They\u2019re
        traitors to Caesar, teaching that there is another king named Jesus.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Their angry shouts stirred up the crowds and troubled the city and
        all its officials. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: The Gospel Received in Berea'
      title: The Gospel Received in Berea
      number: 9
      content: So when Paul and Silas came before the leaders of the city, they refused
        to let them go until Jason and his men posted bail.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'That night the believers sent Paul and Silas off to the city of Berea,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] where they once again went into the synagogue. '
      comments:
      - number: 17:10
        content: '  Berea (modern-day Veria) was a city in Macedonia about forty-five
          miles (seventy-five kilometers) from Thessalonica.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'They found that the Jews of Berea were of more noble character and
        much more open minded than those of Thessalonica. They were hungry to learn
        and eagerly received the word. Every day they opened the scrolls of Scripture
        to search and examine them, to verify that what Paul taught them was true. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: A large number of Jews became believers in Jesus, along with quite
        a few influential [[COMMENT(0)]] Greek women and men.
      comments:
      - number: 17:12
        content: "  The Greek word    also implies \u201Cwomen of high standing,\u201D
          \u201Cwealthy,\u201D \u201Chonorable,\u201D \u201Celegant,\u201D and \u201Crespected.\u201D
          (See  , Gr. 2158.)    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'When the news reached the Jews in Thessalonica that Paul was now
        in Berea, preaching the word of God, the troublemakers went there too and
        they agitated and stirred up the crowds against him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: The fellow believers helped Paul slip away to the coast of the Aegean
        Sea, [[COMMENT(0)]] while Silas and Timothy remained in Berea.
      comments:
      - number: 17:14
        content: "  The Greek text is simply \u201Cthe sea.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: The Apostle Paul in Athens'
      title: The Apostle Paul in Athens
      number: 15
      content: Those who accompanied Paul sailed with him as far as Athens. Then
        Paul sent them back to Berea with instructions [[COMMENT(0)]] for Silas and
        Timothy to hurry and join him.
      comments:
      - number: 17:15
        content: '  The Aramaic makes it clear that this message was written as a
          letter.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'While Paul was waiting for them in Athens, his spirit was deeply
        troubled [[COMMENT(0)]] when he realized that the entire city was full of
        idols. '
      comments:
      - number: 17:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cdeeply pained\u201D or \u201Cirritated.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: He argued the claims of the gospel with the Jews in their synagogue,
        and with those who were worshipers of God, and every day he preached in the
        public square to whomever would listen.
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Philosophers of the teachings of Epicurus, [[COMMENT(0)]] and others
        called Stoics,  debated  with Paul. When they heard him speak about Jesus
        and his resurrection, they said, \u201CWhat strange ideas is this babbler
        trying to present?\u201D Others said, \u201CHe\u2019s peddling some kind
        of foreign religion.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 17:18
        content: "  Epicurus was a Greek philosopher (341\u2013270 BC) who espoused
          a radical materialism that claimed people should live for pleasure and
          materialistic gain. He denied an afterlife and asserted that the gods had
          little interest in or concern for humanity.      Stoicism, in contrast
          to Epicureanism, is a passive determinism of emotional indifference that
          elevates the virtue of self-control. By mastering human passions and emotions,
          one could realize peace within himself. The Greek Stoics believed that
          humans can only reach their full potential when they live by sheer reason
          and divine principle, or the spark of divinity, which they called  .     
          The Aramaic is \u201Cword wrestled.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "So they brought him for a public dialogue before the leadership council
        of Athens, [[COMMENT(0)]] known as the Areopagus.\u201CTell us,\u201D they
        said, \u201Cabout this new teaching that you\u2019re bringing to our city. "
      comments:
      - number: 17:19
        content: "  The Areopagus was a governing body of intellectuals who were
          the overseers of Athens. It was equivalent to the board of education, the
          city council, the ethics committee, the council of foreign relations, and
          leaders of the religious and philosophical community all rolled into one.
          The Areopagus, also known as Mars Hill (Mars, or Ares, was the Greek god
          of war), was not simply a location but a gathering of a council of people
          overseeing the spiritual atmosphere of Athens. It could best be described
          as the Greek temple of human thought. The Aramaic here uses the phrase
          \u201Chouse of religion.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "You\u2019re presenting strange and astonishing things to our ears,
        and we want to know what it all means.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: Paul Speaks to the Leaders of Athens'
      title: Paul Speaks to the Leaders of Athens
      number: 21
      content: Now, it was the favorite pastime of the Athenians and visitors to
        Athens to discuss the newest ideas and philosophies.
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "So Paul stood in the middle of the leadership council and said, \u201CRespected
        leaders of Athens, [[COMMENT(0)]] it is clear to me how extravagant you are
        in your worship of idols.   "
      comments:
      - number: 17:22
        content: "  Or simply, \u201CAthenians.\u201D      As translated from the
          Aramaic, which can also be translated \u201CYou excel in the worship of
          demons\u201D (or \u201Cidols\u201D). The Greek is \u201CHow very superstitious
          you are (i.e., extraordinarily religious).\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "For as I walked through your city, I was captivated by the many shrines
        and objects of your worship. I even found an inscription on one altar that
        read, \u2018To the Unknown God.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]] I have come to introduce
        to you this God whom you worship without even knowing anything about him."
      comments:
      - number: 17:23
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CTo the Hidden God.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CThe true God is the Creator of all things. He is the owner
        and Lord of the heavenly realm and the earthly realm, and he doesn\u2019t
        live in man-made temples. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "He supplies life and breath and all things to every living being.
        He doesn\u2019t lack a thing that we mortals could supply for him, for he
        has all things and everything he needs. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'From one man, Adam, he made every man and woman and every race of
        humanity, and he spread us over all the earth. He sets the boundaries of
        people and nations, determining their appointed times in history. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 17:26
        content: "  The Aramaic adds an interesting nuance: \u201CHe commands the
          separation of the seasons and sets the lifespan of every person.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "He has done this so that every person would long for God, feel their
        way to him, [[COMMENT(0)]] and find him\u2014for he is the God who is easy
        to discover!   "
      comments:
      - number: 17:27
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cinvestigating him in his creation.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cthe God who is not far from each one of us.\u201D    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "It is through him that we live and function and have our identity;
        just as your own poets have said, [[COMMENT(0)]] \u2018Our lineage comes
        from him.\u2019 "
      comments:
      - number: 17:28
        content: "  Paul is quoting two classical Greek writers (ca. 270 BC): Aratus
          (, 5) and Cleanthes (, 5).      Or \u201COur nature comes from him,\u201D
          as translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CWe are his offspring.\u201D
          The Greek word is  , which means \u201Ckindred\u201D or \u201Cfamily\u201D
          (taken from his genes).    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CSince our lineage can be traced back to God, how could we even
        think that the divine image could be compared to something made of gold,
        silver, or stone, sculpted by man\u2019s artwork and clever imagination?"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "\u201CIn the past God tolerated [[COMMENT(0)]] our ignorance of these
        things, but now the time of deception has passed away.  He commands us all
        to repent and turn to God.   "
      comments:
      - number: 17:30
        content: "  Or \u201Cdeliberately paid no attention to.\u201D      As translated
          from the Aramaic.      That is, to turn away from idolatry and worship
          the true God.    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "For the appointed day has risen, in which he is going to judge the
        world in righteousness by the man he has designated. And the proof given
        to the world that God has chosen this man is this: he resurrected him from
        among the dead!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 17:31
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CGod turns the hearts of men to faith in
          him [Jesus] and raises them from among the dead.\u201D    "
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "The moment they heard Paul bring up the topic of resurrection, some
        of them ridiculed him, then got up and left. But others said, \u201CWe want
        to hear you again later about these things.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'So Paul left the meeting. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'But there were some who believed the message and joined him from
        that day forward. Among them were Dionysius, a judge on the leadership council,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and a woman named Damaris. '
      comments:
      - number: 17:34
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. According to the church historian
          Eusebius, Dionysius later became the Bishop of Athens (Eusebius,    III:
          iv).      The Greek word can also mean \u201Cwife,\u201D indicating she
          was possibly the wife of Dionysius. Regardless, she must have been a woman
          of high social standing to be included in the meeting of the leadership
          council.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Apostle Paul in Corinth'
      title: The Apostle Paul in Corinth
      number: 1
      content: 'When Paul left Athens he traveled to Corinth, [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 18:1
        content: '  Corinth is about forty-eight miles (seventy-eight kilometers)
          from Athens. It was a large commercial center with trade links all over
          the entire ancient world. It was the home of the famous Isthmian Games
          and the temple of Aphrodite, which held a thousand temple prostitutes.
          Corinth was known for its debauchery. In the midst of a depraved culture,
          God birthed a church to become light to the people of their city.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'where he met a Jewish man named Aquila, who was originally from northeastern
        Turkey. [[COMMENT(0)]] He and his wife, Priscilla, had recently emigrated
        from Italy to Corinth because Emperor Claudius had expelled all the Jews
        from Rome. '
      comments:
      - number: 18:2
        content: "  Or \u201CPontus,\u201D a Roman province in northeastern Asia
          Minor (Turkey).    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Since Paul and Aquila were both tentmakers [[COMMENT(0)]] by trade,
        Paul moved in with them and they became business partners.
      comments:
      - number: 18:3
        content: "  The Aramaic can also mean \u201Csaddle makers.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: Every Sabbath day Paul spoke openly in the synagogue, to both Jews
        and non-Jews, [[COMMENT(0)]] attempting to persuade them to believe the message
        of Jesus.
      comments:
      - number: 18:4
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cpagans.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: When Silas and Timothy finally arrived from Macedonia, Paul spent
        all his time preaching the word of God, [[COMMENT(0)]] trying to convince
        the Jews that Jesus was the Messiah.
      comments:
      - number: 18:5
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe manifestation of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "When they viciously slandered him and hurled abuse on him, he symbolically
        shook the dust off his clothes in protest against them. He said to them,
        \u201CHave it your way then! I am guiltless as to your fate, for the blood-guilt
        of your actions will be on your own heads, and from now on I will preach
        to the non-Jews.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Leaving the synagogue, Paul went to the home of Titus, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        a convert to Judaism, for he and his family attended the Jewish meetings  
        and they had all become believers in Jesus. '
      comments:
      - number: 18:7
        content: "  The Greek text is \u201CTitus Justus,\u201D but the Aramaic only
          has Titus. It is possible that he is the Titus who accompanied Paul in
          ministry and the one Paul addressed in the book of Titus.      As translated
          from the Aramaic. The Greek says that Titus Justus lived next door to the
          synagogue.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: Crispus, [[COMMENT(0)]] the leader of the synagogue, believed in the
        Lord, together with his entire family, and many of the Corinthians who heard
        what had happened believed in the Lord and were baptized.
      comments:
      - number: 18:8
        content: '  Crispus was one of the few people Paul baptized. See  . According
          to church tradition he became the bishop of Aegina.    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "One night, the Lord spoke to Paul in a supernatural vision and said,
        \u201CDon\u2019t ever be afraid. Speak the words that I give you and don\u2019t
        be intimidated, "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "because I am with you. [[COMMENT(0)]] No one will be able to hurt
        you, for there are many in this city whom I call my own.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 18:10
        content: "  Somewhat more explicit in the Aramaic, this is the great \u201CI
          AM\u201D who is speaking with Paul, assuring him of God\u2019s presence.    "
    - name: '11: Paul Brought before the Roman Official Gallio'
      title: Paul Brought before the Roman Official Gallio
      number: 11
      content: For the next year and a half, Paul stayed in Corinth, faithfully teaching
        the word of God.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Now, at that time, Gallio was the regional governor who ruled over
        the Roman province of Achaia, [[COMMENT(0)]] and the Jews turned against
        Paul and came together to seize him and bring him publicly before the governor\u2019s
        court.   "
      comments:
      - number: 18:12
        content: "  The province of Achaia included the three most important parts
          of southern Greece: Attica, Boeotia, and the Peloponnesus. Gallio was the
          brother of Seneca, the tutor of Nero.      Or \u201Cjudgment seat.\u201D
          This was a raised platform with a marble bench where judicial and governmental
          decrees were issued. This bench has been discovered after excavations in
          the agora.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "They accused him before Gallio, saying, \u201CThis man is creating
        a disturbance by persuading people to worship God in ways that are contrary
        to our laws.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Just as Paul was about to speak in his defense, Gallio interrupted
        and said, \u201CWait! If this involved some major crime or fraud, it would
        be my responsibility to hear the case. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "But this is nothing more than a disagreement among yourselves over
        semantics [[COMMENT(0)]] and personalities  and traditions of your own Jewish
        laws.  Go and settle it yourselves! I refuse to be the judge of these issues.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 18:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cdoctrines.\u201D      Or \u201Cnames.\u201D      The
          Aramaic is \u201CTorah\u201D (the first five books of Moses).    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: So Gallio dismissed them from the court.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: Priscilla and Aquila'
      title: Priscilla and Aquila
      number: 17
      content: Immediately the crowd turned on Sosthenes, [[COMMENT(0)]] one of the
        leaders  of the synagogue who sided with Paul. They seized him and beat him
        up right there in the courtroom! But Gallio showed no concern at all over
        what was happening.
      comments:
      - number: 18:17
        content: "  Sosthenes means \u201Csavior of our nation.\u201D See  .     
          The Aramaic word used here can mean \u201Cpriest\u201D or \u201Celder.\u201D
          Crispus is mentioned as the president or leader (v.  ). Some speculate
          that Crispus\u2019 term of service had been completed and Sosthenes took
          his place.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: After remaining in Corinth several more days, Paul finally bid shalom 
        [[COMMENT(0)]] to the believers and sailed away for the coast of Syria, accompanied
        by Priscilla and Aquila.  Before they left, Paul had his head shaved at Cenchrea, 
        because he had taken a vow of dedication.
      comments:
      - number: 18:18
        content: "    is the Hebrew and Aramaic word for \u201Cpeace and well-being.\u201D
          The Greek is \u201Cfarewell.\u201D The Aramaic can also be translated \u201CPaul
          brought peace to the brothers.\u201D      Priscilla means \u201CAncient\u201D;
          Aquila means \u201CEagle.\u201D      Cenchrea was one of two major ports
          of Corinth, possibly where agricultural goods were exported, for Cenchrea
          means \u201Cmillet,\u201D a grain similar to quinoa.    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'When they reached Ephesus, [[COMMENT(0)]] Paul left Priscilla and
        Aquila behind, then he went into the synagogue and spoke to the Jews. '
      comments:
      - number: 18:19
        content: "  Ephesus was in the ancient world, a white marble city, one of
          the most beautiful in the world. It had the temple of Artemis, one of the
          seven great wonders of that era. It also had two agoras, a beautiful fountain
          in the city supplied by an aqueduct, the monument of Phillio, the Koressian
          Gates, the Bouleuterion, a large stadium, and many terraced houses. It
          was the capital city of the Roman province of Asia and had a population
          of well over one hundred thousand at the time Paul visited the city. Ephesus
          was known historically as the center of powerful magical practices and
          the casting of spells, as well as the cult center of the worship of the
          Ephesian goddess Artemis, known as \u201Cthe supreme power.\u201D It was
          in this backdrop that the apostle Paul and his companions planted the renowned
          church of Ephesus.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'They asked him to stay longer, but he refused '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "and said farewell to them, adding, \u201CI will come back to you,
        if it is God\u2019s will, after I go to Jerusalem to observe the feast.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]] Then he set sail from Ephesus for Caesarea."
      comments:
      - number: 18:21
        content: '  This last clause is only found in the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'When he arrived there he traveled on to Jerusalem to visit the church
        and pray for them, [[COMMENT(0)]] then he left for Antioch. '
      comments:
      - number: 18:22
        content: "  Although this clause is missing in the Greek, the Aramaic can
          be translated \u201Cto pray for the peace of the congregation.\u201D A
          true spiritual father prays for believers and brings them a message of
          hope and peace.    "
    - name: '23: The Ministry of Apollos'
      title: The Ministry of Apollos
      number: 23
      content: After spending some time there, Paul continued on through the region
        of Galatia and Phyrgia in central Turkey. And wherever he went he encouraged
        and strengthened the believers. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 18:23
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CWherever he went he made
          them all disciples.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'A Jewish man by the name of Apollos arrived in Ephesus. He was a
        native of Alexandria [[COMMENT(0)]] and was recognized as an educated and
        cultured man. He was powerful in the Scriptures, '
      comments:
      - number: 18:24
        content: '  This is Alexandria in Egypt.    '
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'had accepted Jesus, and had been taught about the Lord. He was spiritually
        passionate [[COMMENT(0)]] for Jesus and a convincing teacher, although he
        only knew about the baptism of John. '
      comments:
      - number: 18:25
        content: "  Or \u201CHis spirit boiled.\u201D    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "He fearlessly preached [[COMMENT(0)]] in the synagogue. But when
        Priscilla and Aquila heard Apollos\u2019 teachings, they met with him privately 
        and revealed to him the ways of God more completely. "
      comments:
      - number: 18:26
        content: "  That is, boldly and powerfully. The Aramaic can be translated
          \u201Cwith crystal clarity.\u201D      The Aramaic is \u201Cthey took him
          into their home.\u201D      Or \u201Cmore accurately.\u201D They filled
          in the gaps in his understanding of the Lord Jesus.    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Then Apollos, with the encouragement of the believers, went to the
        province of Achaia. [[COMMENT(0)]] He took a letter of recommendation from
        the brothers of Ephesus so his ministry would be welcomed in the region.
        He was a tremendous help to the believers and caused them to increase in
        grace.   '
      comments:
      - number: 18:27
        content: "  See the first footnote on v.  .      As translated from the Aramaic.
          The Greek is \u201CHe helped those who believed by grace.\u201D  "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: Apollos boldly and publicly confronted the Jews, vigorously debating
        them, proving undeniably from the Scriptures that Jesus was the Messiah.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Apostle Paul in Ephesus'
      title: The Apostle Paul in Ephesus
      number: 1
      content: 'While Apollos was ministering in Corinth, Paul traveled on through
        the regions of Turkey  [[COMMENT(0)]] until he arrived in Ephesus, where
        he found a group of twelve followers of Jesus.   '
      comments:
      - number: 19:1
        content: "  The Greek is \u201Cthe upper inland country.\u201D This was a
          trek through certain regions of Turkey for him to arrive in Ephesus.     
          Or \u201Csome disciples.\u201D Verse    states there were twelve. This
          information is included here in v.    for the sake of the English narrative.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "The first thing he asked them was \u201CDid you receive the Holy
        Spirit when you became believers?\u201D\u201CNo,\u201D they replied. \u201CWe\u2019ve
        not even heard of a holy spirit.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Paul asked, \u201CThen what was the meaning of your baptism?\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]They responded, \u201CIt meant that we would follow John\u2019s
        teaching.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 19:3
        content: "  Or \u201Cinto what [name or authority] were you baptized?\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Paul said, \u201CJohn\u2019s baptism was for those who were turning
        from their sins, [[COMMENT(0)]] and he taught you to believe in and follow
        the one who was coming after him: Jesus the Anointed One.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 19:4
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CJohn\u2019s baptism was a
          baptism of grace to the people.\u201D      \u201CThe Anointed One\u201D
          (or \u201CMessiah\u201D) is found only in the Aramaic. The Greek is simply
          \u201CJesus.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'When they understood this, they were baptized into the authority
        of Jesus, the Anointed One. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 19:5
        content: "  Or \u201Con the name of Jesus Christ,\u201D which means they
          were baptized into the authority of the name of Jesus, who was greater
          than John.    "
    - name: '6-7: '
      title: 
      number: 6-7
      content: 'And when Paul laid his hands on each of the twelve, the Holy Spirit
        manifested and they immediately spoke in tongues [[COMMENT(0)]] and prophesied. '
      comments:
      - number: "19:6\u20137"
        content: "  Or \u201Csupernaturally given languages.\u201D      The Aramaic
          is \u201CThey spoke tongue by tongue and gushed out prophecies.\u201D The
          impartation of the Holy Spirit and his gifts are here being transferred
          from Paul to these believers. See also  ;  . Jesus taught that when the
          Holy Spirit comes upon us, it is to impart power for our lives and ministries.
          See  .    "
    - name: '6-7: '
      title: 
      number: 6-7
      content: 'And when Paul laid his hands on each of the twelve, the Holy Spirit
        manifested and they immediately spoke in tongues [[COMMENT(0)]] and prophesied. '
      comments:
      - number: "19:6\u20137"
        content: "  Or \u201Csupernaturally given languages.\u201D      The Aramaic
          is \u201CThey spoke tongue by tongue and gushed out prophecies.\u201D The
          impartation of the Holy Spirit and his gifts are here being transferred
          from Paul to these believers. See also  ;  . Jesus taught that when the
          Holy Spirit comes upon us, it is to impart power for our lives and ministries.
          See  .    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "For three months Paul taught openly and fearlessly in the synagogue,
        arguing persuasively for them to enter into God\u2019s kingdom realm. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 19:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cabout God\u2019s kingdom realm.\u201D It is a big step
          for both Jews and Christians to come out of their religious identity and
          focus on the reality of God\u2019s kingdom realm.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: But some of them hardened their hearts and stubbornly refused to believe.
        When they spoke evil [[COMMENT(0)]] of the Way in front of the congregation,
        Paul withdrew from them and took the believers with him.
      comments:
      - number: 19:9
        content: "  Or \u201Ccursed the Christian way of living.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: Extraordinary Miracles in Ephesus'
      title: Extraordinary Miracles in Ephesus
      number: 10
      content: 'Every day [[COMMENT(0)]] for over two years,  he taught them in the
        lecture hall of Tyrannus,  which resulted in everyone living in the province
        of Asia,  Jews and non-Jews, hearing the prophetic word of the Lord. '
      comments:
      - number: 19:10
        content: "  The Greek manuscript D adds, \u201Cfrom the fifth hour [11:00
          a.m.] to the tenth hour [4:00 p.m.].\u201D      Counting the three months
          of focusing on ministry to the Jews, Paul\u2019s entire stay in Ephesus
          came to three years, which would have included a short visit to Corinth.
          See  .      This was like a college or lecture hall. Tyrannus (whose name
          means \u201Csovereign\u201D) was most likely a philosopher and lecturer
          who had disciples whom he taught. Apparently Tyrannus welcomed Paul after
          he left the Jewish congregation and brought him into his school to teach
          the students.      This \u201Cschool of ministry\u201D exploded as many
          came to hear Paul and then went out to preach, expanding the reach of the
          gospel into all the \u201Cprovince of Asia\u201D (Asia Minor). The province
          of Asia would have covered no less than one-third of Turkey. Many multitudes
          heard the gospel in the two-year period when Paul taught in Ephesus. The
          teaching of the apostles resulted in the expansion of God\u2019s kingdom
          realm.      Or simply, \u201Cthe word of the Lord.\u201D However, the phrase
          \u201Cthe word of the Lord\u201D is a Hebrew expression consistently used
          for the prophetic utterances given by the prophets.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'God kept releasing a flow of extraordinary miracles through the hands
        of Paul. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Because of this, people took Paul\u2019s handkerchiefs and articles
        of clothing, even pieces of cloth that had touched his skin, laying them
        on the bodies of the sick, and diseases and demons left them and they were
        healed."
      comments: []
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "Now, there were seven itinerant Jewish exorcists, sons of Sceva the
        high priest, who took it upon themselves to use the name and authority of
        Jesus over those who were demonized. They would say, \u201CWe cast you out
        in the name of the Jesus that Paul preaches!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "Now, there were seven itinerant Jewish exorcists, sons of Sceva the
        high priest, who took it upon themselves to use the name and authority of
        Jesus over those who were demonized. They would say, \u201CWe cast you out
        in the name of the Jesus that Paul preaches!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "One day, when they said those words, the demon in the man replied,
        \u201CI know about Jesus, and I recognize Paul, but who do you think you
        are?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: Revival Breaks Out'
      title: Revival Breaks Out
      number: 16
      content: Then the demonized man jumped on them and threw them to the ground,
        beating them mercilessly. [[COMMENT(0)]] He overpowered the seven exorcists
        until they all ran out of the house naked and badly bruised.
      comments:
      - number: 19:16
        content: '  True authority comes from relationship with Jesus Christ, not
          just using formulas and techniques. Evil spirits know about the depth of
          our relationship with God.    '
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'All of the people in Ephesus were awestruck, both Jews and non-Jews,
        when they heard about what had happened. Great fear fell over the entire
        city, and the authority of the name of Jesus was exalted. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Many believers publicly confessed their sins and disclosed their
        secrets. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Large numbers of those who had been practicing magic took all of
        their books and scrolls of spells and incantations and publicly burned them.
        When the value of all the books and scrolls was calculated, it all came to
        several million dollars. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 19:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cfifty thousand silver drachmas.\u201D Some historians
          have said that one lamb would be sold for one silver drachma. The price
          of a ewe lamb today is about 150 USD. A drachma was one day\u2019s wage,
          and fifty thousand drachmas would be one hundred years\u2019 wages. The
          value of the books could have been millions of dollars.    "
    - name: '20: A Riot Breaks Out'
      title: A Riot Breaks Out
      number: 20
      content: The power of God caused the word to spread, and the people were greatly
        impacted. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 19:20
        content: '  Chronologically, this would have been the time when Paul wrote
          his first letter to the Corinthians.    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Paul had it in his heart to go to Jerusalem and, on his way there,
        to revisit the places in Greece where he had ministered. [[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CAfter
        that,\u201D he said, \u201CI have to go to Rome also.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 19:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cto go through Macedonia and Achaia.\u201D The implication
          is that Paul wanted to revisit the area of Greece he had ministered in;
          therefore, that is made explicit in this translation.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'So he sent ahead into Macedonia two of his ministry assistants, Timothy
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and Erastus,  while he remained in western Turkey. '
      comments:
      - number: 19:22
        content: "  Timothy\u2019s name means \u201Cone who honors God.\u201D He
          was Paul\u2019s spiritual son and later became an apostolic church planter.
          See    and  .      Erastus means \u201Cbeloved.\u201D He was possibly the
          treasurer of the city of Corinth. See  ;  .      Or \u201Cthe province
          of Asia\u201D (Minor).    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "At that time a major disturbance erupted in Ephesus over the people
        following God\u2019s way. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 19:23
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is simply \u201Cthe
          way.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: It began with a wealthy man named Demetrius, who had built a large
        business and enriched many craftsmen by manufacturing silver shrines for
        the Greek goddess Artemis. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 19:24
        content: '  Also known as Diana. She was venerated as the daughter of Zeus
          and the sister of Apollo.    '
    - name: '25-26: '
      title: 
      number: 25-26
      content: "Demetrius called a meeting of his employees, along with all the various
        tradespeople of Ephesus, and said, \u201CYou know that our prosperous livelihood
        is being threatened by this Paul, who is persuading crowds of people to turn
        away from our gods. [[COMMENT(0)]] We make a good living by doing what we
        do, but everywhere Paul goes, not only here in Ephesus but throughout western
        Turkey,  he convinces people that there\u2019s no such thing as a god made
        with hands. "
      comments:
      - number: "19:25\u201326"
        content: "  The true worship of God threatens not only the political realm,
          but the spiritual and economic realm as well. Jesus compels men to adopt
          new values.      Or \u201Cthe [Roman] province of Asia [Minor].\u201D    "
    - name: '25-26: '
      title: 
      number: 25-26
      content: "Demetrius called a meeting of his employees, along with all the various
        tradespeople of Ephesus, and said, \u201CYou know that our prosperous livelihood
        is being threatened by this Paul, who is persuading crowds of people to turn
        away from our gods. [[COMMENT(0)]] We make a good living by doing what we
        do, but everywhere Paul goes, not only here in Ephesus but throughout western
        Turkey,  he convinces people that there\u2019s no such thing as a god made
        with hands. "
      comments:
      - number: "19:25\u201326"
        content: "  The true worship of God threatens not only the political realm,
          but the spiritual and economic realm as well. Jesus compels men to adopt
          new values.      Or \u201Cthe [Roman] province of Asia [Minor].\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Our businesses are in danger of being discredited. And not only that,
        but the temple of our great goddess Artemis is being dishonored and seen
        as worthless. [[COMMENT(0)]] She is the goddess of all of western Turkey
        and is worshiped in all the world. But if this outrage continues, everyone
        everywhere will suffer the loss of her magnificent greatness.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 19:27
        content: '  The temple of Artemis (Diana) is one of the seven ancient wonders
          of the world. We must never put buildings or temples above the true worship
          of God. The Ephesians valued their goddess and economic standards more
          than truth.    '
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "When the people heard this, they were filled with boiling rage. They
        shouted over and over, \u201CArtemis, the great goddess of the Ephesians!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "The entire city was thrown into chaos as everyone rushed into the
        stadium together, [[COMMENT(0)]] dragging with them Gaius  and Aristarchus, 
        Paul\u2019s traveling companions from Macedonia."
      comments:
      - number: 19:29
        content: "  The stadium of Ephesus has recently been discovered and is estimated
          to have held twenty-four thousand spectators.      Gaius\u2019 name is
          a variant form of \u201Clord.\u201D There is speculation that he could
          be the man to whom the apostle John wrote his third letter (3&nbsp;John).     
          Aristarchus\u2019 name means \u201Cbest ruler.\u201D He was a native of
          Thessalonica (;  ). He traveled often with Paul and is also mentioned in   
          and  , called there Paul\u2019s \u201Cfellow prisoner.\u201D Church tradition
          states that he was martyred by Emperor Nero for loving and serving Jesus
          Christ.    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "When Paul attempted to go in and speak to the massive crowd, the
        disciples wouldn\u2019t let him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Some of the high-ranking governmental officials of the region, because
        they loved him, [[COMMENT(0)]] sent Paul an urgent message, saying, \u201CWhatever
        you do, don\u2019t step foot into that stadium!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 19:31
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: The frenzied crowd shouted out one thing, and others shouted something
        else, until they were all in mass confusion, with many not even knowing why
        they were there!
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Some of the Jews pushed forward a Jewish man named Alexander to be
        their spokesman, and different factions of the crowd shouted instructions
        at him. He stood before the people and motioned for everyone to be quiet
        so he could be heard. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "But when he began to speak, they realized that he was a Jew, so they
        shouted him down. For nearly two hours they shouted over and over, \u201CGreat
        is Artemis, the goddess of the Ephesians!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 19:34
        content: "  Artemis, the great goddess of the Ephesians, has faded from history,
          while we fill stadiums today for conferences and revivals and say, \u201CGreat
          is the God Most High!\u201D    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "Eventually the mayor of the city [[COMMENT(0)]] was able to quiet
        them down. He said, \u201CFellow citizens! Who in the world doesn\u2019t
        know that we are devoted to the great temple  of Artemis and to her image
        that fell from Zeus out of heaven?   "
      comments:
      - number: 19:35
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe city governor.\u201D The Greek is \u201Ccity
          clerk\u201D or \u201Cscribe\u201D (or \u201Ckeeper of the records\u201D).
          For all practical purposes he would be or represent the mayor of the city.     
          As translated from the Aramaic, the Greek is \u201Ccustodians of the temple.\u201D     
          The Aramaic is \u201Cher face that fell from heaven.\u201D Much conjecture
          has been made over this statement. Some of the oldest translations have
          \u201Cfell from Zeus [Jupiter],\u201D while most modern translations have
          \u201Cfell from the sky [heaven].\u201D Some believe it was an aerolite
          that was fashioned into a stature of Artemis; however, Pliny the Elder,
          a Roman author and philosopher who died trying to save relatives from the
          eruption of Mount Vesuvius, says it was made from wood, possibly ebony
          (  16.79.213\u201314).  "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Since no one can deny it, you should all just be quiet. Calm down
        and don\u2019t do anything hasty. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "For you have brought these men before us who aren\u2019t guilty of
        any crime. They are neither temple robbers nor blasphemers of our goddess. "
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'So if Demetrius and the men of his trade have a case against someone,
        the courts are open. They can appear before the judge and press charges. '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "But if you\u2019re looking for anything further to bring up, it must
        be argued before the court and settled there, not here. "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "Don\u2019t you realize we\u2019re putting our city in danger of being
        accused of a riot by the Roman authorities? There\u2019s no good explanation
        we can give them for all this commotion!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: After he had said this, he dispersed the crowds and sent them away.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Apostle Paul Goes to Macedonia and Greece'
      title: The Apostle Paul Goes to Macedonia and Greece
      number: 1
      content: 'When the uproar finally died down, Paul gathered the believers and
        encouraged their hearts. He kissed them, [[COMMENT(0)]] said good-bye, and
        left for Macedonia. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:1
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'At every place he passed through, he brought words of great comfort
        and encouragement to the believers. Then he went on to Greece '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'and stayed there for three months.Just as Paul was about to sail
        for Syria, he learned of a plot against him by the Jews, so he decided to
        return by going through Macedonia. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Seven men accompanied him as far as western Turkey. They were Sopater,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] son of Pyrrhus  from Berea, Aristarchus  and Secundus  from
        Thessalonica, Gaius  from Derbe, and Timothy,  Tychicus,  and Trophimus 
        from western Turkey. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:4
        content: "  Sopater, or Sosipater, is mentioned in    as one of Paul\u2019s
          relatives. His name means \u201Chis father\u2019s savior.\u201D      Or
          \u201Cson of fiery red flames.\u201D This phrase is not found in the Aramaic.     
          See the third footnote on  .      Secundus means \u201Cfortunate.\u201D     
          Many believe this is the same Gaius mentioned in  . See the second footnote
          on  .      The Aramaic is \u201CTimothy of Lystra.\u201D See introductions
          to 1 and 2&nbsp;Timothy.      It is likely that Tychicus was a native of
          Ephesus since he carried the letter Paul wrote to them as well as the letter
          to Colossae. See  ;  . He is also mentioned in    and  . His name means
          \u201Cchild of fortune.\u201D      Trophimus was not a Jew. He is mentioned
          in  . His name means \u201Cnutritious.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: These men went ahead and were waiting for us at Troas. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 20:5
        content: "  Notice \u201Cus,\u201D which implies Luke has now rejoined the
          missionary team.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'As soon as all of the Passover celebrations were over, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        we sailed from Philippi. After five days we joined the others in Troas, where
        we stayed another week.   '
      comments:
      - number: 20:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Days of Unleavened Bread.\u201D This holiday was
          observed during the week immediately following Passover and was wrapped
          into the Passover celebration.      This is when the events took place
          mentioned by Paul in  .    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'On Sunday we gathered to take communion [[COMMENT(0)]] and to hear
        Paul preach. Because he was planning to leave the next day, he continued
        speaking until past midnight. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:7
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cbreaking pieces of the Eucharist.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'There were many flickering lights [[COMMENT(0)]] in the upstairs
        chamber where we were meeting. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:8
        content: '  It is possible that these flickering lights refer to angelic
          activity in the upper chamber.    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Sitting in an open window listening was a young man named Eutychus.
        [[COMMENT(0)]] As Paul\u2019s sermon dragged on, Eutychus became drowsy and
        fell into a deep slumber. Sound asleep, he fell three stories to his death
        below. "
      comments:
      - number: 20:9
        content: "  Or \u201Ca preteen named Eutychus,\u201D which means \u201Cfortunate\u201D
          or \u201Clucky.\u201D      There is no doubt that \u201CLucky\u201D died
          because of his fall. The Greek word    can only mean that he was lifeless.
          This boy becomes a picture of some believers today who, because they view
          themselves as \u201Cwell off,\u201D sit carelessly where they shouldn\u2019t,
          growing drowsy, falling asleep, and enduring a disastrous fall. But God
          has grace and power to raise even the foolish ones back to life.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Paul went downstairs, bent over the boy, and embraced him. Taking
        him in his arms, he said to all the people gathered, \u201CStop your worrying.
        He\u2019s come back to life!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 20:10
        content: "  Or \u201CHis soul is in him.\u201D Paul raised him from the dead.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Paul went back upstairs, served communion, and ate a meal with them.
        Then he picked back up where he left off and taught until dawn. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 20:11
        content: "  The Aramaic adds \u201Cby land\u201D (on foot).    "
    - name: "12: Paul\u2019s Voyage to Miletus"
      title: "Paul\u2019s Voyage to Miletus"
      number: 12
      content: Filled with enormous joy, they took the boy home alive and everyone
        was encouraged. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 20:12
        content: "  The Greek is \u201Ccomforted,\u201D while the Aramaic is \u201Coverjoyed.\u201D
          This translation merges both concepts.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Continuing our journey, we made our way to the ship and sailed for
        Assos. [[COMMENT(0)]] Paul had previously arranged to meet us there as he
        traveled overland by foot. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:13
        content: "  A coastal city in far western Turkey. Assos means \u201Capproaching.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'So he rejoined our team there and we took him aboard and sailed for
        Mitylene. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 20:14
        content: '  A city on the Greek island of Lesbos.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The next day we crossed over to Chios, [[COMMENT(0)]] and the following
        day we arrived at the island of Samos.  We stayed at Trogyllium,  and on
        the day after that we reached Miletus.   '
      comments:
      - number: 20:15
        content: '  A Greek island in the Aegean Sea off the coast of Turkey.     
          A Greek island in the Aegean Sea off the coast of Turkey.      As translated
          from the Aramaic and some Greek manuscripts. Most Greek manuscripts do
          not have this clause.      An ancient seaport of far western Turkey.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Paul was in a hurry to arrive in Jerusalem, hoping to make it in
        time for the Feast of Pentecost, so he decided to bypass Ephesus and not
        spend any time in that region. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 20:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cwaste any time in the province of Asia [Minor].\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: However, from Miletus Paul had sent a message to the elders of the
        church [[COMMENT(0)]] in Ephesus and asked them to come meet with him.
      comments:
      - number: 20:17
        content: '  These elders would be equivalent to pastors, leaders of the church.    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "When they arrived, he said to them, \u201CAll of you know how I\u2019ve
        lived and conducted myself while I was with you. From the first day I set
        foot in western Turkey "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "I\u2019ve operated in God\u2019s miracle power [[COMMENT(0)]] with
        great humility and served you  with many tears. I\u2019ve endured numerous
        ordeals because of the plots of the Jews. "
      comments:
      - number: 20:19
        content: "  As translated in the Aramaic, which is literally \u201CI\u2019ve
          performed God\u2019s miracles.\u201D The Greek is \u201CI\u2019ve served
          the Lord.\u201D      Some manuscripts add, \u201Cfor more than three years.\u201D
          See also  .    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "You know how I\u2019ve taught you in public meetings and in your
        homes, and that I\u2019ve not held anything back from you that would help
        you grow. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'I urged both Jews and non-Jews to turn from sin to God and to have
        faith in our Lord Jesus. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'And now I am captive to the Holy Spirit [[COMMENT(0)]] to go to Jerusalem,
        without really knowing what will happen to me there. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cshackled by the Holy Spirit.\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Yet I know that the Holy Spirit warns me [[COMMENT(0)]] in town after
        town, saying, \u2018Chains and afflictions are prepared for you.\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 20:23
        content: '  This warning from the Holy Spirit could have come through prophecies,
          dreams, visions, or the voice of the Holy Spirit speaking within him.    '
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CBut whether I live or die is not important, for I don\u2019t
        esteem my life as indispensable. [[COMMENT(0)]] It\u2019s more important
        for me to fulfill my destiny and to finish the ministry my Lord Jesus has
        assigned to me, which is to faithfully preach the wonderful news of God\u2019s
        grace. "
      comments:
      - number: 20:24
        content: "  Or \u201CI do not consider my life worth a single word.\u201D
          That is, Paul viewed his life as not worth mentioning. We don\u2019t need
          to see our lives as precious in our own eyes, for they are precious in
          the eyes of our Lord Jesus, and that must be enough.    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "I\u2019ve been a part of your lives and shared with you many times
        the message of God\u2019s kingdom realm. But now I leave you, and you will
        not see my face again. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'If any of you should be lost, I will not be blamed, for my conscience
        is clean, '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "because I\u2019ve taught you everything I could about God\u2019s
        eternal plan and I\u2019ve held nothing back. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: So guard your hearts. Be true shepherds [[COMMENT(0)]] over all the
        flock and feed them well. Remember, it was the Holy Spirit who appointed
        you to guard and oversee  the churches that belong to Jesus, the Anointed
        One,  which he purchased and established by his own blood.
      comments:
      - number: 20:28
        content: "  Or \u201Cpastors.\u201D      The Greek uses the word    or  .
          This is the sacred duty of his leaders in the church.      As translated
          from some Greek and Aramaic texts. Jesus is implied, for the Aramaic is
          simply \u201Cthe Anointed One.\u201D Some Greek manuscripts and the Western
          Peshitta read \u201Cthe church of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CI know that after I leave, imposters who have no loyalty to
        the flock [[COMMENT(0)]] will come among you like savage wolves. "
      comments:
      - number: 20:29
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cthey won\u2019t
          spare the flock.\u201D    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Even some from among your very own ranks will rise up, twisting the
        truth [[COMMENT(0)]] to seduce people into following them instead of Jesus. '
      comments:
      - number: 20:30
        content: "  Or \u201Cspeaking crooked things.\u201D    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "So be alert and discerning. Remember that for three years, night
        and day, I\u2019ve never stopped warning each of you, pouring out my heart
        to you with tears."
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "\u201CAnd so now, I entrust you into God\u2019s hands and the message
        of his grace, [[COMMENT(0)]] which is all that you need to become strong. 
        All of God\u2019s blessings are imparted through the message of his grace,
        which he provides as the spiritual inheritance given to all of his holy ones. "
      comments:
      - number: 20:32
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe manifestation of grace.\u201D      Or
          \u201Cto build you up,\u201D a Greek word taken from the root word for
          \u201Carchitect.\u201D      Or \u201Csanctified\u201D; that is, those who
          are devoted to holiness.    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "\u201CI haven\u2019t been after your money or any of your possessions.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 20:33
        content: "  Or \u201Csilver, gold, or fine apparel.\u201D    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "You all know that I\u2019ve worked with my hands to meet my own needs
        and the needs of those who\u2019ve served with me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "I\u2019ve left you an example of how you should serve and take care
        of those who are weak. [[COMMENT(0)]] For we must always cherish the words
        of our Lord Jesus, who taught, <JESUS>\u2018Giving brings a far greater blessing
        than receiving.\u2019</JESUS> &nbsp;\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 20:35
        content: "  Or \u201Cminister to the sick.\u201D      The Aramaic is an idiom
          that speaks of extravagant generosity. \u201CBlessed are those who try
          to give more than they\u2019ve been given.\u201D  "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'After Paul finished speaking, he knelt down and prayed with them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'Then they all cried with great weeping as one after another hugged
        Paul and kissed him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "What broke their hearts the most were his words \u201CYou will not
        see my face again.\u201DThen they tearfully accompanied Paul back to the
        ship."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Paul\u2019s Journey to Jerusalem"
      title: "Paul\u2019s Journey to Jerusalem"
      number: 1
      content: 'After we tore ourselves away from them, we put out to sea and sailed
        a direct course for the island of Kos, and on the next day to the island
        of Rhodes, [[COMMENT(0)]] and from there to Patara.   '
      comments:
      - number: 21:1
        content: '  Both Kos and Rhodes are Greek islands in the Aegean Sea.     
          A city on the Mediterranean coast of Turkey.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'There we found a ship that was crossing over to Syria, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        so we went aboard and sailed away. '
      comments:
      - number: 21:2
        content: "  Or \u201CPhoenicia,\u201D a Greek term for coastal Lebanon and
          Syria.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: After we sighted Cyprus and sailed south of it, we docked at Tyre
        [[COMMENT(0)]] in Syria, where the ship unloaded its cargo.
      comments:
      - number: 21:3
        content: '  Tyre was a city in Phoenicia. They would have sailed four or
          five days from Patara to reach Tyre.    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'When we went ashore we found a number of believers and stayed with
        them for a week. They prophesied to Paul repeatedly, warning him by the Holy
        Spirit not to set foot in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "When it was time for us to leave and be on our way, everyone\u2014men,
        women, and children\u2014accompanied us out of the city down to the beach.
        After we all knelt in the sand and prayed together, "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: we kissed one another, [[COMMENT(0)]] said our good-byes, and boarded
        the ship, while the believers went back to their homes.
      comments:
      - number: 21:6
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic idiom \u201Cone to one\u201D (kissed).    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'From Tyre we sailed [[COMMENT(0)]] on to the town of Akko and greeted
        the believers there with peace.  We stayed with them for a day. '
      comments:
      - number: 21:7
        content: "  The text can mean either \u201Ccontinued our journey\u201D or
          \u201Ccompleted our journey.\u201D If they completed their journey by boat
          to Akko, they would have gone by land to Caesarea. Akko, or Ptolemais,
          was named after the Egyptian ruler Ptolemy II Philadelphus in 261 BC ( 
          115;  ). See also  .      As translated from the Aramaic.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Then we went on to Caesarea and stayed for several days [[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the home of Philip the evangelist, who was one of the seven deacons  and '
      comments:
      - number: 21:8
        content: "  This information is supplied from v.  .      See  . An evangelist
          is simply \u201Ca preacher of the good news\u201D or in Aramaic, \u201Ca
          preacher of the hope.\u201D Philip is described as both an evangelist and
          a deacon (servant). Every minister must become a servant.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: the father of four unmarried daughters who prophesied.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'During our stay of several days, Agabus, [[COMMENT(0)]] a prophet
        from Judea, came to visit us. '
      comments:
      - number: 21:10
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "As a prophetic gesture, he took Paul\u2019s belt and tied his own
        hands and feet with it as he prophesied, \u201CThe Holy Spirit says, \u2018The
        one who owns this belt will be tied up in this same way by the Jews and they
        will hand him over to those who are not Jews.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 21:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cgentiles\u201D; i.e., the Romans.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'When we heard this, both we and the believers of Caesarea begged
        Paul not to go on to Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "But Paul replied, \u201CWhy do you cry and break my heart with your
        tears? Don\u2019t you know that I\u2019m prepared not only to be imprisoned
        but to die in Jerusalem for the sake of the wonder of the name of our Lord
        Jesus?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Paul Arrives in Jerusalem'
      title: Paul Arrives in Jerusalem
      number: 14
      content: "Because we couldn\u2019t persuade him, we gave up and said nothing
        more except \u201CMay the will of the Lord be done.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Afterward we packed our bags and set off for Jerusalem, '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: with some of the believers from Caesarea accompanying us. They brought
        us to a village  [[COMMENT(0)]] where they introduced us to Mnason, a Cypriot,
        one of the original disciples,  and he offered us hospitality.
      comments:
      - number: 21:16
        content: "  Implied in the text and found in a few Greek manuscripts.     
          That is, one of the first converts. He may have been one of the original
          converts at Pentecost or one of the first disciples converted by Paul and
          Barnabas.    means \u201Cremembering.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'When we finally arrived in Jerusalem, the believers welcomed us with
        delight. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'The next day Paul and our team had a meeting with Jacob [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and all the elders of the Jerusalem church. '
      comments:
      - number: 21:18
        content: '  That is, Jacob (James) the brother of our Lord Jesus, not the
          apostle Jacob who was martyred.    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: After greeting everyone, Paul explained in detail what God had accomplished
        through his ministry among the non-Jewish people.
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When they heard Paul\u2019s report, they praised God. And they said
        to him, \u201CYou should know, brother, that there are many tens of thousands
        of Jews who have also embraced the faith and are passionately keeping the
        law of Moses. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "But they\u2019ve heard a rumor that you\u2019ve been instructing
        the Jews everywhere to abandon Moses [[COMMENT(0)]] by telling them they
        don\u2019t need to circumcise their children or keep our Jewish customs. "
      comments:
      - number: 21:21
        content: "  Or \u201Capostasy from [the law of] Moses.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "They will certainly hear that you\u2019ve come to Jerusalem. So what
        is the proper way to proceed? "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'We urge you to follow our suggestion. We have four men here who have
        taken a vow and are ready to have their heads shaved. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Now go with them to the temple and sponsor them in their purification
        ceremony, [[COMMENT(0)]] and pay all their required expenses. Then everyone
        will know that the rumors they\u2019ve heard are false. They\u2019ll see
        that you are one who lives according to the law of Moses. "
      comments:
      - number: 21:24
        content: '  This could have been the completion of a Nazarite vow () or a
          reference to the Jewish custom of when a Jew returned from a trip to a
          foreign (pagan) land, he would purify himself of the defilement of being
          with unbelievers (Mishnah    2:3).    '
    - name: '25: Paul Arrested in Jerusalem'
      title: Paul Arrested in Jerusalem
      number: 25
      content: "But in reference to the non-Jewish believers, we\u2019ve sent them
        a letter with our decision, stating that they should avoid eating meat that
        has been offered to an idol, or eating blood or any animal that has been
        strangled, and to avoid sexual immorality.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 21:25
        content: "  It seems strange that Jacob makes no mention of the offering
          that Paul brought for the poor saints in Jerusalem, which was the reason
          for leaving his missionary work to come to Jerusalem. Instead, Jacob wants
          to ensure the purity of Paul\u2019s message. There is at least a hint that
          Paul\u2019s ministry was not always well received in Judea. See  .    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: The next day, Paul took the four men to the temple and ceremonially
        purified himself along with them. He publicly gave notice of the date when
        their vows would end and when sacrifices would be offered for each of them.
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'When the seven-day period [[COMMENT(0)]] was almost over, a number
        of Jews from western Turkey  who had seen him in the temple courts stirred
        up the whole crowd against him. Seizing him, '
      comments:
      - number: 21:27
        content: "  This could also mean \u201Cthe Sabbath.\u201D      Or \u201CAsia
          (Minor).\u201D They were possibly in Jerusalem to celebrate the Feast of
          Pentecost.    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "they shouted, \u201CMen of Israel, help us! This is the man who teaches
        everywhere what is contrary to our nation, our law, and this temple. And
        not only that, but now he brings these non-Jewish men with him into the inner
        courts of our temple! They have made this sacred place ritually unclean.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: (For Trophimus, an Ephesian, had been seen previously with him, and
        they assumed that he entered the inner courts with Paul.)
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'This ignited a huge riot in the city as all the people came together
        to seize Paul and drag him out of the temple courts, closing the gates behind
        him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'But as they were about to kill Paul, the news reached the commander
        of the Roman garrison [[COMMENT(0)]] that the entire city was in an uproar. '
      comments:
      - number: 21:31
        content: '  The Roman commander was in charge of about six hundred soldiers.    '
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'He immediately ran out to the crowd with a large number of his officers
        and soldiers. When the crowd saw them coming, they stopped beating Paul. '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "The commander arrested him and ordered that he be bound with two
        chains. He then asked, \u201CWho is he and what has he done wrong?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'Some in the crowd shouted one thing and others something else, just
        adding to the confusion. Since the commander was unable to get to the truth
        because of the disturbance, he ordered that Paul be brought back to their
        headquarters. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'When they reached the steps leading up to the fortress, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        they had to protect Paul and carry him up because of the violent mob following
        them, '
      comments:
      - number: 21:35
        content: '  This was the Antonia Fortress (or Tower) built by Herod the Great
          in 19 BC.    '
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "and everyone was screaming out, \u201CAway with this man! Kill him!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "As Paul was being led to the entrance of the compound, he said to
        the commander in Greek, \u201CMay I have a word with you?\u201DThe commander
        replied, \u201CSo you know Greek, do you? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 21:37
        content: '  The commander was surprised that Paul could speak some Greek,
          for the people living in Israel at that time did not speak Greek. Paul,
          an educated Jew from Turkey, spoke to the commander in the common language
          of the Roman Empire.    '
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Aren\u2019t you that Egyptian fanatic who started a rebellion some
        time ago and led four thousand assassins [[COMMENT(0)]] out into the wilderness?\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 21:38
        content: '  The Greek word used here is  , a sect of Jewish nationalists
          who were violently hostile to Roman rule. They got their name from the
          small dagger known as a sicarii.    '
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "Paul answered, \u201CI am, in fact, a Jew from Tarsus, in Cilicia,
        a well-known city of southern Turkey where I was born. I beg you, sir, please
        give me a moment to speak to these people.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'When the commander gave his permission, Paul stood on the steps and
        gestured with his hands for the people to listen. When the crowd quieted
        down, Paul addressed them in Aramaic [[COMMENT(0)]] and said:'
      comments:
      - number: 21:40
        content: "  Or \u201CHebrew.\u201D The Hebrew language had been replaced
          with Aramaic during the Babylonian captivity. For more than a thousand
          years the Aramaic language remained the language of the Jewish people.
          Note that Paul did not address the Jewish people in Greek.  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Paul\u2019s Defense"
      title: "Paul\u2019s Defense"
      number: 1
      content: "\u201CLadies and gentlemen, fellow believers and elders [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014please
        listen to me as I offer my defense.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 22:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cfathers\u201D (or \u201Cparents\u201D).      The Aramaic
          is literally \u201CListen to my soul\u2019s outburst.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: (Now, when everyone realized he was speaking to them in their Judean
        Aramaic language, [[COMMENT(0)]] the crowd became all the more attentive.)
      comments:
      - number: 22:2
        content: "  Or \u201CHebrew.\u201D Throughout the Middle East, Assyria, and
          Babylon, Aramaic was the lingua franca, the language of the people of that
          day. Greek and Latin were also spoken but were not as prevalent as Aramaic.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then Paul said, \u201CI am a Jewish man who was born in Tarsus, a
        city of Turkey. [[COMMENT(0)]] However, I grew up in this city and was properly
        trained in the Mosaic law and tutored by Rabbi Gamaliel according to our
        ancestral customs. I\u2019ve been extremely passionate in my desire to please
        God, just as all of you are today. "
      comments:
      - number: 22:3
        content: "  Or \u201CCilicia,\u201D which was known as Asia Minor.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I\u2019ve hunted down and killed the followers of this Way. I have
        seized them and thrown them into prison, both men and women. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: All of this can be verified by the high priest and the Supreme Council
        of Elders. For they even wrote letters to our fellow Jews of Damascus, authorizing
        me to arrest them and bring them back to Jerusalem as prisoners to be punished.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CAs I was on the road approaching Damascus, about noon, a brilliant
        heavenly light suddenly appeared, flashing all around me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "As I fell to the ground I heard a voice say, <JESUS>\u2018Saul, Saul&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.
        why are you persecuting me?\u2019</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CI answered, \u2018Who are you, my Lord?\u2019\u201CHe said
        to me, <JESUS>\u2018I am Jesus, the Victorious.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>I am the one you are persecuting.\u2019</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 22:8
        content: "  Or \u201CJesus the Nazarene.\u201D The word    means \u201Cthe
          branch\u201D or \u201CScion.\u201D The Aramaic word implies the title of
          an heir of a powerful family, or one who is victorious (\u201CJesus, the
          Victorious\u201D). Believers are now grafted-in branches of his family
          tree, victorious ones in Christ.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CThose who were with me saw the brilliant light, but they didn\u2019t
        hear the voice of the one who spoke to me. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 22:9
        content: "  Some Greek manuscripts add \u201Cand they were afraid.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CSo I asked, \u2018Lord, what am I to do?\u2019\u201CAnd the
        Lord said to me, <JESUS>\u2018Get up and go into Damascus, and there you
        will be told about all that you are destined to do.\u2019</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CBecause of the dazzling glory of the light, I couldn\u2019t
        see\u2014I was left blind. So they had to lead me by the hand the rest of
        the way into Damascus."
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CA Jewish man living there named Ananias came to see me. He
        was a godly man who lived according to the law of Moses and was highly esteemed
        by the Jewish community. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "He stood beside me and said, \u2018Saul! My brother, Saul\u2014open
        your eyes and see again!\u2019 At that very instant I opened my eyes and
        I could see! "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Then he said to me, \u2018The God of our ancestors has destined you
        [[COMMENT(0)]] to know his plan and for you to see the Holy One  and to hear
        his voice. "
      comments:
      - number: 22:14
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Craised you up.\u201D      Or \u201Cthe Righteous
          One\u201D or \u201Cthe Just One.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "For you will be his witness [[COMMENT(0)]] to every race of people
        and will share with them everything that you\u2019ve seen and heard. "
      comments:
      - number: 22:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cmartyr.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So now, what are you waiting for? Get up, be baptized, and wash away
        your sins as you call upon his name.\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CThen I returned to Jerusalem. And while I was praying in the
        temple, I entered another realm [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 22:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cfell into a trance.\u201D The Greek word for trance
          (, from which we get the word  ) literally means \u201Cto be taken to another
          place\u201D (state or realm). (See  , Gr. 1611.) He was actually taken
          into another realm as a trance came over him.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "and saw him. He said to me, <JESUS>\u2018Hurry and depart from Jerusalem
        quickly, for the people here will not receive the truths you share about
        me.\u2019</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201C&nbsp;\u2018But Lord,\u2019 I argued, \u2018they all know that
        I\u2019m the one who went into our Jewish meetings to find those who believe
        in you and had them beaten [[COMMENT(0)]] and imprisoned. "
      comments:
      - number: 22:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cbeat with a whip\u201D (flogged).    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When the blood of your witness [[COMMENT(0)]] Stephen was shed, I
        stood nearby in full approval of what was happening. I even guarded the cloaks
        of those who stoned him to death.\u2019"
      comments:
      - number: 22:20
        content: "  Or \u201Cmartyr.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CThen he said to me, <JESUS>\u2018Go at once, for I am sending
        you to preach to the non-Jewish nations.\u2019</JESUS> &nbsp;\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 22:21
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cthe far-away nations.\u201D See also  .    "
    - name: '22: The Roman Commander Interrogates Paul'
      title: The Roman Commander Interrogates Paul
      number: 22
      content: "The crowd listened attentively to Paul up to this point. But when
        they heard this, all at once they erupted with loud shouts, saying, \u201CGet
        rid of this man! Kill him! He doesn\u2019t deserve to live!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'While the crowd was screaming and yelling, removing their outer garments,
        and throwing handfuls of dust in the air in protest, '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: the commander had Paul brought back into the compound. He ordered
        that he be whipped with a lash and interrogated to find out what he said
        that so infuriated the crowd.
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "When the soldiers stretched Paul out with ropes, he said to the captain,
        who was standing nearby, \u201CIs it legal for you to torture a Roman citizen
        like this, without a proper trial?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "When the officer heard this, he immediately went to his commander
        and reported it, saying, \u201CThis man is a Roman citizen. What should we
        do now?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "The commander came to Paul and asked him, \u201CTell me the truth,
        are you a Roman citizen?\u201D\u201CYes I am,\u201D he replied."
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "The commander said, \u201CI had to purchase my citizenship with a
        great sum of money.\u201DPaul replied, \u201CI was born as a citizen!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: All of the soldiers who were about to whip Paul backed away, because
        they were afraid of the consequences for tying up and holding a Roman citizen
        against his will.
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: The next day the commander ordered that the high priest and the supreme
        Jewish council [[COMMENT(0)]] be convened, because he wanted to find out
        exactly why the Jews were accusing Paul. So he had him untied and brought
        out to stand before them all.
      comments:
      - number: 22:30
        content: "  Or \u201CSanhedrin,\u201D a council of seventy of the elders
          of Israel.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Paul before the Supreme Council'
      title: Paul before the Supreme Council
      number: 1
      content: "Paul fixed his eyes on the members of the council and said, \u201CMy
        brothers, up to this day I have lived my life before God with a perfectly
        clear conscience.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 23:1
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CI have been blessed by God in every way
          unto this day\u201D or \u201CI have been guided by God unto this day.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: At that moment, Ananias [[COMMENT(0)]] the high priest ordered those
        standing near Paul to strike him in the mouth.
      comments:
      - number: 23:2
        content: "  It is ironic that one Ananias was God\u2019s instrument to bring
          healing and sight to Paul in Damascus, but here it is a different Ananias.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Paul responded, \u201CGod is going to strike you, you corrupt pretender!
        [[COMMENT(0)]] For you sit there judging me according to the law, yet you
        broke the law when you ordered me to be struck.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 23:3
        content: "  Or \u201Cwhite-washed wall\u201D (or \u201Chypocrite\u201D).
          See  ;  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Those standing near Paul said to him, \u201CDo you dare insult the
        high priest of God?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Paul answered, \u201CI had no idea, brothers, that he was the high
        priest. [[COMMENT(0)]] For the Scriptures say, \u2018Do not curse the ruler
        of your people.\u2019&nbsp;\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 23:5
        content: '  It was common for priests and rabbis to wear common clothes except
          on holy occasions. This could be why Paul did not recognize him as the
          high priest. There was also uncertainty as to who the high priest was,
          as Paul had been away from Jerusalem for years.      See  .    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Just then Paul realized that part of the council were Sadducees,
        who deny the resurrection of the dead, [[COMMENT(0)]] and others were of
        the separated ones. So he shouted, \u201CMy fellow Jews, I am a separated
        one,  and the son of a separated one. That\u2019s why I\u2019m on trial here.
        It\u2019s because of the hope I have that the dead will rise to live again.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 23:6
        content: "  This clause is borrowed from v.    and inserted here for the
          sake of clarity of the English narrative. Of the three major sects of Judaism
          of that day (Pharisees, Essenes, and Sadducees), the Sadducees were a small
          but influential group that philosophically denied the supernatural (including
          the resurrection of the dead, angels, and spirits) and gravitated instead
          toward political control of the people.      Or \u201CPharisee,\u201D which
          means \u201Cseparated one.\u201D They were strict keepers of the law and
          believed in angels and the resurrection.      Or \u201Cthe hope and the
          resurrection from the dead.\u201D This is most likely a hendiadys. The
          Aramaic is \u201CI have faith in the [miracle] of the resurrection from
          the dead.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'When he said this, a heated argument started among them, dividing
        the council between the Sadducees and the separated ones. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Paul knew that the Sadducees teach there is no resurrection and do
        not believe in angels or spirits, but the separated ones believe in them
        all. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "This sparked an even greater uproar among them.Finally, some of the
        separated ones who were religious scholars [[COMMENT(0)]] stood up and protested
        strongly, saying, \u201CWe find nothing wrong with this man. It could be
        that the Spirit  has spoken to him or an angel came to him.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 23:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cscribes\u201D (experts in the law).      The Spirit
          referred to was obviously sent from God (the Holy Spirit).    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: When the shouting match became intense, the commander, fearing they
        would tear Paul to pieces, intervened and ordered his soldiers to go in to
        their meeting and seize him and take him back to their headquarters.
      comments: []
    - name: '11: The Plot to Kill Paul'
      title: The Plot to Kill Paul
      number: 11
      content: "That night our Lord appeared to Paul and stood before him and said,
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>\u201CReceive miracle power.</JESUS>    <JESUS>For
        just as you have spoken for me in Jerusalem, you will also speak for me in
        Rome.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 23:11
        content: "  The Lord Jesus works with his apostolic servants and appeared
          to them throughout church history to encourage and give them direction
          for the expansion of God\u2019s kingdom realm. See also  ;  ;  ;  ;  .     
          As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CHave courage.\u201D     
          The Aramaic is \u201CYou are destined to speak for me in Rome also.\u201D    "
    - name: '12-13: '
      title: 
      number: 12-13
      content: 'The next day, more than forty Jews formed a conspiracy and bound
        themselves under an oath [[COMMENT(0)]] to have no food or water until they
        had killed Paul. '
      comments:
      - number: "23:12\u201313"
        content: "  Or \u201Cwith a curse.\u201D That is, they pronounced a curse
          upon themselves, calling down heaven\u2019s punishment if they did not
          murder Paul. One wonders what happened to them when their plot failed.    "
    - name: '12-13: '
      title: 
      number: 12-13
      content: 'The next day, more than forty Jews formed a conspiracy and bound
        themselves under an oath [[COMMENT(0)]] to have no food or water until they
        had killed Paul. '
      comments:
      - number: "23:12\u201313"
        content: "  Or \u201Cwith a curse.\u201D That is, they pronounced a curse
          upon themselves, calling down heaven\u2019s punishment if they did not
          murder Paul. One wonders what happened to them when their plot failed.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "They went to the high priest and the elders to divulge their plans
        and said to them, \u201CWe have united in a solemn oath not to eat or drink
        until Paul is dead. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "So we urge you to have the commander bring him to you as though you
        were to determine his case with a more thorough inquiry. And we will kill
        him before he even gets here!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When Paul\u2019s nephew, his sister\u2019s son, overheard their plot
        to kill him, he came to the headquarters and informed him of their plans. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Paul called for one of the captains [[COMMENT(0)]] and said, \u201CTake
        this boy  to the commander, for he has something important to report to him.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 23:17
        content: "  Or \u201Ccenturions.\u201D See also v.  .      The Aramaic is
          \u201Cpreteen boy.\u201D The Greek is \u201Cyoung man.\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "The captain took him to the commander and informed him, \u201CPaul
        the prisoner asked me to bring this boy to you because he has something important
        for you to know.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "The commander took him by the arm and led him aside in private and
        asked him, \u201CWhat do you have to tell me?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "He replied, \u201CThe Jews have plotted to kill Paul. Tomorrow they
        will ask you to bring him again to the supreme council under the pretense
        of wanting to question him further. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Don\u2019t believe them, because they have forty men lying in wait
        to ambush Paul. These men have sworn an oath not to eat or drink until they
        have killed him. They\u2019re all waiting for you to agree to their request
        so they can carry out their plot.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "The commander dismissed Paul\u2019s nephew after directing him, \u201CTell
        no one that you\u2019ve reported these things to me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23-24: '
      title: 
      number: 23-24
      content: "Then he summoned two of his captains and said to them, \u201CI want
        you to take Paul by horseback to Caesarea tonight at nine o\u2019clock. Dispatch
        two hundred infantrymen, seventy horsemen, and another two hundred spearmen
        to provide security and deliver him safely to Governor Felix.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23-24: '
      title: 
      number: 23-24
      content: "Then he summoned two of his captains and said to them, \u201CI want
        you to take Paul by horseback to Caesarea tonight at nine o\u2019clock. Dispatch
        two hundred infantrymen, seventy horsemen, and another two hundred spearmen
        to provide security and deliver him safely to Governor Felix.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'He sent with them a letter that read:'
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'From Claudias Lysias, to His Excellency, Governor Felix: [[COMMENT(0)]]Dear
        Governor,'
      comments:
      - number: 23:26
        content: '  This was Antonius Felix, the governor of Caesarea who had jurisdiction
          over Israel and parts of Syria. He was known as a corrupt and cruel tyrant.
          However, he was married to a Jewish woman and was well acquainted with
          Jewish laws and traditions. It was important that Paul, a Roman citizen,
          be tried by Roman authorities.    '
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'I rescued this man, who was seized by the Jews as they were about
        to put him to death. I intervened with my troops because I understand that
        he is a Roman citizen. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'I was determined to learn exactly what charge they were accusing
        him of, so I brought him to stand before the Jewish supreme council. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'I discovered that he was being accused with reference to violating
        controversial issues about their law, but I found no charge against him that
        deserved death or imprisonment. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: When I was informed of an imminent plot to kill him, I sent him to
        you at once, and I have ordered his accusers to also come before you and
        state their charges against him.Sincerely,Claudius Lysias
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'The soldiers carried out their orders and escorted Paul during the
        night until they reached the city of Antipatris. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 23:31
        content: '  This was over halfway from Jerusalem to Caesarea.    '
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: The next day the horsemen continued on with Paul and the rest of the
        soldiers were dismissed to return to their headquarters.
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'Upon their arrival in Caesarea, they presented the letter to the
        governor and brought Paul before him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "After reading the letter, he asked Paul what province he was from.Paul
        answered, \u201CSoutheast Turkey.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 23:34
        content: "  Or \u201CCilicia.\u201D  "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "The governor said, \u201CI will give you a full hearing when your
        accusers arrive here also.\u201D Then he ordered that Paul be kept under
        guard in Herod\u2019s palace."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Paul\u2019s Trial before Felix"
      title: "Paul\u2019s Trial before Felix"
      number: 1
      content: 'Five days later, Ananias the high priest arrived in Caesarea, accompanied
        by some Jewish elders and Tertullus, their prosecuting attorney. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        They were brought before the governor to present formal charges against Paul. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:1
        content: "  Or \u201Can orator\u201D or \u201Ca public speaker.\u201D He
          was a professional advocate representing the high priest and Jewish elders.
          Tertullus means \u201Ctriple-hardened.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'After Paul was summoned, Tertullus accused him, saying, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CYour Excellency Felix, under the shadow of your wise leadership
        [[COMMENT(0)]] we Jews have experienced a long period of peace. Because of
        your wise foresight, many reforms are coming to pass in our nation because
        of you, Most Honorable Felix. We deeply appreciate this and thank you very
        much."
      comments:
      - number: 24:3
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic, \u201Cunder your shade\u201D
          (or \u201Cshadow\u201D) or \u201Ctent.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CSo that I won\u2019t weary you with a lengthy presentation,
        I beg you to hear our brief summary, with your customary graciousness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'For we have found this man to be a contagious plague, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        a seditious man who continually stirs up riots among the Jews all over the
        world. He has become a ringleader of the sect known as the Nazarenes.   '
      comments:
      - number: 24:5
        content: "  As translated literally from the Greek. The Aramaic is \u201CHe
          is an assassin.\u201D      The word    means \u201Cthe branch\u201D or
          \u201CScion.\u201D The Aramaic word implies the title of an heir of a powerful
          family, or one who is victorious (\u201CJesus, the Victorious\u201D). Believers
          are now grafted-in branches of his family tree, victorious ones in Christ
          (Nazarenes). Many modern-day Arabic speakers still use the term    when
          speaking of believers in Jesus.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'He has even attempted to desecrate our temple, which is why we had
        him arrested. We sought to judge him according to our law, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'but Commander Lysias came with great force, snatched him away from
        our hands, and sent him here to you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "He has ordered his accusers to come to you so that you could interrogate
        him and ascertain for yourself that all these charges we are bringing against
        him are true.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 24:8
        content: '  Verse    and parts of vv.    and    are missing in most reliable
          Greek manuscripts. They are a part of the Aramaic text and included here.    '
    - name: "9: Paul\u2019s Defense before Felix"
      title: "Paul\u2019s Defense before Felix"
      number: 9
      content: "All the Jews present joined in the verbal attack, saying, \u201CYes,
        it\u2019s true!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "The governor motioned that it was Paul\u2019s turn to speak, so he
        began to answer the accusations.\u201CBecause I know that you have been a
        judge over this nation for many years, I gladly respond in my defense. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'You can easily verify that about twelve days ago, I went to Jerusalem
        to worship. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'No one found me arguing with anyone or causing trouble among the
        people in the synagogues or in the temple or anywhere in the city. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: They are completely unable to prove these accusations they make against
        me.
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CBut I do confess this to you: I worship the God of our Jewish
        ancestors as a follower of the Way, which they call a sect. For I believe
        everything that is written in the Law and the Prophets. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'And my hope is in God, the same hope that even my accusers have embraced,
        the hope of a resurrection from the dead of both the righteous and the unrighteous. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "That\u2019s why I seek with all my heart to have a clean conscience
        toward God and toward others."
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CAfter being away from Jerusalem for several years, I returned
        to bring to my people gifts for the poor. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 24:17
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CFor many years I brought to my people gifts
          for the poor.\u201D    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "I was in the temple, ritually purified and presenting my offering
        to God, when they seized me. I had no noisy crowd around me, and I wasn\u2019t
        causing trouble or making any kind of disturbance whatsoever. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'It was a group of Jews from western Turkey [[COMMENT(0)]] who were
        being unruly; they are the ones who should be here now to bring their charges
        if they have anything against me. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:19
        content: "  Or \u201CAsia\u201D (Minor).    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Or at least these men standing before you should clearly state what
        crime they found me guilty of when I stood before the Jewish supreme council, '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "unless it\u2019s the one thing I passionately spoke out when I stood
        among them. I am on trial today only because of my belief in the resurrection
        of the dead.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Felix, who was well acquainted with the facts about the Way, concluded
        the hearing with these words: \u201CI will decide your case after Commander
        Lysias arrives.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: Paul Speaks to Felix and Drusilla'
      title: Paul Speaks to Felix and Drusilla
      number: 23
      content: He then ordered the captain to keep Paul in protective custody, but
        to give him a measure of freedom, he allowed any of his friends to visit
        him and help take care of his needs.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Several days later, Felix came back with his wife, Drusilla, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        who was Jewish. They sent for Paul and listened as he shared with them about
        faith in Jesus, the Anointed One. '
      comments:
      - number: 24:24
        content: "  Drusilla was the youngest daughter of Herod Agrippa I and sister
          of Agrippa II. As a Jewess, she was likely the source of Felix\u2019s understanding
          of the Way.    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "As Paul spoke about true righteousness, self-control, and the coming
        judgment, Felix became terrified and said, \u201CLeave me for now. I\u2019ll
        send for you later when it\u2019s more convenient.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 24:25
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CWhen my conscience is clear
          I will call for you.\u201D  "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: He expected to receive a bribe from Paul for his release, so for that
        reason he would send for Paul from time to time to converse with him.
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: Two years later, Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus. Before he
        left office he decided to leave Paul in prison as a political favor to the
        Jews.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Paul Appeals to Caesar'
      title: Paul Appeals to Caesar
      number: 1
      content: 'Three days after Festus assumed his duties in Caesarea, he made the
        journey to Jerusalem. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 25:1
        content: '  This was a journey of about sixty-five miles (over one hundred
          kilometers).    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Religious authorities and prominent leaders among the Jews brought
        formal charges against Paul before Festus. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "They came asking him for a favor\u2014that he would transfer Paul
        from Caesarea to Jerusalem\u2014all the while plotting to ambush and kill
        Paul along the way."
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Festus responded to their request by informing them that he planned
        to return to Caesarea shortly. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "He told them, \u201CYour leaders can come with me to Caesarea. If
        this man has broken any laws, you can bring charges against him there.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'After Festus had stayed in Jerusalem no more than eight to ten days,
        he left for Caesarea. The day after he arrived, he convened the court and
        took his seat on the bench as judge over the proceedings. After he ordered
        Paul brought into the courtroom, '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: the Jewish leaders who came from Jerusalem encircled him and leveled
        against him many serious charges, which they were unable to substantiate.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "In his defense, Paul said by the Holy Spirit, [[COMMENT(0)]] \u201CI
        have done nothing wrong.  I\u2019ve committed no offense against Jewish law,
        or against the temple, or against Caesar.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 25:8
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic.      Or \u201CI have not sinned
          in anything.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Festus, because he wanted to curry favor with the Jews, asked Paul,
        \u201CAre you willing to go with me to Jerusalem and be tried for these charges?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Paul replied, \u201CI am standing here before Caesar\u2019s tribunal.
        This is where I should be tried. As you well know, I have done no harm to
        the Jews. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "If I have committed a crime worthy of death, I won\u2019t seek to
        escape the death penalty. But if none of their charges are true, no one has
        the right to hand me over to them. I appeal to Caesar!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '12: Festus and King Agrippa'
      title: Festus and King Agrippa
      number: 12
      content: "After conferring with the members of his council, Festus replied,
        \u201CSince you have appealed to Caesar, to Caesar you will go!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Several days later, King Agrippa and Bernice [[COMMENT(0)]] arrived
        at Caesarea for a visit with Festus. '
      comments:
      - number: 25:13
        content: '  Bernice, a Jewess, was the sister of King Agrippa and the older
          sister of Drusilla, wife of Felix ().  '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "During their stay of many days, Festus explained Paul\u2019s situation
        to the king to get his opinion on the matter, saying, \u201CThere is a man
        here whom Felix left as a prisoner. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'When I was in Jerusalem, the leading priests and Jewish elders pressed
        charges against him and demanded that I issue a guilty verdict against him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'I explained to them that it is not our Roman custom to condemn any
        man before he has an opportunity to face his accusers and present his defense. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So they returned here with me. I didn\u2019t postpone the trial,
        but convened the court the very next day and ordered the man to be brought
        before me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'I listened to their accusations against him, but they were not what
        I expected to hear, for he had committed no crime. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Rather, their issues centered around disagreements with him over
        their religion, and about a dead man named Jesus, who Paul claimed was alive. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Because I was perplexed about how to proceed, I asked him if he would
        be willing to go to Jerusalem to stand trial on these charges. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "When Paul appealed his case to the emperor for a decision, I ordered
        him to be held in custody until I could send him to Caesar.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '22: Paul before King Agrippa'
      title: Paul before King Agrippa
      number: 22
      content: "King Agrippa said to Festus, \u201CI would like to listen to this
        man myself.\u201D\u201CTomorrow,\u201D he replied, \u201Cyou will have that
        opportunity.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: The next day King Agrippa and Bernice entered the audience hall with
        much pomp and pageantry. Accompanying them were the senior military officers
        and prominent citizens. Festus ordered that Paul be brought before them all.
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then Festus said, \u201CKing Agrippa, and esteemed guests, here is
        the man whom the entire Jewish community, both here and in Jerusalem, has
        asked me to condemn to death. They have screamed and shouted at me, demanding
        that I end his life. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Yet upon investigation I couldn\u2019t find one thing that he has
        done to deserve the death penalty. When he appealed to His Majesty the emperor,
        I determined to send him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'But I have nothing concrete to write to His Majesty, so I have now
        brought him before you all, and especially before you, King Agrippa. After
        this preliminary hearing I should have something to write, '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "for it seems absurd to me to send a prisoner without specifying the
        charges against him.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Paul\u2019s Defense before King Agrippa"
      title: "Paul\u2019s Defense before King Agrippa"
      number: 1
      content: "King Agrippa said to Paul, \u201CYou may now state your case.\u201D
        Paul motioned with his hand for silence, then began his defense. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 26:1
        content: "  An alternate reading of the Aramaic is \u201CThe [Holy] Spirit
          issued from his mouth.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CKing Agrippa, I consider myself highly favored to stand before
        you today and answer the charges made against me by the Jews. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: Because you, more than anyone else, are very familiar with the customs
        and controversies among the Jewish people, I now ask for your patience as
        I state my case. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 26:3
        content: "  An alternate reading of the Aramaic is \u201CI beg you to allow
          the Spirit to flow so that you can hear me.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CAll the Jews know how I have been raised as a young man, living
        among my own people from the beginning and in Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "If my accusers are willing to testify, they must admit that they\u2019ve
        known me all along as a Pharisee, a member of the most strict and orthodox
        sect within Judaism. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 26:5
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CI have lived by the elite knowledge of the
          Pharisees.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "And now, here I am on trial because I believe in the hope [[COMMENT(0)]]
        of God\u2019s promises made to our ancestors. "
      comments:
      - number: 26:6
        content: "  The Aramaic can also be translated \u201Cgood news.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "This is the promise the twelve tribes of our people hope to see fulfilled
        as they sincerely strive to serve God with prayers night and day. [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CSo,
        Your Highness, it is because of this hope that the Jews are accusing me. "
      comments:
      - number: 26:7
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'And how should you judge this matter? [[COMMENT(0)]] Why is it that
        any of you think it unbelievable that God raises the dead? '
      comments:
      - number: 26:8
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'I used to think that I should do all that was in my power to oppose
        the name of Jesus of Nazareth. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "And that\u2019s exactly what I did in Jerusalem, for I not only imprisoned
        many of the holy believers by the authority of the chief priests, I also
        cast my vote against them, sentencing them to death. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: I punished them often in every Jewish meeting hall and attempted to
        force them to blaspheme. I boiled with rage against them, hunting them down
        in distant foreign cities to persecute them.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CFor that purpose I went to Damascus, with the authority granted
        to me by the chief priests. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'While traveling on the road at noon, Your Highness, I saw a light
        brighter than the sun flashing from heaven all around me and those who were
        with me. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "We all fell to the ground, and I heard a voice speaking to me in
        Aramaic, saying, <JESUS>\u2018Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? You
        are only hurting yourself when you resist your calling.\u2019</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 26:14
        content: "  Or \u201CWhy are you hurting yourself by kicking against the
          ox-goads?\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CI asked, \u2018Who are you, Lord?\u2019\u201CAnd the Lord replied,
        <JESUS>\u2018I am Jesus,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>the one you are
        persecuting.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 26:15
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CJesus, the Victorious.\u201D See    and
          footnote.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: '<JESUS>Get up and stand to your feet, for I have appeared to you</JESUS> 
        <JESUS>to reveal your destiny and to commission you</JESUS>  <JESUS>as my
        assistant.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>You will be a witness to what
        you have seen and to the things I will reveal whenever I appear to you.</JESUS>    '
      comments:
      - number: 26:16
        content: "  The Greek word    is also used for John Mark as the \u201Cassistant\u201D
          to Barnabas in  .      As translated from the Aramaic, which is literally
          \u201Ca witness that you have seen me and are going to see me again.\u201D
          The Greek is \u201Cto what shall yet appear before your eyes\u201D or \u201Cto
          the things in which I will appear to you.\u201D Both Greek and Aramaic
          are somewhat combined in the translation of this verse. Jesus promised
          future appearances to Paul.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: '<JESUS>I will rescue you from the persecution of your own people
        and from the hostility of the other nations that I will send you to.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "<JESUS>And you will open their eyes to their true condition, so that
        they may turn from darkness to the Light</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>and
        from the power</JESUS>    <JESUS>of Satan to the power of God. By placing
        their faith in me they will receive the total forgiveness</JESUS>    <JESUS>of
        sins and be made holy,</JESUS>  <JESUS>taking hold of the inheritance that
        I give to my children</JESUS><JESUS>!\u2019</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 26:18
        content: "  See  ;  ,  .      Or \u201Cauthority\u201D or \u201Cdominion.\u201D     
          Or \u201Ccancellation of sins.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CSo you see, King Agrippa, I have not been disobedient to what
        was revealed to me from heaven. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'For it was in Damascus that I first declared the truth. And then
        I went to Jerusalem and throughout our nation, [[COMMENT(0)]] and even to
        other nations, telling people everywhere that they must repent and turn to
        God and demonstrate it with a changed life.   '
      comments:
      - number: 26:20
        content: "  Or \u201CJudea.\u201D      Or \u201Cwith fruits in keeping with
          repentance.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "That\u2019s why the Jews seized me when I was in the temple and tried
        to murder me."
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CBut in spite of all this, I have experienced the supernatural
        help of God up to this very moment. So I\u2019m standing here saying the
        same thing that I\u2019ve shared with everyone, from the least to the greatest.
        For I teach nothing but what "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Moses and the prophets have said was destined to happen: that our
        Messiah had to suffer and die and be the first to rise from the dead, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        to release the bright light of truth both to our people and to the non-Jewish
        nations.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 26:23
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cto inaugurate [or \u2018be the origin of\u2019]
          the resurrection from the dead.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Festus interrupted Paul\u2019s defense, [[COMMENT(0)]] blurting out,
        \u201CYou\u2019re out of your mind! All this great learning of yours is driving
        you crazy.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 26:24
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CAs the Holy Spirit spoke
          through Paul, Festus interrupted.\u201D      Or \u201CSo much Scripture
          has made you senseless!\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Paul replied, \u201CNo, Your Excellency Festus, I am not crazy. I
        speak the words of truth and reason. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 26:25
        content: "  Or \u201Cwords of sober truth.\u201D  "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "King Agrippa, I know I can speak frankly and freely with you, for
        you understand these matters well, and none of these things have escaped
        your notice. After all, it\u2019s not like it was a secret! "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Don\u2019t you believe the prophets, King Agrippa? I know that you
        do.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Agrippa responded, \u201CIn such a short time you are nearly persuading
        me to become a Christian.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Paul replied, \u201CI pray to God that both you and those here listening
        to me would one day become the same as I am, except, of course, without these
        chains.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'The king, the governor, Bernice, and all the others got up. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "As they were leaving the chamber, they commented to one another,
        \u201CThis man has done nothing that deserves death or even imprisonment.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "King Agrippa said to Festus, \u201CIf he hadn\u2019t appealed to
        Caesar, he could have been released.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Paul Sails to Italy'
      title: Paul Sails to Italy
      number: 1
      content: 'When it was decided that we [[COMMENT(0)]] were to sail for Italy,
        Festus handed over Paul and a number of other prisoners to the custody of
        a Roman officer named Julius, a member of the imperial guard. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:1
        content: '  It is likely that Luke rejoined Paul here and sailed with him
          to Rome.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: We went on board a ship from the port of Adramyttium [[COMMENT(0)]]
        that was planning to stop at various ports along the coast of southwestern
        Turkey.  We put out to sea and were accompanied by Aristarchus  from Thessalonica
        in Macedonia.
      comments:
      - number: 27:2
        content: "    (modern-day Edrimit, Turkey) was a seaport in the Roman colony
          of Mysia. Adramyttium means \u201CI will abide in death.\u201D      Or
          \u201Cthe coast of the province of Asia\u201D (Minor).        means \u201Cthe
          best leader.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'The next day we docked at Sidon, [[COMMENT(0)]] and Julius, being
        considerate of Paul, allowed him to disembark and be refreshed by his friends
        living there. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:3
        content: '  A Phoenician city now in modern-day Lebanon.    '
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'From there we put out to sea, but because the winds [[COMMENT(0)]]
        were against us, we sailed under the lee of Cyprus.   '
      comments:
      - number: 27:4
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cthe spirits were against
          us.\u201D      That is, east and north of the island.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'After sailing across the open sea off Cilicia and Pamphylia, we docked
        at the port of Myra in Lycia. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: While we were there, the commanding officer found an Egyptian ship
        from Alexandria that was bound for Italy, and he put us on board.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'We made little headway for several days, and with difficulty we made
        it to Knidus. [[COMMENT(0)]] The strong winds kept us from holding our course,
        so from there we sailed along the lee of Crete,  opposite Cape Salome. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:7
        content: "  Or \u201CCnidus,\u201D an ancient port city on the Gulf of G\xF6kova
          on the coast of Turkey.      The Aramaic is \u201Cwe circled Crete.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Hugging the coast, we struggled on to a place called Fair Havens,
        near the town of Lasea. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'We remained there a long time, until we passed the day of the Jewish
        fast. [[COMMENT(0)]]Paul advised the frightened sailors that they should
        not put out to sea in such dangerous weather,  saying, '
      comments:
      - number: 27:9
        content: '  This was possibly the Day of Atonement, when every Jew fasts.     
          As translated from the Aramaic. This was the season the Romans called 
          , the closed sea, when the Mediterranean was not navigable.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CMen, I can see that our voyage would be disastrous for us and
        bring great loss, not only to our ship and cargo but also to our own lives.
        We should remain here.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:10
        content: '  This was clearly prophetic revelation given to the apostle Paul.    '
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "But the officer in charge was persuaded more by the ship\u2019s helmsman
        and captain [[COMMENT(0)]] than he was by Paul. "
      comments:
      - number: 27:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cship\u2019s owner.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'So the majority decided to put out to sea, since Fair Haven was an
        exposed harbor and not suitable to winter in. They had hoped to somehow reach
        the Cretan port of Phineka, [[COMMENT(0)]] which was a more suitable port
        because it was facing south. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:12
        content: "  Or \u201CPhoenix.\u201D      As translated from the Aramaic.
          The Greek is \u201Clooking toward Lips and Choros.\u201D    was the Greek
          term for the \u201Cwinds from the southwest,\u201D and    the word for
          \u201Cwinds from the northwest.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'When a gentle south breeze began to blow, they assumed they could
        make it, so they pulled up anchor and sailed close to Crete. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "But it wasn\u2019t long before the weather abruptly worsened and
        a storm of hurricane force called the Nor\u2019easter [[COMMENT(0)]] tore
        across the island and blew us out to sea. "
      comments:
      - number: 27:14
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CEuroclydon\u2019s typhoon.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "The sailors weren\u2019t able to turn the ship into the wind, so
        they gave up and let it be driven by the gale winds. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:15
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cwe surrendered to its power.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "As we passed to the lee of a small island called Cauda, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        we were barely able to get the ship\u2019s lifeboat under control, "
      comments:
      - number: 27:16
        content: "  Or \u201CGaudos.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: so the crew hoisted the dinghy aboard. The sailors used ropes and
        cables to undergird the ship, [[COMMENT(0)]] fearing they would run aground
        on the shoals of Syrtis.  They lowered the drag anchor to slow its speed
        and let the ship be driven along.
      comments:
      - number: 27:17
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CThey tied down the lifeboat on the ship,
          lest it fall into the sea.\u201D      This was a shallow region full of
          reefs and sandbars off the coast of Libya between Benghazi and Tripoli.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'The next day, because of being battered severely by the storm, the
        sailors jettisoned the cargo, '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "and by the third day they even threw the ship\u2019s tackle and rigging
        overboard. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: After many days of seeing neither the sun nor the stars, and with
        the violent storm continuing to rage against us, all hope of ever getting
        through it alive was abandoned.
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "After being without food for a long time, Paul stepped before them
        all and said, \u201CMen, you should have obeyed [[COMMENT(0)]] me and avoided
        all of this pain and suffering by not leaving Crete. "
      comments:
      - number: 27:21
        content: "  The Greek word    means \u201Cto obey one who is in authority.\u201D
          Paul was the true captain of the ship and carried the weight of authority.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Now listen to me. Don\u2019t be depressed, for no one will perish\u2014only
        the ship will be lost. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "For God\u2019s angel visited me last night, the angel of my God,
        the God I passionately serve. He came and stood in front of me "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "and said, \u2018Don\u2019t be afraid, Paul. You are destined to stand
        trial before Caesar. And because of God\u2019s favor on you, he has given
        you the lives of everyone who is sailing with you.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'So men, keep up your courage! I know that God will protect you, just
        as he told me he would. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "But we must run aground on some island to be saved.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'On the fourteenth night of being tossed about the Adriatic Sea, about
        midnight, the sailors sensed we were approaching land. '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'So they took soundings and discovered that the water was about 120
        feet deep. [[COMMENT(0)]] After sailing a short distance, they again took
        soundings and found it was only ninety feet deep.   '
      comments:
      - number: 27:28
        content: "  Or \u201Ctwenty fathoms.\u201D      Or \u201Cfifteen fathoms.\u201D    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: Fearing we would be dashed against a rocky coast, they dropped four
        anchors from the stern and waited for morning to come.
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Some sailors pretended to go down to drop anchors from the bow when
        in fact they wanted to lower the lifeboat into the sea and escape, abandoning
        ship. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "Paul said to the Roman officer and his soldiers, \u201CUnless you
        all stay together onboard the ship, you have no chance of surviving.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: At the moment they heard this, the soldiers cut the ropes of the dinghy
        and let it fall away.
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Just before daybreak, Paul urged everyone to eat. He said, \u201CToday
        makes two full weeks that you\u2019ve been in fearful peril and hunger, unable
        to eat a thing. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "Now eat and be nourished. For you\u2019ll all come through this ordeal
        without a scratch.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 27:34
        content: "  Or \u201CNot one hair of your heads will perish.\u201D    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'Then Paul took bread and gave thanks to God [[COMMENT(0)]] in front
        of them, broke it and began to eat. '
      comments:
      - number: 27:35
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cglorified God.\u201D    "
    - name: '36-37: '
      title: 
      number: 36-37
      content: 'There were 276 people who ate until they were filled, and were strengthened
        and encouraged. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: "27:36\u201337"
        content: '  Paul served communion on board the ship and fed every passenger
          and crew member. (Did God multiply the bread?) The language used is vividly
          eucharistic. There is a variation among many Greek manuscripts as to the
          total of those who were fed. Some have as few as sixty-nine or seventy.
          The majority of reliable manuscripts in Greek and Aramaic have 276.    '
    - name: '36-37: '
      title: 
      number: 36-37
      content: 'There were 276 people who ate until they were filled, and were strengthened
        and encouraged. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: "27:36\u201337"
        content: '  Paul served communion on board the ship and fed every passenger
          and crew member. (Did God multiply the bread?) The language used is vividly
          eucharistic. There is a variation among many Greek manuscripts as to the
          total of those who were fed. Some have as few as sixty-nine or seventy.
          The majority of reliable manuscripts in Greek and Aramaic have 276.    '
    - name: '38: Paul Is Shipwrecked'
      title: Paul Is Shipwrecked
      number: 38
      content: After they were satisfied, they threw the grain into the sea to lighten
        the ship.
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "When daylight came, the sailors didn\u2019t recognize the land, but
        they noticed a cove with a sandy beach, so they decided to run the ship ashore. "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'They cut away the anchors, leaving them in the sea, untied the ropes
        holding the rudders, and hoisted the foresail to the breeze to head for the
        beach. '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: But they drifted into the rocky shoals between two depths of the sea,
        causing the ship to flounder still a distance from shore. The bow was stuck
        fast, jammed on the rocks, while the stern was being smashed by the pounding
        of the surf.
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'The soldiers wanted to kill all the prisoners to prevent them from
        escaping. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'But the Roman officer was determined to bring Paul safely through,
        so he foiled their attempts. He commanded the prisoners and crew who could
        swim to jump overboard and swim ashore. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 27:43
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.  '
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: The rest all managed to survive by clinging to planks and broken pieces
        of the ship, so that everyone scrambled to the shore uninjured.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Paul on the Island of Malta'
      title: Paul on the Island of Malta
      number: 1
      content: 'After we had safely reached land, we discovered that the island we
        were on was Malta. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: The people who lived there showed us extraordinary kindness, for they
        welcomed us around the fire they had built because it was cold and rainy.
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "When Paul had gathered an armful of brushwood and was setting it
        on the fire, a venomous snake was driven out by the heat and latched onto
        Paul\u2019s hand with its fangs. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "When the islanders saw the snake dangling from Paul\u2019s hand,
        they said to one another, \u201CNo doubt about it, this guy is a murderer.
        Even though he escaped death at sea, Justice [[COMMENT(0)]] has now caught
        up with him!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 28:4
        content: "  The implication in the Greek text is that they were referring
          to a \u201Cgoddess of justice,\u201D perhaps a local deity.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'But Paul shook the snake off, flung it into the fire, and suffered
        no harm at all. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Everyone watched him, expecting him to swell up or suddenly drop
        dead. After observing him for a long time and seeing that nothing unusual
        happened, they changed their minds and said, \u201CHe must be a god!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'The Roman governor of the island, named Publius, had his estate nearby.
        He graciously welcomed us as his houseguests and showed us hospitality for
        the three days that we stayed with him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'His father lay sick in bed, suffering from fits of high fever and
        dysentery. So Paul went into his room, and after praying, placed his hands
        on him. He was instantly healed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'When the people of the island heard about this miracle, they brought
        all the sick to Paul, and they were also healed. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 28:9
        content: '  Although Paul was technically a prisoner, he was the one setting
          everyone free. No doubt he preached the gospel with signs and wonders,
          leaving the island healed in more ways than one.    '
    - name: '10: Paul Reaches Rome'
      title: Paul Reaches Rome
      number: 10
      content: The islanders honored us greatly, [[COMMENT(0)]] and when we were
        preparing to set sail again, they gave us all the supplies we needed for
        our journey.
      comments:
      - number: 28:10
        content: "  Or \u201CThey honored us with many honors.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "After three months we put out to sea on an Egyptian ship from Alexandria
        that had wintered at the island. The ship had carved on its prow as its emblem
        the \u201CHeavenly Twins.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 28:11
        content: "  These were the twin sons of Zeus, Castor and Pollux. The Aramaic
          is \u201Cflying the flag of Gemini.\u201D This was a widespread cult in
          Egypt in that era.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'When we landed at Syracuse, [[COMMENT(0)]] we stayed there for three
        days. '
      comments:
      - number: 28:12
        content: '  This was the city on the eastern coast of Sicily.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'From there we set sail for the Italian city of Rhegium. The day after
        we landed, a south wind sprang up that enabled us to reach Puteoli [[COMMENT(0)]]
        in two days. '
      comments:
      - number: 28:13
        content: '  This was on the western coast of Italy, with a road leading to
          Rome, about 145 miles to the north.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: There we found some believers, who begged us to stay with them for
        a week. Afterward, we made our way to Rome.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: When the believers were alerted we were coming, they came out to meet
        us at the Forum of Appius while we were still a great distance from Rome.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  Another group met us at the Three Taverns.  When Paul saw
        the believers, his heart was greatly encouraged and he thanked God.
      comments:
      - number: 28:15
        content: '  The Forum of Appius was about forty-three miles away from Rome.     
          Three Taverns was about thirty-three miles from Rome.    '
    - name: '16: Paul Speaks to Prominent Jews of Rome'
      title: Paul Speaks to Prominent Jews of Rome
      number: 16
      content: When we finally entered Rome, Paul was turned over to the authorities
        and was allowed to live where he pleased, with one soldier assigned to guard
        him.
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "After three days Paul called together all the prominent members of
        the Jewish community of Rome. [[COMMENT(0)]] When they had all assembled,
        Paul said to them, \u201CMy fellow Jews, while I was in Jerusalem, I was
        handed over as a prisoner of the Romans for prosecution, even though I had
        done nothing against any of our people or our Jewish customs. "
      comments:
      - number: 28:17
        content: "  Some believe there could have been as many as fifty thousand
          Jews living in Rome at the time of Paul\u2019s visit.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'After hearing my case, the Roman authorities wanted to release me
        since they found nothing that deserved a death sentence. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'When the Jews objected to this, I felt it necessary, with no malice
        against them, [[COMMENT(0)]] to appeal to Caesar. '
      comments:
      - number: 28:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cnot that I had any feud against my own nation.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "This, then, is the reason I\u2019ve asked to speak with you, so that
        I could explain these things. It is only because I believe in the Hope of
        Israel that I am in chains before you.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "They replied, \u201CWe haven\u2019t received any letters from the
        Jews of Judea, nor has anyone come to us with a bad report about you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "But we are anxious to hear you present your views regarding this
        Christian sect we\u2019ve been hearing about, for people everywhere are speaking
        against it.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "So they set a time to meet with Paul. On that day an even greater
        crowd gathered where he was staying. From morning until evening Paul taught
        them, opening up the truths of God\u2019s kingdom. With convincing arguments
        from both the Law and the Prophets, he tried to persuade them about Jesus.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 28:23
        content: "  That is, about the purpose of Jesus\u2019 coming, which would
          include his life, ministry, death for our sins, and glorious resurrection.    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Some were converted, but others refused to believe. They argued back
        and forth, '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "still unable to agree among themselves. They were about to leave
        when Paul made one last statement to them: \u201CThe Holy Spirit stated it
        well when he spoke to your ancestors through the prophet Isaiah: [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 28:25
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CThe Holy Spirit spoke beautifully
          through the mouth of Isaiah the prophet.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u2018I send you to this people to say to them, \u201CYou will keep
        learning, [[COMMENT(0)]] but not understanding. You will keep staring at
        truth but not perceiving it. "
      comments:
      - number: 28:26
        content: "  Or \u201Clistening.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "For your hearts are hard and insensitive to me\u2014you must be hard
        of hearing! For you\u2019ve closed your eyes so that you won\u2019t be troubled
        by the truth, and you\u2019ve covered your ears so that you won\u2019t have
        to listen and be pierced by what I say. For then you would have to respond
        and repent, so that I could heal your hearts.\u201D&nbsp;\u2019"
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CSo listen well. This wonderful salvation given by God is now
        being presented to the non-Jewish nations, and they will believe and receive
        it!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 28:28
        content: "  Verse    is not included in the oldest and most reliable Greek
          manuscript, and it is omitted from almost every modern translation, including
          the Aramaic. Verse  , if included, would read \u201CAfter hearing this,
          the Jews left with a heated argument among themselves.\u201D    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'Paul lived two more years in Rome, in his own rented quarters, welcoming
        all who came to visit. '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "He continued to proclaim to all the truths of God\u2019s kingdom
        realm, teaching them about the Lord Jesus, the Anointed One, speaking triumphantly
        and without any restriction. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 28:31
        content: '  Tradition says that Paul was eventually released from house arrest
          and traveled to Spain. But the inspired account ends here, with Paul ministering
          to all who came to him. This completes the Acts of the Holy Spirit as recorded
          by Luke. Although the book of Acts is finished, the acts of God continue
          to be accomplished through his apostolic company of surrendered lovers.
          Every believer has the same Holy Spirit and can do the works of Jesus on
          the earth today.  '
